as one of the comprehensive telecommunication providers, china unicom provides a variety of telecommunication services, including mobile communication, international and domestic long distances, data, internet and paging services.
china unicom announced that last year, the company's total connection time for outgoing business calls and regular two-way calls through switchboard telephones and ip telephones reached 6.41 billion minutes, 5.9 times more than that of the previous year. its market share rose from 1.3% in 2000 to 7.7%. the total time of international connection for the entire year increased 3.4 times than the year before.
yang xianzu, ceo of china unicom, indicated that this year the company will continue to speed up its development of mobile communication business, ensure a coordinated development of cdma and gsm mobile communication businesses by adopting a differentiation strategy so that the number of the company's mobile phone customers will continue to grow substantially.
china and japan's central banks signed agreement on currency exchange
xinhua news agency, tokyo, march 28 (reporter wang yan) dai xianglong, governor of people's bank of china, signed on the 28th in tokyo an agreement on bilateral currency exchange of renminbi and japanese yen with masaru hayami, governor of bank of japan.
under the agreement, people's bank of china and bank of japan can provide the other party when necessary a currency exchange arrangement with a total amount worth 3 billion us dollars so as to help the other party maintain the stability of its financial market.
the signing of this currency exchange agreement between china and japan indicated a deepening cooperation between the central banks of both china and japan.
the agreement signed between china and japan is the second bilateral currency exchange agreement following the 2-billion-us-dollar agreement signed between people's bank of china and bank of thailand in december, 2001.
from now on, china will also sign currency exchange agreements with south korea and some other countries.
dai xianglong noted that china will actively get involved in the asian financial cooperation and will work with other asian countries and regions and make its due contribution to the regional economy, financial stability and risk prevention.
wu dawei, chinese ambassador to japan, attended the signing ceremony for the currency exchange agreement between people's bank of china and bank of japan.
earthquake victims in afghanistan start to rebuild homeland
xinhua news agency, kabul, march 28 (reporter pan yunzhao) merely three days after the earthquake, the victims in baghlan province in northern afghanistan have already started rebuilding their homeland.
rebecca, a spokeswoman from the un office for the coordination of afghan humanitarian assistance, told xinhua reporters that while a central team formed by the interim afghan government, the un agencies and non-governmental organizations was conducting investigations and assessments on the 28th in the area hit by the earthquake, they found the victims there had already started to rebuild their homeland. some of them had used the relief supplies provided to the victims by the relief agencies.
given this situation, she said, the un relief agencies have already started considering the issue of helping the victims rebuild their homeland.
at present, the relief agencies have a large inventory of relief supplies in the affected region and are distributing them to the victims from the ground and the air.
on the 25th, a strong earthquake shook the area of nahrin and bojiaer in baghlan province of afghanistan, causing serious casualties and leaving tens of thousands of people homeless.
japan to temporarily freeze humanitarian assistance to russia
xinhua news agency, tokyo, march 29 japanese foreign minister yoriko kawaguchi announced on the 29th that japan will temporarily freeze its humanitarian assistance to russia until the japanese side has reformed the international committee in charge of the assistance program.
yoriko kawaguchi noted that apart from maintaining the committee's personnel expenses and a technological cooperation project japan is currently assisting russia with, the japanese government will control the financial aid that is provided to russia through this committee until it has reformed the committee.
this move came as a response to the recent remarks made by the japanese finance minister masajuro shiokawa.
masajuro shiokawa recently suggested to the cabinet members that given the worsening financial situation in japan itself, the cabinet members should ensure that every fund of the government be used effectively.
it is learned that after the disclosure that deputy chief cabinet secretary muneo suzuki imposed improper pressure on ministry of foreign affairs and influenced the application procedures for the russia aid project, the committee was accused by the outside as delinquent and not being transparent enough as to where the funds went.
eu to hold consultations with china on the implementation of temporary safeguard measures over steel imports
xinhua news agency, beijing, march 29 (reporter che yuming) shi guangsheng, minister of foreign trade and economic cooperation, said here today that in response to china's concern over eu's implementation of temporary safeguard measures on some steel imports, eu has made it clear that it will hold consultations with china as soon as possible and will treat china as a developing country and make some special arrangements so as to properly solve this problem.
shi guangsheng answered the reporters' questions today at the national working conference on laws governing foreign trade and economic cooperation.
the current trade war over steel is escalating, he said, and it originated in the united states.
at present, all relevant parties are challenging the us steel 201 case and demanding bilateral consultations. some even propose a resolution through the world trade organization's dispute resolution agency.
on march 27, after eu decided to implement a temporary safeguard measure over 15 types of steel imports from all nations, china made a prompt response. shi guangsheng immediately wrote a letter to lamy, trade member of the eu commission, expressing his deep concerns over the issue and requesting for bilateral consultations with eu.
train-truck collision killing seven in liaoning
xinhua news agency, shenyang, march 30 (reporter wang jun) at 2:13 p.m. on march 29, a train-truck collision took place in the city of jinzhou, liaoning province, killing seven people and seriously injuring three.
according to the safety inspection office of shenyang railroad bureau, in a hurry to cross a railroad intersection between lijiagou and zhoujiadun within the boundary of yi county in the city of jinzhou, a four-wheeled agricultural truck collided with a train enroute from jinzhou to chengde.
at the time, the truck was carrying 14 passengers in violation of traffic regulations in addition to 50 bags of fertilizer and seeds.
before the collision, 4 people jumped from the truck to save their lives and suffered no injury while the rest 10 people were either dead or injured. the railroad fence at the intersection was damaged by the impact, and the train's locomotive was also damaged to some extent.
after the accident, officials from ministry of railroad, shenyang railroad bureau, the city of jinzhou and the local government rushed to the scene to deal with the aftermath.
arab league council held emergent meeting on the day at its headquarters to discuss situation in palestine
permanent representatives at the arab league from 22 arab nations attended the meeting.
moussa said at a press conference held after the meeting that israel's escalation of its military action against palestine clearly demonstrates that israel refuses peace.
what is happening right now is a continuation of israel's military occupation of palestine. the palestinian people will continue to resist against the aggression of israel.
he said: "as long as israel's military occupation of the palestinian territory exists for a day; as long as israel's tanks and its soldiers are on the palestinian territory for a day, the palestinian people will continue their resistance for a day."
xinhua news agency, jerusalem, march 31 (reporters zhong cuihua and nie xiaoyang) on the evening of the 31st, the israeli security cabinet decided to step up the military strikes against the palestinian controlled area and to implement ahead of schedule a series of military actions still being planned.
on the afternoon of the same day, the israeli prime minister sharon called in core ministers for a meeting to discuss the current situation in israel and palestine and how to respond to the ever-increasing bombing attacks from the palestinian side. they decided at the meeting to step up the military attacks against palestine.
as disclosed by people in the political circle here, the security cabinet believes that stepping up the attacks against palestine can weaken the momentum of palestinian terrorist activities, yet it can in no way completely eradicate such type of attacks.
sharon will make a televised speech to the nation at 8:30 p.m. local time on the 31st (1:30 on april 1, beijing time) and explain to the people the government's position on handling the conflict between israel and palestine.
cambodia and vietnam hold joint trade show
xinhua news agency, phnom penh, april 1 (reporter yan ming) a trade show jointly held by cambodia and vietnam opened here on the 1st and displays nearly 200 varieties of commodities.
participating in the show are 50 merchants from cambodia and vietnam with 55 exhibition booths.
exhibits include motorcycles, household appliances, agricultural tools, medications, beverages, foods and garments.
nguyen duy hung, vietnamese ambassador to cambodia, noted at the opening ceremony that there is a great deal of potential in the development of the economic and trade cooperation between vietnam and cambodia, and trade shows can further promote the economic and trade cooperation and exchanges between the two countries.
he said the volume of trade in recent years between the two countries has made pleasing progress, increasing from 169 million us dollars in 2000 to 180 million us dollars in 2001.
it is great for cambodia and vietnam to jointly develop the economic and trade cooperation between them, said cham prasidh, the cambodian minister of commerce, it will not only help promote the economy and trade in both countries, but will also help promote the economic development of asean nations, making it possible for cambodia and vietnam to integrate themselves economically into asean and the world economy at an earlier date.
indonesian badminton experts think taufik's ranking favorable
xinhua news agency, jakarta, april 1 (reporter mai tangyuan) alisangtuo, president of the gutushi badminton club in central java of indonesia, told the antara reporters on the 1st in the capital city of semarang that men's singles player taufik's world ranking is very favorable to retaining indonesian team's thomas cup.
taufik now ranks the 33rd, he said, as a result, he will become the second or third singles player in men's singles. this will be less stressful than being the first singles player.
in the group matches, the victory in the first singles may affect the subsequent matches. it will at least psychologically influence the team players, making them play harder to win.
however, if the indonesian team loses in the first singles, taufik, as the second or third singles player, will have hopes of scoring. the final result will be decided by the two doubles matches.
he thinks that taufik's return to the team has increased the indonesian team's chance of retaining thomas cup because this young member is a player of great potential in the world.
he believes that taufik's comeback brings hope to indonesia of beating all the opponents, including those from china the hosting nation.
it is reported that in a survey conducted on a badminton website, 45% of people think the indonesian team will be able to retain thomas cup, 21% think the chinese team is likely to win the championship, while 17% believe the title will go to the malaysian team.
georgia to withdraw troops from kodori canyon
xinhua news agency, moscow, april 2 news from tbilisi: on the 2nd, representatives from four parties: the un special representative, georgia, abkhazia, and peace-keeping troops from commonwealth of independent states, signed an agreement in tbilisi on georgia's withdrawal of troops from kodori canyon.
according to itar-tass, under the agreement, georgian troops shall withdraw from kodori canyon by april 10. meanwhile, the peace-keeping troops and the un observer shall resume patrolling the area and all parties shall ensure the safety of the local residents.
boden, un secretary general's special representative to georgia, thinks that this agreement is a "good signal" indicating that georgia and abkhazia are willing to solve the conflict on the basis of a mutual compromise.
he said that this document should pave the way for further dialogs.
in 1992, in their demand for independence, local ethnic abkhazian authorities within georgia had an armed conflict with the georgian government.
in october of last year, soon after both sides had another clash in kodori canyon, georgia sent troops to station there.
xinhua news agency, ankara, april 2 (reporter huai chengbo) according to anadolu news agency, on the 2nd, at the plenary session of the turkish parliament and during the discussion over israel's large-scale invasion of the palestinian territory in the west bank, the turkish foreign minister cem made a speech that the madrid process upon which the middle east peace process is based needs a new beginning. therefore, turkey proposes convening a new international conference on the middle east issues.
cem said the united states should take immediate actions so as to end the tremendous sufferings of the palestinian and israeli peoples and their mutual slaughter.
he also emphasized that the united states must treat palestine and israel equally and fulfil its own obligations.
while talking about turkey's position on the middle east issues, he said that since the middle east is of strategic importance to turkey, turkey hopes for the peace and stability in this region.
he also reiterated that turkey supports the resolution on the palestine-israel conflict that un security council has recently passed.
the resolution urges palestine and israel to cease fire and demands that israel withdraw its troops from ramallah and other palestinian territories.
it is also reported that turkey has consulted with the middle east nations egypt, saudi arabia and jordan as well as palestine and israel regarding an international conference on the middle east issues. it has held consultations with the united states, russia and the european union.
in 1990, the international peace conference on the middle east held in madrid, capital of spain, confirmed the "land-for-peace" principle.
under the guidelines of this principle, palestine and israel signed in washington d. c. in 1993 the declaration of principles on palestinians' interim self-rule.
ntt communication infuses blood into an internet company
xinhua news agency, tokyo, april 3 a spokesman for ntt communication corporation, a subsidiary of ntt, said on the 3rd that the company will continue to support the business development of an internet company (verio) headquartered in the united states and will pour in an additional 305 million us dollars.
the spokesman claimed that according to their estimates, verio will need at least 305 million us dollars this year to make up for the losses. however, ntt communication is willing to pay this amount of money and plans to continue its financial support of verio until it turns to profit.
it is reported that verio, located in the state of colorado, is an internet service provider for businesses. its business covers high-speed internet access, e-commerce, private networking and maintenance of web sites, etc.
ntt acquired the company for 5.5 billion us dollars in 2000.
in the past few years, verio has been losing money without making any profit. ntt communication has successively invested a total of 2.16 billion us dollars in the company.
liberian anti-government armed forces approach capital
xinhua news agency, lagos, april 3 news from monrovia: the liberian military announced that the fighting in the past week between the liberian anti-government armed forces and the government forces escalated and by the evening of the 3rd, the fighting has spread close to the government military barracks only 35 kilometers from the key military line of transportation that leads to the capital of monrovia.
the distance is the same as when the anti-government armed forces fought their way for a time in february of this year to klay town in the suburb of the capital.
the town of duodi, where the barracks is located, is the only route to the neighboring countries cote d'ivoire and guinea from the capital monrovia.
this fighting that broke out on the early morning of the 28th of last month occurred at a time when a un investigation team was investigating the liberian government's exchange of diamonds for weapons and imposing sanctions on liberia.
liberians united for reconciliation and democracy (lurd) attempted to further intensify the offensive aimed at overthrowing the taylor government and force president taylor to step down.
a senior officer of the government forces said the reason why lurd armed forces launched the military offensive is mainly because they want to occupy the diamond mining area as they need the money to buy more weapons and support their current difficult financial situation.
lurd anti-government armed forces have been engaged in a war against the liberian president taylor since 2000.
xinhua news agency, un, april 4 (reporter ding baozhong) bertini, un world food program (wfp) executive director, said on the 4th in new york that wfp distributed a total of nearly 1.7 billion us dollars worth of food aid in various parts of the world in 2001 and has become the largest humanitarian aid agency in the world.
while reporting to the un security council about the agency's activities and functions, bertini pointed out on the same day that wfp has lent a hand to the disaster and conflict-afflicted areas in various parts of the world, saved many lives and made contributions to the rebuilding of some countries. this has helped stabilize the situation in the conflict-afflicted regions.
she said, wfp provided 240 million us dollars worth of food aid to afghanistan last year and millions of afghans benefited from it.
bertini called on the donor nations to be generous so that wfp can fulfil its new mission of assistance to afghanistan in 2002.
he went on to say that so far, only a sum of 70 million us dollars has been raised for this program totaling 285 million us dollars.
bertini also called on the un system and member nations to watch over the safety of the un officials on humanitarian missions and bring to justice those criminals who harmed the un officials.
according to statistics, a total of 204 un officials have been killed since 1992, but only 15 criminals have been arrested.
germany presented un with berlin wall pieces
xinhua news agency, beijing, april 5 on the 4th, the german government presented the united nations with three pieces of the berlin wall, a symbol of the cold war between the east and the west.
according to foreign newswire, each of these three pieces of the wall is 3.6 meters high and weighs 2.8 tons, decorated with an image of a man and a woman embracing across the top of the wall.
the three pieces of the wall were shipped to new york last october in commemoration of the reunification of the two germanys in 1990.
due to the closure of the un garden on the bank of new york's east river since september 11, the public were unable to pay their visit.
taking advantage of the occasion, un secretary general annan noted that the end of the east-west division shows "peace is always possible, even in the middle east."
thierse, president of the german parliament, told annan that even before the berlin wall was built, such a wall already existed in the hearts of many people.
the berlin wall has finally become history, and it was not only the germans who have benefited from it.
bill gates duped on april fools' day
xinhua news agency, beijing, april 5 bill gates, the all-famous microsoft chairman, was duped by a canadian radio station the other day and fell a victim to a big prank on april fools' day.
marc-antoine audette and sebastien trudel, employees of a canadian quebec radio station ckmf-fm, got through to bill gates on the phone on april 1 and claimed to be the canadian prime minister chretien. he imitated the prime minister's voice several times and had an intimate conversation with him for as long as 10 minutes.
the topics of the conversation covered the world economy and the shortcomings of "windows" operation system, and bill gates was also invited to visit quebec at an appropriate time.
the radio station aired the recording of the conversation in its entertainment program on the evening of the 2nd, and on the next day re-aired it at the request of its listeners.
marc-antoine audette later said that he did not expect to get through to bill gates so easily, and that it further surprised him that his aide should fail to find or think that it was just a april fools' day "hoax."
upon learning the truth, a microsoft spokesman claimed that the radio station "convinced" microsoft that they were canadian government employees only after forging some documents and warned that although the "joke" was funny, it went a little bit too far.
it is learned that the radio station had also duped other celebrities in the past such as celine dion on april fools' day.
xinhua news agency, ankara, april 5 (reporter huai chengbo) karzai, prime minister of the afghan interim government, demanded again on the 5th in ankara that the multi-national peace keeping troops in afghanistan extend their mission to areas outside the capital of kabul.
karzai told the reporters at the airport after his two-day visit in turkey that afghans outside the capital of kabul all consider the extension of the peace-keeping troops' activities as an assurance of the continued security in afghanistan.
earlier this year, karzai requested that the un extend the mission area of the peace-keeping troops and station them in areas outside the capital of kabul.
such an action, he said, would send out a signal that the international community assumes its obligations toward a country ravaged by war for 23 years.
turkey has agreed on principle to take over from britain the command of the peace-keeping troops in afghanistan.
however, concerned about the safety in areas outside kabul, turkey did not agree to extend the mission area of the peace-keeping troops.
the united states has made it clear that it supports turkey's position.
karzai said on the 5th that turkey's concern over its troops' potential involvement in renewed unrest in other areas of afghanistan is redundant.
however, he also indicated that no matter what decision the peace-keeping nations make, the afghan government will accept it.
another sandstorm to hit northern china and other places
xinhua news agency, beijing, april 6 (reporter dong jun) chinese central meteorological station issued a sandstorm forecast at 6 pm this afternoon, saying that due to a strong cold air, there will be a sanddust weather from this evening till tomorrow in the eastern part of northwest china, most areas of north china and the south central areas of the northeast china plain.
the forecast said the sandstorm will sweep the central and east-by-southeast inner mongolia, the northern shaanxi, shanxi and hebei, and some parts in the west liaoning and jilin provinces. some areas will be hit by strong sandstorms, and float-dust or sandy weather will affect certain regions between the yellow river and the huai river. in most of the above regions, there will also be strong winds ranging from force 5 to 7. the temperature will drop by 6 to 12 degrees celsius with some areas experiencing a temperature decrease of more than 14 degrees celsius.
in beijing, while it was sunny and balmy in the morning, a gusty wind started to blow in the afternoon, driving people who were in the outdoors to their homes.
although chinese central meteorological station issued a forecast last night of strong winds in north china and other places, the refreshing and pleasant weather right after a spring rain still lured many residents to go outing in the morning.
today, hohhot, the capital of inner mongolian autonomous region, was also hit by a gale accompanied by a drop in temperature.
although a north wind was howling, the sky remained clear and blue.
experts said that yesterday, a spring rain fell over a great part of inner mongolian with a rainfall of as much as 33mm in hohhot. it not only greatly eased the drought but also effectively alleviated the onset of the sandstorm.
telecommunication market in china to exceed 1 trillion yuan in 2005
xinhua news agency, shanghai, april 6 (reporter feng yizhen) the officials of the ministry of information industry (mii) attending the china-russia high-level seminar on information and communication here disclosed that by 2005 the value of the entire telecommunication market in china will reach 1.05 trillion yuan, an increase of 2.5 times from 2000.
according to the projections, during the "the tenth five-year plan" period (2001 to 2005), the number of telephone users in china will increase at an average annual rate of about 26%, with 24% in the east, 26% in central china, and 30% in the west.
by 2005, the number of telephone users in china will hit 500 million, about 40% of that of the population.
the section for mobile phone users in china will expand to include ordinary consumers while the service will expand from simple messaging to data exchange, medium and high-speed multi-media and high-speed interactive multi-media operations.
internet will remain the business with the fastest growth in china's telecommunication industry with demands expanding from the narrowband to broadband business, categorized selection evolving into high-speed interaction, and the customer base expanding from large and medium-sized cities to central towns.
during the "tenth five-year plan" period, the average annual growth rate for the number of data and multi-media internet users in china will exceed 70%.
by 2005, the number of internet users in the whole country will reach 200 million.
annan to hold talks with us, russia and eu over situation in middle east
xinhua news agency, madrid, april 7 (reporter liu ruichang) the spanish newspaper abc reported on the 7th that the un secretary general annan will hold a four-side talk on the 10th in madrid, capital of spain, with us secretary of state powell, foreign minister pique of spain, the member state that currently assumes presidency of eu, eu senior representative solana in charge of foreign affairs and security policies, and foreign minister of russia ivanov, to discuss ways to resolve the gravely worsening israel-palestine conflict.
this news was disclosed by annan in an exclusive interview with the newspaper's reporter at the un headquarters in new york.
abc published this exclusive interview on the same day.
while talking about the un's role in mediating the current military clashes between israel and palestine, annan said the un has played a positive role in mediating the conflict. the un security council has successively passed two important resolutions no. 1397 and no. 1402 on resolving the israel-palestine conflict.
when he attends a meeting in madrid on the 10th of this month, he said, he will use the opportunity to meet with senior officials from the united states, the eu and russia to discuss the grave situation in the middle east.
it is reported that on the 8th annan will, together with the spanish prime minister aznar, preside over the opening ceremony of the un second world assembly on aging in madrid; powell will also pay a formal visit to spain next week to renew the agreement of military cooperation between the united states and spain; and ivanov will take a special trip to spain to meet with powell and discuss the issues concerning the bilateral relationship.
computer-related crimes cost us billions of dollars last year
xinhua news agency, washington, april 7 the us 2001 computer crime and security survey published on the 7th shows that the increasingly rampant computer-related crimes last year cost the us corporations and government agencies billions of dollars in losses, a substantial increase over the year of 2000.
everywhere in the united states there are numerous cases of computer systems attacked by viruses, denial-of-service attacks, and various types of security loopholes.
538 computer security practitioners from corporations, government agencies and universities noted that the us corporations and other institutions are all paying high prices every year as a result of computer-related crimes.
although the exact figure of losses has not yet been finally determined, of the institutions surveyed, 35% admitted that they had suffered losses, with a total value of over 3.778 billion us dollars, a substantial increase from nearly 2.656 billion us dollars in 2000.
the report jointly compiled by the computer security institute (csi) and fbi does not provide any assessment of losses suffered by the individual computer users in the nation.
berber language confirmed as algeria's official language
xinhua news agency, algiers, april 8 (reporter xu donghua) on the 8th, at the joint bicameral meeting held here, the algerian parliament reviewed and passed an amendment draft to the constitution proposed by president bouteflika and confirmed the berber language as one of the constitutionally recognized official languages.
the algerian prime minister bin flis pointed out in a speech at the meeting that the passage of the draft means a legal confirmation of the cultural diversity of algeria, which will help strengthen the solidarity among ethnic groups in algeria.
berbers are the native residents in north africa and the berbers currently living in algeria make up about one sixth of the total population of the country.
the constitution after algeria's independence sets arabic as the only official language but it met protests from the berbers.
in april of last year, serious unrest occurred in kabylie, a berber-populated region in eastern algeria.
during the unrest that lasted more than three months, a total of more than 60 people died and over 2,000 were wounded.
the local residents demanded that the berber language be constitutionally recognized as the official language in algeria.
on march 12 of this year, president bouteflika promised in a televised address to the nation to satisfy the berbers' demand through a constitutional amendment.
white house says israeli military withdrawal from two west bank cities only a beginning
xinhua news agency, washington, april 8 the us white house spokesman fleischer made a statement on the evening of the 8th, calling the israeli military withdrawal from tulkarem and qalqilya in the west bank just "a beginning," and that all parties concerned in the middle east should fulfil their own obligations.
fleischer said in this brief written statement: "this is only a beginning.
just as president bush said on the 4th, all parties in the middle east should fulfil their own obligations. the president hopes that all parties will work harder."
israeli troops started to withdraw from tulkarem and qalqilya on the early morning of the 9th local time. israel has not revealed so far when it is going to withdraw all its troops from other cities in the west bank.
bush reiterated in his speech to reporters in tennessee on the same day that israel must withdraw its troops from the palestinian territory immediately, stressing that he "means what he says."
bush said he had already told the israeli prime minister sharon the us demand, and he is waiting now for israel to immediately withdraw its troops.
bush says nato must forge new relationship with russia
xinhua news agency, beijing, april 10 according to news received at this time, the us president bush said on the 9th when he was meeting with the visiting nato secretary general robertson in the white house that nato must forge a "new relationship" with russia that is "more constructive."
bush said, through forging this relationship, "we will finally and forever abolish the divisions that are relics of a previous era."
during this meeting, bush and robertson discussed a series of issues, including the issues of iraq and the eastern expansion of nato.
bush said: "nato must develop new, flexible capabilities to meet the challenges of the 21st century.
we must also take on new members."
when interviewed by reporters after the meeting, bush did not mention iraq directly.
but he said: "as we move forward in the war against terror, we will consult closely with our allies."
robertson said that bush and he have discussed "the common threats we face in europe and north america, including weapons of mass destruction."
he said that all the nato member nations will unite in their actions to overcome these threats and will "succeed."
mexican president's visit to the us and canada vetoed by senate
xinhua news agency, mexico city, april 9 a spokesman for the mexican senate said on the 9th that the mexican president fox's plan to visit the united states and canada in the middle of this month was vetoed by the senate on the same day.
this is the first time in the history of this country that the senate has vetoed a president's visiting plan.
the spokesman said that the senate vetoed 71-41 against the president's visit.
the senators who voted against the visit held that the president should spend more energy on domestic issues instead of being interested in going abroad.
last year, president fox made 15 foreign trips.
one senator said the reason for their veto is because they were surprised to learn that one of the main purposes of the president's visit this time is nothing but to hold talks with the mexican immigrants.
it is reported that after being vetoed by the senate, the president's visiting plan will be submitted to the house of representatives for a vote.
if it is again vetoed there, his visiting plan will be canceled right away.
however, if it is passed, the senate will review it again.
president fox originally planned to visit seattle in the united states on the 15th of this month, where he would meet bill gates, chairman of the board of microsoft and members of the mexican immigrant communities.
after that, he would fly to vancouver and calgary in canada to hold talks with the local businessmen and people from academic circles. the trip would take 3 days.
track and field meet at west asian games goes full steam
xinhua news agency, kuwait, april 10 (reporter an jiang) half way through the agenda since the opening of the west asian games, the much awaited track and field meet slowly took its place today.
the athletes from 12 nations participating in this year's competition will compete for the gold medals in seven categories in the first day's track and field competition.
in the competition of the ball games on the 9th, the kuwaiti basketball team defeated its strong opponent qatar team by a narrow margin of 97-93 and won the championship of the basketball match at this west asian games.
the syrian team defeated the iranians 110-92 and won the third place.
if the kuwaiti team wants to win the championship in the football competition, it must win in today's game with the "dark horse," the palestinian team.
the game called "a bottleneck fight" by the kuwaiti media will determine the champion.
the syrian handball team defeated the iranian team with a close score of 33-32 and will compete with the kuwaiti team today for the gold medal.
as of the 9th, the kuwaiti team still sits securely on top of the list with a total number of 49 medals, of which there are 19 gold, 18 silver, and 12 bronze. right after kuwait are iran, syria, saudi arabia, qatar and jordan.
powell said talks with arafat very important
xinhua news agency, madrid, april 10 the us secretary of state powell said here on the 10th that his talks with the palestinian leader arafat during his trip to the middle east is "very important," and that he hopes there will be no problems in arranging his talks with arafat.
powell made the above remarks after he had held talks with the eu, russian and un officials.
he said: "arafat is the leader of the palestinian people. i think the palestinian people and the leaders of the arab nations believe he is the person israel has to deal with."
it is reported that the white house spokesman fleischer indicated in washington on the same day that israel has promised the united states that powell will be able to meet with arafat during his visit to the middle east.
israeli minister of defense ben-eliezer also told reporters on the same day near the west bank town of jenin that israel will not prevent powell from meeting with arafat later this week.
initially, powell did not have any plan to meet with arafat in his mediation in the middle east.
palestinian officials once indicated that if powell refused to meet with arafat, no palestinian representatives would hold talks with him.
while powell was visiting morocco and egypt, the leaders of the arab nations also emphasized repeatedly that if he did not meet with arafat during his visit, he would accomplish nothing.
former serbian interior minister of yugoslavia attempted suicide
xinhua news agency, belgrade, april 11 (reporter yang chengming) stojiljkovic, the war crime suspect wanted by the hague tribunal, the former serbian interior minister of yugoslavia and the current member of the federal parliament, shot himself in the head in front of the federal parliament building on the evening of the 11th.
he was taken immediately to a hospital for emergency treatment, but so far he is still in a critical condition.
in his suicide note, stojiljkovic said: "as a deputy of the federal parliament, i am acting in protest of this puppet regime.
i denounce their reckless violation of the yugoslav constitution and laws and their trampling of our national dignity to destroy this country."
yugoslav president kostunica made a statement on this incident in the evening, claiming that stojiljkovic's suicide was a warning to the western nations that constantly set conditions and pressures on yugoslavia.
the yugoslav parliament, chamber of republics and chamber of citizens, passed the law on cooperation with the hague tribunal on the 10th and the 11th respectively.
under the terms of the law, war crime suspects wanted by the hague tribunal before this law was passed, will be extradited to the hague tribunal if found on the yugoslav territory, no matter what citizenship they have.
according to this law, stojiljkovic will also be extradited to the hague.
saudi arabia to raise money in support of palestine
xinhua news agency, riyadh, april 12 (reporter yu kaiyuan) to support palestine, saudi arabia held a nation-wide fund-raising event via a television station from 4 p.m., april 11 to 3 a.m., april 12 local time.
saudi arabian national television station set up 30 hotlines and 15 computers to receive donors.
inside the courtyard of the television station, a reception team of 25 people was formed to attend to those who came to make donations in person.
the event raised a total of 210 million riyal(56 million us dollars) in cash and large quantity of goods.
saudi arabia's king took the lead and donated 10 million riyal (2.67 million us dollars); crown prince abdullah donated 5 million riyal (1.34 million us dollars); and the famous saudi arabian entrepreneur prince alwaleed also donated 100 million riyal (26.7 million us dollars).
although april 11 and 12 were non-working days in saudi arabia and it happened to have a thunderstorm, the street in front of the television station was still jammed with long lines of cars waiting to make donations.
many company employees also donated their one-day wages.
presidential election in east timor drew to a close
xinhua news agency, jakarta, april 12 according to the local media, the 3-week presidential campaign in east timor has drawn to an official close on april 12.
on the 14th, voters will elect the first president of this country that will officially become independent on may 20.
candidates running for the presidency are xanana gusmao and xavier do amaral.
gusmao is the leader of the independence movement in east timor, while do amaral was once the president of the democratic republic of east timor that was pronounced established in november, 1975 but existed only for a very brief period.
the two candidates held a public debate in dili on the 11th and answered various kinds of questions the voters asked.
gusmao said that he will first of all try to solve the economic problems of the country after he is elected, while do amaral expressed he will ensure the democracy of the country.
public opinion generally holds that gusmao has a great chance of winning because he is considered a hero in winning east timor's independence.
under the sponsorship of the united nations, east timor held a referendum on august 30, 1999, in which most voters chose independence.
on august 30 of last year, east timor officially voted for the establishment of its constituent assembly which passed the country's first constitution in march of this year.
the new constitution will become effective on may 20 when east timor becomes officially independent. the constituent assembly will immediately become the first national parliament.
foreign ministry spokeswoman confirmed death of a chinese worker in jerusalem bombing
xinhua news agency, beijing, april 13 foreign ministry spokeswoman zhang qiyue confirmed here today that a chinese worker died in the bombing that took place near a bus station in jerusalem on the afternoon of april 12. another two chinese workers were wounded and one worker is missing.
zhang qiyue said, at about 4 p.m. on april 12, a suicide bombing took place at a bus station in downtown jerusalem. six were instantly killed and more than 70 were wounded.
the bombing incident left one chinese worker dead, another two wounded, still another missing.
she said chinese embassy in israel took the incident very seriously and immediately sent people and the company's representatives to jerusalem to identify the dead and visited the wounded. they investigated the case and contacted the relevant parties to deal with the aftermath.
the embassy has already issued an overnight notice to chinese citizens and companies in israel that they must pay attention to safety and be cautious when going out.
she said the chinese government expresses condolences over the misfortune of the chinese citizens in the bombing and offers consolation to their family members.
china condemns the violence against innocent civilians and strongly urges israel and palestine to take real actions to stop their violent confrontations and stabilize the situation as soon as possible so as to avoid more civilian casualties.
zhang qiyue said the chinese government again reminds the chinese citizens in israel and those planning to go to israel to pay attention to safety and be cautious when going out. they should keep close contact with their families in china and contact the chinese embassy in israel right away if there is an emergency.
according to middle east news agency (mena) in egypt, foreign ministers of both nations agreed over their telephone conversation that israel should make a positive response to the four-side joint statement issued in spain by the united nations, the united states, russia and the european union and immediately withdraw its troops from the palestinian territories.
maher briefed pique on his meeting with arafat on friday of this week in the west bank city of ramallah controlled by palestinians.
maher said that palestine is ready to work with the international community and seek for ways to end the israeli invasion into the palestinian territories pursuant to the relevant un resolutions.
maher and pique agreed to keep in touch with all parties concerned and to seek for ways that will thoroughly solve the middle east conflicts.
the us state department spokesman boucher who accompanied powell on his visit to the middle east indicated earlier on the same day that due to the bombing in downtown jerusalem on the 12th, powell has cancelled his scheduled meeting with arafat on the 13th.
but a state department official who preferred to remain anonymous disclosed that powell's meeting with arafat may be postponed to the 14th.
according to another report, maher also contacted on the same day the lebanese prime minister hariri by phone, and both sides exchanged their opinions on the latest development of the situation in palestine.
uae announced to foot the bill for rebuilding jenin refugee camp in palestine
xinhua news agency, abu dhabi, april 13 (reporter xin xudong) hamdan, united arab emirates minister of state for foreign affairs, announced to the press on the evening of the 13th that uae will foot the bill for rebuilding jenin refugee camp in palestine destroyed by the israeli troops. the rebuilding will start soon so that those homeless families will have their own residences as early as possible.
hamdan said that after coordinating with the united nations relief and works agency for palestine refugees in the near east (unwra), red crescent society of the united arab emirates in charge of this operation has already formulated specific plans on repairing the damaged buildings and public facilities in jenin refugee camp.
the minister also said since israel launched large-scale military actions against the palestinian cities in the west bank on march 29, uae has organized several nation-wide fund-raising events for palestine. the donation collected so far has reached 350 million uae dirham (close to 100 million us dollars).
(detailed news) chavez reinstated as president of venezuela
xinhua news agency, caracas, april 14 (reporter jia anping) venezuela's president hugo chavez who was detained in a military coup two days ago returned to the presidential palace on the 14th and swore in again as president of bolivarian republic of venezuela among cheers of his supporters.
in a televised speech to the nation, chavez expressed his thanks to the venezuelan people for their trust and support. he also thanked the international organizations such as the organization of american states, rio group and g-77 for their support of democracy and condemnation of the coup, and called on all circles in venezuela to adopt reconciliatory actions.
chavez stressed that venezuela needs peace, stability and reason for which all parties should work hard together and stop any conflicts.
he said that in this incident, "we have learned a lot. we will try hard to correct the past mistakes and faults and build our country together."
a military coup took place in venezuela on the 11th. more than 10 senior military officers issued a statement that they did not support the chavez government and put chavez in their custody.
carmona, former chairman of venezuelan business association (fedecamaras), became the temporary president of the transitional government on the 12th.
on the same day, supporters of chavez held a peaceful demonstration in the capital, demanding that chavez be reinstated.
on the afternoon of the 13th, a group of pro-chavez military officers quietly escorted vice president cabello to the presidential palace who swore in as the temporary president on the very night. carmona announced his resignation.
the pro-chavez military forces then issued an ultimatum to the military officers in the coup for the release of chavez and occupied tiuna military barracks, an important strategic stronghold.
on the early morning of the 14th, chavez boarded on a helicopter from a small caribbean island where he had been detained and flew back to the presidential palace.
xinhua news agency, damascus, april 15 (reporter gong zhenxi) on the 15th, syrian president bashar al-assad held a talk here with the visiting us secretary of state powell on the latest development in the middle east, especially the serious situation in palestine, the tensions in the lebanon-israel border areas and other issues.
according to sana (syrian arab news agency), president bashar commented during the talk: "events in palestine have pushed the peace process (middle east) into a cul-de-sac. if we don't understand this, things may develop out of control. by then we will just have to wait for another generation."
he pointed out that only after israel pulls out its troops from the occupied palestinian territories and stops killing palestinians can peace process be discussed.
he said: "only when both sides want to realize peace can peace be realized."
he urged that the united states maintain a clear notion of the peace in the middle east and play its due role in this so that the un resolutions can be actually implemented.
as for the palestinians' suicide actions, bashar said, these actions are not the cause of what has happened in the occupied palestinian territories but rather the consequences. they are the counterattacks against the israeli actions.
he pointed out that the best solution is to remove the cause of the tension in palestine.
some diplomatic sources disclosed that during his talk with bashar, powell also discussed the situation in the lebanon-israel border areas.
powell paid this brief visit to syria when he arrived in damascus from beirut at noon.
stocks plummet in new york exchange
xinhua news agency, new york, april 15 due to the poor performances of the citigroup and continental airlines, investors still worried about the profit prospect of the listed companies. there was a general drop in new york stock market on the 15th, with the dow jones index slipping to the lowest level in the last 8 weeks.
the dow jones 30 industrial stocks average index dropped 97.15 for the day, closing at 10093.67, the lowest point since february 22. the nasdaq composite index comprised mainly of tech stocks slipped 2.41 points, closing at 1753.78. standard & poor's 500 index dropped 8.46 points, closing at 1102.55.
in addition, the new york stock exchange composite index and russell 2000 index of smaller stocks also showed a decline. only the american stock exchange market price index rose slightly up.
new york stock exchange's decline-advance ratio was 5-4, and the trade volume declined from 1.26 billion shares of the previous day to 1.12 billion shares.
when citigroup announced on the same day that due to losses in its operation in argentina, the profits for the first quarter did not reach the estimated goal; continental airlines also announced that it suffered losses in the first quarter of this year.
the news made investors jittery about the performances of the ipo companies set for this week, for which they opted to take a wait-and-see attitude.
after some small fluctuations on wall street, the stock market posted losses at closing with a low trade volume of the day.
both blue chips such as citibank, continental airlines, general electric and tech stocks such as microsoft, intel, cisco, oracle, dell and sun microsystems plummeted.
powell to hold talks again with palestinian and israeli leaders
xinhua news agency, jerusalem, april 16 (reporter zhong cuihua) the visiting us secretary of state powell will hold talks again with the israeli prime minister sharon and arafat, chairman of the palestinian national authority, respectively on the afternoon of the 16th and the morning of the 17th.
it is reported that powell postponed his departure from the middle east at least for 24 hours so as to continue his mediation efforts between israel and palestine.
powell expressed his hope that israel and palestine can issue a joint statement, condemning the terrorist attacks targeted at israelis and palestinians, calling for an establishment of a palestinian state through negotiations and continuing their fight against terrorism.
on the evening of the 15th, powell returned to israel after he finished his one-day visit to lebanon and syria, and announced late that night his cancellation of the scheduled talk with arafat on the 16th.
powell told the press that the united states supports sharon's proposal of convening a regional peace conference, that a ministerial conference can be convened and arafat can send a senior delegation to attend it.
in response, arafat has already remarked that only when israel withdraws immediately its troops from the palestinian controlled territories in the west bank can palestinian side accept the proposal to hold a regional peace conference.
powell held a talk with sharon on the 12th.
on the 14th, he went to the city of ramallah in the west bank and held talks with arafat who was under the siege of the israeli military.
on that night, he briefed sharon on his meeting with arafat.
un high commissioner for refugees visits afghanistan
xinhua news agency, kabul, april 16 (reporter shang xuqian) on the evening of the 15th, lubbers, unhcr (un high commissioner for refugees) who is currently visiting afghanistan, met with karzai, chairman of the afghan interim government, and both sides held talks on such issues as the repatriation of afghan refugees and their re-entering the society.
on the 16th, the un refugee agency issued a press communique that lubbers stressed in his talks the importance of the refugees' re-entering the society to the stability in afghanistan.
he emphasized that the safety of the refugees returning home must be guaranteed and that the security in the rural areas is very important in preventing the influx of too many refugees to the cities.
karzai expressed his thanks to the un refugee agency for its long-term work in afghanistan.
he said that one of the focuses for the interim government is to reintroduce the refugees into the society.
he stressed that for the internally displaced people to go back to their homeland is an issue that must be immediately addressed.
he indicated that at present the situation in most areas in afghanistan is stable; as there has been plenty of rainfall, these people can immediately start farming as soon as they return to their homeland and achieve self-sufficiency in food supply.
according to the un refugee agency spokesman hasan, since the un refugee agency and the afghan interim government officially started the operation of repatriating refugees on march 1, over 240,000 afghans have returned home from pakistan. the number of the afghan refugees returning home from iran reached 5,000, and another 4,000 returned home from tajikistan.
40% of these people have gone into cities.
lubbers arrived in afghanistan for a visit after he ended his visit in iran.
he will visit pakistan on the 17th.
seeds began being eliminated in the second round at badminton european championship
xinhua news agency, stockholm, april 17 (reporter wu ping) the badminton european championship started its second round today in the city of malmo in southern sweden for the five individual competitions.
except in the mixed doubles, seeds began being eliminated in all other individual competitions.
in men's singles, the seed coli haughton from england was eliminated by peter rasmussen from denmark.
the seed eliminated in women's singles is tine rasmussen from denmark. she was defeated by juliane schenk from germany.
in men's doubles, the seeds joakim andersson/johan holm were defeated by a pair of russian players.
the seeds eliminated in women's doubles are felicity gallup/joanne muggeridge from wales. they were defeated by a pair of polish and belarus-russian partners.
according to the agenda, the five individual competitions will start their one-eighth and quarter finals tomorrow.
semi-finals and finals will be held on the 19th and 20th respectively.
palestine condemned israeli troops' continued aggression against palestinian people.
xinhua news agency, gaza, april 18 (reporter du zhen) palestinian national authority issued a statement on the 17th, condemning israeli troops' continued aggression against the palestinian people in the west bank and the gaza strip, claiming israeli prime minister sharon's policy of abusing its military power "killed all the hopes for peace in the region."
the statement said that the main reason why the us secretary of state powell's mediation efforts in the middle east have failed is because "the israeli government and its prime minister sharon refuse to withdraw troops from the palestinian cities and to end their military actions there."
for that day, the israeli troops continued to control most of the palestinian cities in the west bank.
according to eyewitnesses, the israeli armored troops withdrew from jenin for a time during that day, but came back again soon afterwards and reoccupied the central area of the city.
as reported by a israeli radio station, the israeli troops shot one palestinian near the israeli settlement in the southern part of gaza on that night.
palestinian security officers said that this palestinian was shot to death while passing by the settlement.
whereas, the israeli military claimed he was shot to death by the israeli troops while he was attempting to attack the settlement with several other armed palestinians.
putin delivered state of the union address
xinhua news agency, moscow, april 18 on the 18th, the russian president putin pointed out in the state of the union address at a bicameral meeting of the duma that russia should become an economically powerful and competitive country, commit itself to developing normal and constructive relations with all nations of the world, and should become a real member of the international community.
putin said that the goals for the national construction in russia are still promoting democracy, building a civilized market economy, and most importantly, raising people's living standards.
while summarizing last year's job performance, he pointed out that the country has achieved some accomplishments in completing the major tasks; the economy has maintained its continued growth; the unemployment is down; the people's life has improved; and the russian people are full of confidence for the future.
putin expressed his satisfaction with the good implementation of the budget and improvement of the business environment for two years in a row.
he laid special emphasis on the fact that the oil production in russia has ranked the 2nd in the world and that the volume of energy trade ranked the 1st in the world.
in his state of the union address, putin also talked about the national development plan for this fiscal year and the domestic and foreign policies.
this is the third time that putin has delivered his state of the union address to the two houses of duma since he became president.
a total of nearly 1,000 people, including more than 600 assemblymen, 89 leaders of the russian federation, chief officials from the office of president and government agencies, attended the joint meeting.
foreign ministry spokeswoman comments on report adopted by european parliament
xinhua news agency, beijing, april 19 while answering reporters' questions here today, foreign ministry spokeswoman zhang qiyue commented on the report adopted by the european parliament.
a reporter asked: on april 11, the plenary session of the european parliament reviewed and adopted "european parliament's report on an eu strategy towards china."
how does china comment on this?
zhang qiyue answered: china has noticed that the european parliament has recently adopted this report.
the report holds that a broad range of common interests exists between china and europe. it advocates development of the partnership between china and europe, increase in bilateral contacts, exchanges and dialogs, and expansion of the cooperation between both sides in such fields as economics, trade, science and technology, education and culture.
we welcome all the above positive propositions.
however, the report has made many wrong conclusions that do not conform to objective facts on such issues as human rights situation in china, and the issues of taiwan and tibet. these seriously interfere with china's internal affairs and are unacceptable to the chinese side.
we hope the european parliament will truly abide by the one-china principle and do more things that will benefit the development of the bilateral relations so as not to cause any negative impact on the relationship between china and europe.
kidnapped employee of the indian high commission in pakistan released
xinhua news agency, new delhi, april 19 (reporter xiong changyi) indian foreign ministry spokeswoman rao announced on the evening of the 19th that khanna, an indian high commission employee in pakistan, who was kidnapped in the capital city of islamabad in the morning, was released in the afternoon.
rao said, khanna was handed over to the indian side in a local police bureau after the pakistani police notified the indian high commission in pakistan.
khanna, severely beaten up, is now hospitalized.
she said the pakistani police refused to make this a case of kidnapping, which arouses the suspicion that the pakistani intelligence agency may be involved.
khanna was kidnapped while going to work on a bus on the morning of the 19th.
indian foreign ministry issued a statement on that morning strongly protesting the pakistan's kidnapping in broad daylight of the indian high commission employee in pakistan.
enterprises in hebei actively apply for right to engage in foreign trade
xinhua news agency, shijiazhuang, april 20 (reporter rao yajie) the reporter learned from the hebei provincial department of foreign economics and trade (hpdfet) that since the beginning of this year, nearly 200 enterprises of various types have registered with hpdfet for the right to engage in foreign trade or for approval by the department, an increase of 2.3 times that of the same period last year.
the reporter was told that 39 foreign trade companies of various types filed their registrations this time, among whom 17 are private-owned foreign trade companies.
in addition, there are also dozens of commercial, material supply, supply and marketing enterprises and the state-owned collective enterprises.
77 private-owned manufacturers also applied for the right to engage in foreign trade.
the increasing participation of the private-owned enterprises is a new trend in applying for the right to engage in foreign trade.
last july, hpdfet further loosened up the requirements and criteria for all types of enterprises in applying for the right to conduct their own import and export businesses and changed the previous process of review and approval to the present process of ratification and registration. it sets uniform standards and management systems on enterprises of various types of ownership, which greatly motivates them to apply.
israel to cooperate with un fact-finding team
xinhua news agency, jerusalem, april 20 (reporters zhong cuihua and ming dajun) on the 20th, the israeli government officials indicated that the relevant israeli parties will cooperate with the fact-finding committee sent by the united nations to jenin palestinian refugee camp in the west bank to find the truth.
the israeli radio station quoted the government officials as saying that the israeli side will show the un delegation the video-tapes that recorded how israeli troops carried out their military actions in jenin refugee camp and that they will let the delegates interview the soldiers and officers who took part in the military mission. it hopes the delegation will remain objective and fair during the investigation.
on the 19th, the un security council unanimously passed a resolution proposed by the united states to invite a un investigation team to conduct investigations on jenin refugee camp.
a few hours before the vote, the israeli foreign minister peres noted in his phone call to the un secretary general annan that israel will welcome the un delegates to "clarify" the truth on jenin refugee camp.
annan also talked with the israeli defense minister ben-eliezer on the phone that day. ben-eliezer also said he agreed to let the un delegation conduct investigations.
it is reported that both ben-eliezer and peres claim that the israeli troops exchanged heavy fires with the armed palestinians while carrying out their military missions. 23 israelis lost their lives, while 50 palestinians died with most of them being the armed personnel.
in recent days, the international community has been increasingly demanding for an investigation on jenin refugee camp where the most heavy fightings occurred in the recent israel-palestinian conflict.
palestine has accused the israeli troops of slaughtering palestinians there, causing hundreds of deaths, which israel totally denies.
china expresses strong dissatisfaction over junichiro's visit to yasukuni shrine
xinhua news agency, beijing, april 21 chinese foreign ministry spokeswoman zhang qiyue pointed out here today that china strongly opposes to japanese leaders' visit in any form and at any time, to the yasukuni shrine that houses tablets for class a war criminals.
china expresses strong dissatisfaction over the japanese leader's move this time.
zhang qiyue said in her speech on japanese prime minister junichiro koizumi's visit to the yasukuni shrine this morning that such a move on the japanese side can only hurt the image of japan itself and make it even more difficult for japan to win the trust of peoples in asian countries on historical issues.
this is the second time that junichiro koizumi has paid a visit to the yasukuni shrine since he became prime minister.
the yasukuni shrine is a place where japan honors its soldiers who were killed in the wars (mostly wars of aggression) since the meiji restoration, including such class a criminals as hideki tojo in world war ii.
first round of vote in french presidential election started
xinhua news agency, paris, april 21 (reporter liang guihe) the first round of vote in the french presidential election started at 8 a.m. on the 21st at 64,000 polling stations across france.
40 million voters in the nation will elect the 7th president for the french fifth republic from 16 candidates.
the result of the vote will be released at night.
according to a communique issued by the french interior ministry, as of 12 noon on the 21st, the voters' turnout is 21.4%, lower than the 22.52% voters' turnout at the first round of the presidential election in 1995.
according to the estimates of the local media, the voters' turnout this year may break the lowest record in history.
according to the french constitution, if no candidate wins more than 51% of votes in the first round, the two candidates who head the poll will enter the runoff on may 5.
the final result of opinion poll released last friday shows that the incumbent chirac and the current prime minister jospin may win the first round with very close votes.
since there are as many as 16 candidates in this presidential election, the highest record in the french history, the votes may be widely spread in the first round of the election.
the presidential candidate le pen from the french right-wing extremist national front may come in third in the first round, or even may score a surprise victory and enter the first two.
us to help georgia reform military
xinhua news agency, moscow, april 22 (reporter zhou liang) news from tbilisi: on the 22nd, georgian president shevardnadze denied the report that the united states has refused to help georgia reform its military.
according to itar-tass, shevardnadze made the above remark at a press conference held in tbilisi.
he said that neither the united states nor georgia has changed the previous agreement that the us military experts will help georgia reform its military, and that only so far no specific date has been decided upon as to when the us military experts will arrive in georgia.
he said the us military experts are making preparations right now for their trip to georgia, and they will arrive in georgia sooner or later.
he pointed out that the strengthened cooperation between the united states and georgia is not directed at russia.
it is reported that under the agreement reached between georgia and the united states, the us military experts will help georgia train four battalions and one company of soldiers this year.
foreign press association in israel demands israeli military return confiscated press cards
xinhua news agency, jerusalem, april 22 (reporter zhong cuihua) foreign press association stationed in israel announced a statement on the 22nd, demanding that israeli military return immediately the press cards of at least 17 foreign reporters they confiscated in the west bank city of bethlehem.
the statement said, an israeli military officer on that day confiscated the press cards of some palestinians working for international news agencies and the press cards of some foreign reporters at a location about 400 meters away from the church of the nativity, on the ground that the place is a closed military zone, yet producing no document as proof.
the statement pointed out that by confiscating the press cards, the israeli military was actually trying to restrict the media from reporting on the standoff between israeli military and palestinian militants at the church of the nativity, rather than out of consideration for the safety of the reporters. this broke the promise the israeli military made to the foreign press association last week.
on april 2, the israeli military that took over bethlehem laid siege to more than 200 armed palestinians at the church of the nativity and the standoff continues even as of today.
attitude softened under pressure, hindus hold peace prayers
(syndicated news from ayodhya, india) hundreds of hindus dressed in white robes held peace prayers in the holy site of ayodhya under the supervision of the riot police yesterday.
the hindu leader paramhans who proposes that a hindu temple be built on the site of the razed mosque handed over a sacred stone to a government official outside the place where the supreme court has banned any religious rituals.
the day before yesterday, paramhans threatened that he would hold prayers in ayodhya in spite of the court order.
however, he suddenly softened his attitude yesterday and indicated the prayers will be changed to another location in ayodhya.
according to the local media, paramhans, currently 93, has changed his original plan under the pressure of the ruling indian people's party.
before that, the indian authorities, concerned that hindu radicals might hold a prayer meeting near the original site of the mosque in spite of the court order, had sent additional paramilitary police force to station in this small northern town.
one-fourth voted against the work reports or abstained
npc deputies still not satisfied with the reform in the judicial system
(reporter zhou ruipeng) over one-fourth of the deputies to china's national people's congress (npc) yesterday voted against the work reports of the supreme people's court and the supreme people's procuratorate or abstained, showing that they are still not satisfied with the reform in the judicial system and the progress made in the adoption of the rule by law.
however, of the 2,813 deputies attending the closing meeting of the fifth session of the ninth national people's congress in the great hall of the people, 2,742 voted for premier zhu rongji's government work report, an approval rate still as high as 97.5%, comparable with that of last year.
it is expected by all that zhu rongji, who once publicly announced his intention to retire, will resign from the standing committee of the political bureau, the highest level of policy-making agency, at the "16th cpc congress" that will convene this fall.
the result of the vote, however, shows that zhu rongji is not treated coldly by the deputies just because he is going to lose his power.
yesterday, the 10.5-day session also passed the 2002 fiscal budget with a deficit as much as of 309.8 billion yuan (about 68.8 billion singapore dollars) by 80.5% of votes in favor.
the report by chairman li peng of the npc on the work of the standing committee of the npc, on the other hand, encountered a slightly more dissenting votes and abstentions than last year's.
yesterday, 2,587 deputies voted for the report by the standing committee of the people's congress, 112 voted against it and 114 abstained.
last year, 2,582 voted for the report, 85 voted against it and 122 abstained.
although the response from the npc deputies yesterday was slightly better than last year's, as many as 28% and 27% npc deputies voted against or abstained on the work reports of the supreme people's court and the supreme people's procuratorate respectively.
the work report by president xiao yang of the supreme people's court yesterday obtained a vote of 2,026 in favor, 528 against and 259 abstaining.
his last year's report obtained a vote of 1,953 in favor, 530 against and 306 abstaining.
the report by chief procurator han zhubin of the supreme people's procuratorate obtained yesterday a vote of 2,044 in favor, 516 against and 253 abstaining.
his report last year obtained a vote of 1,873 in favor, 584 against and 332 abstaining.
since this year's session is the last one for the ninth people's congress which will change to the tenth congress next year, at the closing meeting yesterday, the resolution on the number and election of deputies of the tenth national people's congress was also passed by votes, specifying that the deputies to the 10th npc be elected by the end of january next year.
china to speed up the reshuffle of local party and government leaders
(hong kong) sources at the "two meetings" in beijing disclosed to mingpao that after the session of the national people's congress (npc) and the chinese people's political consultative conference (cppcc) ended, the reshuffle of local party and government leaders will be accelerated.
the central government requires that government agencies in all parts of the country should complete their change of personnel for the new term by the end of june of this year. the 17 provinces, municipalities directly under the central government, and autonomous regions that have not completed their adjustment will form new leadership groups.
the report said, according to the recruitment standards of the central committee of the communist party of china, the party and government leaders at the provincial level should generally have post-baccalaureate education and post-baccalaureate degrees.
cccp also requires that newly appointed secretaries of provincial party committees be under 59 and provincial governors under 56.
in addition, in order to strengthen the communist party's leadership of the people's congress at all levels, the positions of directors of the people's congress at all levels will be concurrently held by secretaries of the party committee at corresponding levels after the change of personnel for the new term is completed at all local governments.
sources pointed out, since last march, within china's 31 provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities directly under the central government, 62 party and government leaders have been switched and transferred.
among them, from last year up till now, a total of 14 provinces have completed the adjustment in the local party committees, including the six provinces and regions of inner mongolia, jiangxi, hubei, hainan, yunnan, qinghai where adjustments have been made to the secretaries of provincial party committees.
at the government level of the provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions, including the governors or mayors of shanghai, jiangxi, shandong, hunan and yunnan, a total of 11 provincial officials have had their positions adjusted.
us embassy in yemen attacked by grenades, young man arrested but nobody injured
(sanaa, syndicated news) yemeni and us officials said that a yemeni young man threw grenades toward the us embassy in yemen the night before, but the young man was immediately arrested and no one was injured in this attack.
the us embassy in italy received a package of white powder through mail.
in rome, the us embassy in italy received a package of white powder through mail the day before yesterday. the embassy staff were afraid that the package might contain anthrax.
an embassy spokesman said that the package has been handed over to a team of biochemical experts in the local fire department for a lab test, and the result will be released next week.
an official from yemeni interior ministry told the state-run television station that a 25-year-old man named awad threw a grenade to the wall of the us embassy in the northern shawang area in the capital city of sanaa.
he said awad was from the governorate of al mahwit 60 km northwest of sanaa. he was carrying another grenade at the time of his arrest.
the official said the grenade blast did not cause any death or injury nor any damage.
eyewitnesses said that after the grenade exploded, the police immediately surrounded the neighborhood of the embassy.
in washington d.c., state department spokesman boucher said the preliminary investigation shows that the embassy has suffered no damages and no one inside the embassy was injured.
the perpetrator is currently in the custody of the yemeni authorities.
the authorities said that the grenade failed to be thrown inside the wall of the embassy.
stock markets in new york and london surge together
(syndicated news) the us consumer confidence and industrial production have been rising together, rekindling the confidence in wall street markets. with three key indexes climbing up at the same time, the dow jones industrial index enters its fifth week on a more steady upward trend.
investors believe that as the us economy recovery enters its best state, corporate profits are expected to rise. wal-mart, a chain group that enjoys the highest volume of sales in the united states, and the credit card issuer american express, took the lead to soar, making the dow jones index enjoy the longest weekly rate of increase ever since september, 2000.
at closing on friday, the dow jones industrial index posted 10607.23, up 90.09 points or 0.9%.
nasdaq posted 1868.30, up 14.16 points or 0.8%, while the broader standard & poor's 500 posted 1166.16, up 13.12 points or 1.1%.
for the entire week, the dow jones index edged higher by 0.3%, expanding this year's rate of increase to 5.8%.
standard & poor's 500 rose slightly by 0.2%, while the nasdaq index fell 3.2%, marking the first declining week in three weeks.
the us consumer confidence index released by the university of michigan on friday rose for the fifth time in six months, hitting the highest point in the past 15 months and showing the momentum of the economic rebound.
on the other hand, the industrial production index for february this year released by the us authorities rose 0.4%, better than what the market originally predicted. it is also the second time that it has risen in the past 17 months.
economists think these two data paint a clearer picture of the economic recovery.
therefore, the future trend of the market may lead to more optimistic realms.
in new york stock exchange, the advancer/decliner ratio is 4-3, while the volume of trade reached 1.4 billion shares.
however, nasdaq's advancer/decliner ratio is 6-5.
in british markets, the record company emi may lay off employees, the bio-tech company celltech may stop selling stocks. both pieces of news will cheer up the market and push up the stock market by 0.6%.
however, pharmaceutical company glasosmithkline's second best-selling drug may have to face competition from its counterpart in indian; and deutsche bank's lowering the targeted stock price for vodafone, the largest mobile phone company in europe, limited the index's rate of increase.
london ftse index closed at 5292.70 on friday, up 31.30 points.
north korean patrol boat accused of incursion into south korean territorial waters
(seoul, ap) south korean officials said a north korean patrol boat intruded into the south korean territorial waters yesterday.
south korean joint chiefs of staff (jcs) said, the patrol boat crossed the yellow sea border by 1.5 km and stayed there for 42 minutes. then, it was chased away by south korean warships.
it said the north korean patrol boat accidentally intruded into the south korean territorial waters while it was inspecting a cambodian freighter.
the marine border between the two koreas is not very clear. yesterday's intrusion is the second time for this year.
south korea accused north korea of intruding into the western part of its territorial waters for 12 times last year, but each time the incident was not very serious.
in 1999, a succession of north korean ships intruding into the south korean territorial waters triggered the first sea clash since the korean war, causing a north korean warship to sink. 30 north korean marines were believed to have lost their lives.
on the other hand, intelligence sources said that 25 north korean defectors stayed for the night on an army base in the philippines yesterday before they flew to south korea for asylum.
this group of refugees arrived at the manila airport from beijing on friday night.
according to the relevant parties, "their documents for travelling to south korea are being processed right now."
south korean foreign ministry said, this group of north koreans will board a korean air flight on monday and fly to seoul.
us official: al qaeda steps up money flow
(washington, syndicated news) according to the us media, a us official said on condition of anonymity that the world's no.1 terrorist osama's al qaeda network has stepped up its financial activities in recent weeks. this shows that some al qaeda leaders are resuming their control of this organization and will likely attempt to finance more terrorist attacks targeted at the us interests.
this official said, while al qaeda increases its money flow, communications among the surviving al qaeda members have also been increasing.
the information intercepted by the us intelligence agencies shows that a small group of al qaeda members are contacting the armed talibans.
most of the communication activities are concentrated in the northwestern pakistan near the border with afghanistan.
this official said these activities show that some well-known al qaeda leaders are resuming the control of the remnants of this terrorist organization, but the us official declined to reveal the names of these people.
cannistraro, a former chief of a cia counterterrorist agency, said many signs show that al qaeda is reconstituting itself; most of their communications are conducted through the internet and funds exchanges are also frequent.
cannistraro also said some evidence shows that the al qaeda leadership is also starting to be active.
taiwan dpp legislator chen chin-teh visits beijing with fishing delegation
(beijing, syndicated news) taiwan's democratic progressive party (dpp) legislator chen chin-teh arrived yesterday in beijing for a visit together with an exploratory delegation made up of several fishing groups.
chen chin-teh is the first dpp member to visit mainland china after china's vice premier qian qichen delivered a speech on the 7th anniversary of "jiang's eight points" that welcomes dpp members to visit mainland china in appropriate capacity.
chen chin-teh went to hong kong on saturday for his visa and arrived in beijing yesterday for his 10-day visit.
chen chin-teh emphasized that the purpose of this trip is solely to get some assistance in solving the shortage of fishermen in ilan constituency. since he is going to china in a private capacity, he hopes he can keep a low profile. but he disclosed that he will on this trip meet with officials from the ministry of foreign economics and trade and the relevant civil groups in mainland china in hopes that the beijing authorities will agree to lift the ban on mainland fishermen working in taiwan.
after mainland china banned its fishermen from going to work in taiwan, there has been a serious shortage of fishermen in ilan region. in order to help the shipowners in his constituency, chen chin-teh decided to go to beijing and join the visiting delegation organized by the fishing association of taiwan province so as to help the owners of the fishing business, in the hope that mainland china can resume its labor-export of fishermen to taiwan.
the visiting delegation made up of chairmen of the board of fishing associations from 13 districts of taiwan is headed by huang yung-chu, secretary general of the taiwan provincial fishery association. it left for beijing for a visit last thursday under the name of "the employees' association of the republic of china."
serious sandstorm hit beijing again
(beijing, afp) the state media of china said that yesterday a serious sandstorm hit beijing again.
although the government has invested huge sums of money to improve the environment in beijing and prevent the sandstorm from approaching beijing, eliminating the sandstorms that occur frequently every year remains the major difficulty facing the city of beijing where olympics games is to be held in 2008.
china national meteorological bureau forecasts said that the first sandstorm of this year hit beijing last friday. the cold fronts from mongolia are expected to envelop beijing in a yellow dusty haze.
yang weixi (transliterated), chief engineer of the desertification control center of china's ministry of forestry told beijing review: "i can't say there will be no more sandstorms in 2008.
what we can do is to control the human factors that cause sandstorms and prevent desertification of the environment."
he said, however, natural factors beyond human control such as wind, drought, and vast deserts make it impossible for china to avoid sandstorms within a short period of time.
the chinese government pledged to pour in 56.8 billion yuan (12.376 billion singapore dollars) from 2002 to 2008 to curb desertification and reduce the formation of sandstorms.
beijing alone will spend about 1 billion yuan (about 220 million singapore dollars) this year.
an expert from china forestry research institute said: "increased financial appropriations will greatly improve the situation, but...it may take decades to see the result of harnessing efforts."
chinese environmental experts warned after conducting a survey at the beginning of this year: about one third of the land in china is currently desert. it is mainly caused by human beings' economic activities such overgrazing.
the survey report said that in the first six months of last year, 18 sandstorms struck beijing, and they all originated from inner mongolia where 60% of the land is desert.
at the session of the national people's congress (npc) that just closed this month, deputies from shanghai, beijing and inner mongolia urged the government to "erect" a green great wall (formed by trees)" to block the assaults of sandstorms.
according to shanghai star, xu shiyuan, vice chairman of the geographical society of china, warned that if the government does not take emergency measures, sandstorms may even hit as far as shanghai.
fake diplomas run rampant, many active cadres found to hold bogus credentials
(hong kong, syndicated news) fake diplomas are running rampant in mainland china. while verifying the degree certificates of 15 officials submitted by a city in chaoshan district, college graduates placement center of guangdong province confirmed seven of them as fake certificates just by the naked eye.
hong kong newspapers report that since the center started the verification service last may, it has so far verified more than 3,500 diplomas, of which over 800 are various types of fake credentials, accounting as much as 23% of the total.
it is reported that certificates of adult education and self-study examinations make up the most of the fake credentials. two-thirds are forged by the street solicitors, and the other one-third are issued by the regular education institutions in violation of regulations.
the chief official from the center also disclosed, their verification department was founded at a time when the organizational reform was underway. therefore, their clients are mostly the government agencies, corporations and institutions. the ratio of the fake certificates among some of these clients is very high. many fake certificate holders are all cadres in active duty.
approved by the relevant agency of the chinese ministry of education, the college graduates placement center of guangdong province is currently the only authorized agency in china to verify diplomas and credentials of higher education in the country.
the chief official also disclosed that a state-owned municipal bank, in consideration of its employee promotion, sent the diplomas of 36 middle-level officials and key business personnel for verification. only six of them were authentic.
it is reported that as the business of verification becomes popular, quite a few private enterprises also requested for the service. what they mainly wanted to verify were the job applicants and newly recruited college graduates.
the verification department found quite a few fake college diplomas.
last year, a large corporation set up a branch in the pearl river delta and recruited a group of college students.
the boss sent over 30 diplomas and credentials of employees for verification and found ten of them were counterfeits.
in recent years, quite a few colleges and universities of other provinces have set up their branches in guangdong province. actually, these schools are never qualified to issue any diplomas. yet, in order to attract students, they resort to fraud at the time of recruitment, claiming they can issue state-accredited diplomas. when the students graduate, they simply forge these fake certificates and give them to the students.
25 north korean asylum seekers arrived in seoul
(seoul, reuters) 25 north korean asylum seekers arrived at seoul international airport yesterday and started a new life in south korea.
after they went through the customs, they waved and smiled at the south korean tv camera.
li song, a 43-year-old factory worker, said at an ad hoc press conference at the airport: "we hope to settle down here and live in a place full of freedom and hopes."
another man said: "i risked my life to come here because south korea is a free country."
the group of north koreans stormed the spanish embassy in china last thursday and resolutely expressed their intention to go to south korea.
on friday, china allowed them to travel to seoul via the philippines.
they are from six families and two of them are orphaned girls.
they are the largest group of escapees since the korean war ended.
according to the national information agency (nia) in seoul, these people will join the 2,000 north koreans who have already settled down in south korea. of those, 138 defected to south korea this year.
last year, a record-breaking number of 583 defected to south korea.
the 25 new arrivals will take adjustment lessons in a government shelter near the capital city of seoul.
the main purpose of the curriculum is to help the defectors overcome the stress of fleeing and then they will be offered counseling to adjust themselves to the south korean culture, including understanding capitalism.
the last step is for them to receive new job training.
the new yorker weekly: iraqi intelligence agency in close contact with al qaeda for years
(washington, syndicated news) the most recent issue of the new yorker weekly reports that for years the iraqi intelligence agency has been in close contact with al qaeda network led by osama who masterminded the september 11 attacks.
it is reported that these two organizations jointly command a terrorist organization in the kurdish area of northern iraq.
the cia has always been skeptical about the claim that iraqi president hussein has been in touch with al qaeda network.
the "hawks" in the bush administration who support military actions against iraq have been trying in the past to find evidence of hussein's ties with al qaeda network.
the day before yesterday, these officials praised highly the report by the new yorker weekly, saying the report is the latest evidence that supports their argument.
the report said that there is an ansar muslim guerrilla made up of kurds and arabs in the kurdish area of iraq. the members of this guerrilla have all received training in osama's camps.
the article's author goldberg said that he interviewed several ansar muslim guerrilla's special agents captured by a pro-american kurdish group, "the patriotic union of kurdistan." these special agents claimed that ansar muslim guerrilla is under the joint command of hussein and al qaeda network and that some al qaeda fighters in afghanistan have already fled to the kurdish area of iraq controlled by ansar muslim guerrilla.
the special agents added that iraq once hosted an al qaeda leader of egyptian origin in baghdad in 1992.
the us officials warned that the patriotic union of kurdistan may make full use of this report to prove that the us plan to overthrow hussein regime is justifiable.
newspapers in gulf countries report: cheney's middle east trip is a failure
(dubai, syndicated news) newspapers in gulf countries said on monday that the us vice president cheney's trip to the middle east is a failure.
cheney's trip is to lobby the middle east nations to support the united states in its attack against iraq.
cheney arrived in kuwait on monday after he visited all the gulf nations, but even this most loyal ally of the us also objects to attacking baghdad.
the saudi arabian newspaper "motherland" said: "what this vice president has heard is : the united states must stop the israeli terrorism and prevent israel from possessing weapons of mass destruction."
the newspaper also pointed out: "if the united states continues to ignore the interests of the middle east nations, it will lose its interests in the gulf region."
the united arab emirates newspaper gulf news also said: "this is a new failure of the united states in the middle east after it ran into snags in europe.
most of the us allies in europe publicly object to invading iraq."
yesterday in manama, the capital of bahrain, cheney denied the mission of his middle east trip was to organize a military assault on iraq.
he said at a joint press conference held with crown prince salman that some people think his only interest during this trip is to organize a military assault on iraq, but he denies that.
cheney claimed that he and crown prince salman mainly talked about the latest development in the war against terrorism, the situation in the middle east and afghanistan.
cheney arrived in israel on monday evening for a visit. he is expected to meet with prime minister sharon and discuss the latest development in the israeli-palestinian conflict.
on the other hand, the commanders-in-chief of israel and palestine in the west bank and the gaza strip surprisingly held a talk yesterday aiming to end the violence in this region.
this talk may be the first step israel has made in withdrawing its troops from the palestinian controlled territories.
the palestinian side said that if the israeli troops do not withdraw from these areas, palestine will not participate in any peace negotiations brokered by the united states.
street crimes rose sharply, britain to increase police patrol
(london, ap) the british government will be committed to solving the ever-increasing street crimes and will increase police patrol.
home secretary blunkett said that in order to curb the rising street muggings and violence, it is essential to increase police patrol.
he said, "we really should keep order in the street, because the law-abiding citizens hope to walk safely in the street, live a peaceful life and have no fear of being attacked."
although the overall crime rate in britain has dropped, the street crimes increased 13% from 2000 to 2001.
the situation in london is even more alarming. from september to november of 2001 alone, the reported cases of robbery amounted to 19,248, more than double the figure of 8,614 in the same period the year before.
the government also said the rise of crime cases was mainly due to the large increase of mobile phone robberies. last year, there were more than 700,000 cases of mobile phone robbery in the country.
this is the first time that the british police have focused their forces on the street hooliganism and robbery, while the previous focus was mainly on cracking down on the illegal possession of firearms and drug dealing in the street.
this new plan will first be implemented in the ten neighborhoods where street crimes are more concentrated.
the police will increase patrols in these neighborhoods and provide more protection to the victims.
workers in 10 state-owned factories in liaoning staged mass demonstration
(beijing, afp) workers in 10 state-owned factories in liaoyang, liaoning province in northeastern china staged a mass demonstration yesterday in protest of the overdue wages and pensions, low severance packages and embezzlement.
meantime, the laid-off oil workers in daqing, heilongjiang province have been continuously demonstrating for three weeks.
hong kong-based information center for human rights & democracy said that on sunday the public security bureau of liaoyang city arrested a demonstration organizer, the 54-year-old yao fuxin. at the same time, they are hunting about a dozen of workers who organized the demonstration.
according to a relative of yao who spoke on condition of anonymity: "he never returned from shopping. several people saw him taken away."
in addition, in daqing oilfield in the neighboring province of heilongjiang, the police and daqing petroleum administration bureau told the reporter that the sit-in demonstration by the laid-off oil workers has entered the third week, though the number of the workers participating in the sit-in has decreased from the initial 50,000 to just over 1,000.
some sources said that the workers in these two cities have established an independent labor union and decided to elect some representatives for negotiations.
under the existing law, this action is not permitted.
han dongfang, executive of a hong kong-based organization of chinese labor movement, said that although the two demonstrations started right after the national people's congress ended its session, the problem has been there for quite a long time.
han went on to say, a demonstration also took place in a textile factory on monday in guangyuan, sichuan. it was triggered by the arrest of several labor leaders who organized weekend strikes. as a result, 1,000 workers staged a demonstration in protest.
aviation safety council of taiwan (asc) repeatedly delayed investigation report on singapore airlines crash, causing prosecutors to smell a rat
(taipei) a year and half have passed since the plane crash of the singapore airlines, yet aviation safety council of taiwan (asc) has delayed the investigation report on the plane crash again and again, stalling the investigation by taoyuan district prosecutor's office and causing the prosecutors to smell a rat. as for asc, it has promised to deliver the investigation report in april.
at 11:18 p.m. on october 31, 2000, the singapore airlines flight sq-006 at chiang kai-shek airport bound for los angeles entered by error the runway #05 on the right side during take-off and crashed into the two digging machines and exploded, killing 83 passengers and injuring nearly a hundred passengers.
china times reported yesterday that taoyuan district prosecutor's office in charge of prosecuting for criminal liability after the plane crash has had several disputes over the right to investigate with asc investigation unit.
since the plane crash, wang tiensheng, former chief prosecutor of taoyuan prosecutor's office, has been promoted to chief prosecutor of taichong. chen shouhuang serves as his replacement. the case prosecutor huang moushin has also been transferred to taipei prosecutor's office, handing over the case to chiang yuanchen.
meanwhile, the original due date of the investigation report at the end of last year promised by asc was postponed to the end of january. after the end of january, it was again changed to february. so far there has been no news. urged by the prosecutors, asc now promises to deliver the report in april.
as los angeles was the destination of flight sq-006, some of the victims' families have already taken the case to the us court for huge sums of civil compensation, suing not only singapore airlines but also taiwan civil aviation administration.
the lawsuit by the victims' families for compensation is tantamount to accusing taiwan aviation administration's control tower of negligence of duty. therefore, the result of the investigation by taoyuan prosecutor's office will draw all the more attention.
if arafat abides by us cease-fire agreement, cheney will hold bilateral talks
(jerusalem, syndicated news) israeli prime minister sharon said yesterday that if the palestinian leader arafat implements the cease-fire agreement proposed by the united states, israel will allow arafat to leave the palestinian territories.
the us vice president cheney also indicated yesterday that if arafat implements the armistice agreement proposed by the united states, he will hold talks with the other side over the peace process in the middle east in the near future.
the arab league secretary general moussa said yesterday that the arab league will support a land-for-peace program in the next week's summit meeting so as to prevent the violence in the middle east from escalating.
moussa said during an interview with the italian newspaper evening post: "i believe there will be a clear consensus at the arab summit to be held in beirut, that is, land-for-peace.
by then, israel must make a decision."
the egyptian foreign minister maher indicated the day before yesterday that even if israel does not allow arafat to attend the arab league summit, saudi arabia will still propose a peace motion to solve the violent conflict in the middle east during the summit meeting.
annan condemned the israeli military actions for disregarding the safety of civilians.
on the other hand, the un secretary general annan sent a letter to sharon the day before yesterday, condemning israel for disregarding the safety of civilians in its escalating military actions and pointing out that the fighting "has come to resemble an conventional warfare with no restraint at all."
annan said that israel used f-16 fighter-bombers, helicopters, naval gunships and missiles to engage in cluster bombings "causing hundreds of innocent civilians including women and children to be injured or killed, and many buildings and homes to be damaged or destroyed."
annan called on sharon to ensure that israeli security forces "use weapons and fighting methods that will cause minimum threat to the safety and property of the palestinian civilians."
another warning for global warming, antarctic ice shelf collapsed
(auckland, syndicated news) the experts at the us national snow and ice data center said yesterday that an antarctic ice shelf has completely collapsed and broken up into thousands of icebergs. this is the largest single event of its kind over the last 30 years and therefore sends another warning about the global warming.
it is reported that the larsen b ice shelf of 3,250 square kilometers on the eastern side of the antarctic peninsula has completely disintegrated in a 35-day period.
the center warned that with the advent of the hot summer season, the other ice shelves are also on the verge of disintegration.
this portends an increase in the rate of flow of glaciers in antarctica, a rise in the global sea level and a threat to the lowland regions.
the center at the university of colorado says at its web site (nsida.org) that the larsen b ice shelf that may have existed for 12,000 years and weighs 720 billion tons started to break up since january 31 of this year, and the ice fragments have formed thousands of drifting icebergs in the weddell sea.
the center also indicated that the cause that led to the break-up of the ice shelf is the climate warming in the region.
more than half of britons disapprove government's support of us assault on iraq
(london, syndicated news) a poll released yesterday shows that more than half of the british voters disapprove the government's support of the us assault on iraq.
the polls by the guardian and the polling firm icm show that 51% voters are opposed to british backing of the us assault on iraq.
this is in contrast with the similar polls done last year and three years ago when the majority of british voters supported the attacks on iraq.
on the other hand, the similar polls done by the cable news network of the united states and the times weekly released the day before yesterday show that 70% americans support the government's military attack on iraq to overthrow the hussein regime.
in ottawa, the canadian prime minister chretien indicated the day before yesterday that if the united states leads the allied troops in attacking iraq, canada will consider joining.
chretien and other canadian ministers have been feeling uneasy about bush's hardline position against the iraqi regime of hussein, and have been also insisting that no evidence has shown hussein's ties to al qaeda network.
but chretien seems to have changed his original position after he went to hold talks with bush in washington d.c. last thursday.
he told cbs that he will seriously consider any us request for military assistance in areas outside afghanistan.
he said: "in terms of military involvement, if such a situation (as in afghanistan) occurs in other areas, we will study the current situation just as we did when we participated in afghan actions."
us to reduce domestic combat air patrol
(washington, reuters) the us defense officials said on monday that the bush administration has decided to reduce the alert level of combat air patrol that has been in effect since the sept. 11 attacks, but will still maintain a small number of patrolling flights and keep the planes on strip alert.
the pentagon said although the around-the-clock air patrol has cost the air force 500 million us dollars (about 900 million singapore dollars), the air patrol over washington d.c. will continue. as for the new york area, the air patrol will discontinue unless there is an emergency.
as airports and airlines have heightened the security since the sept. 11 attacks, the authorities have decided to reduce or cancel the air patrol.
the pentagon spokeswoman clark told the reporters: "we are studying a plan that will combine a mixture of various methods, including the combat air patrol over specified areas, intermittent combat air patrol on random orders and various levels of strip alerts."
"strip alert" means that planes are kept in readiness for emergent take-off at any time.
she also said that the alert will be adjusted at any time according to the level of threat.
palestinian suicide bomber blew up bus, 7 dead and 30 injured
(jerusalem, syndicated news) the police said that a suicide bomber carrying explosives on himself blew up a bus near the israeli arab town of umm al fahm, killing 7 people and injuring about 30.
the passengers on the bus were mainly israeli arabs.
the palestinian islamic jihad has claimed responsibility for this attack.
the palestinian authority has condemned this violence.
this is the most serious attack since zinni, the us special envoy to the middle east, arrived last thursday in the middle east in an effort to bring about a cease-fire agreement between the israelis and the palestinians.
a spokesman for the bus company said: "the suicide bomber set off the explosives he was carrying on him in the back of the bus.
the bus was filled to capacity at the time. it was travelling from tel aviv to the northern israeli town of nazareth. "
the spokesman added that most of the passengers were israeli arabs on their way to work.
the explosion took place near the "green line" that separates israel and the west bank.
this attack brought up the death toll of palestinians to 1,562 since they launched an uprising in september of two years ago.
us senator: smallpox-infected terrorists can spread disease at airport
(washington, ap) the us senator dr. frist warned at a hearing on biochemical weapons the day before yesterday that smallpox-infected terrorists can spread the deadly virus or bacteria at airports and make the virus circulate in the entire country. this may cause thousands or even millions of deaths.
when a smallpox-infected terrorist enters into an airport, frist said at the hearing, he can spread the virus to ten innocent passengers through coughing, sneezing or even merely breathing. these ten passengers can in turn spread the virus all over the nation, causing thousands or even millions of deaths through the disease.
he said this is one of the possible forms of weapons of mass destruction.
it does not have to be launched by a missile, nor will it attract the attention like anthrax.
those infected victims and the defense personnel in charge of preventing this kind of weapon may never even know where these viruses (bacteria) come from.
experts told senate foreign relations committee: that is the part of the reason why biochemical weapons are so dangerous.
biden, chairman of senate foreign relations committee, said that preventing biochemical attacks is "an extremely urgent issue that must be taken care of."
senator helms, the committee's most senior republican, said that in order to prevent enemy missiles carrying any kind of warhead from attacking the united states, the united states still needs to build up its missile defense system.
hundreds of thousands of us and south korean soldiers to launch large-scale military exercise
(seoul, afp) on thursday, hundreds of thousands of us and south korean soldiers will launch a largest military exercise in history which will simulate a conflict with north korea. pyongyang angrily labeled it as a provocation of war.
the us officers said on the eve of the week-long military exercise that the drill is purely defensive in nature, but it just takes place after south korean authorities warned that the danger of north korea is not to be ignored.
this is the largest-scale military exercise since the 1950-53 korean war. as no formal agreement has been signed to end the conflict in the korean peninsular, the place has become the last front of the cold war in the world. about 2 million soldiers are facing each other across the border.
the us-south korean combined forces command (cfc) in seoul said that the military exercise from march 21 to march 27 will be testing for the first time the effectiveness of combining two different joint military exercises.
this means hundreds of thousands of soldiers will participate, but the military did not reveal any details.
the cfc spokesman said this exercise will mobilize almost every us and south korean military unit in the korean peninsular and the us military from the outside.
37,000 american soldiers are permanently stationed in south korea to prevent 1.1 million north korean soldiers from attacking the south.
south korea also has 650,000 soldiers.
the cfc named this exercise rs0i/fe02, a combination of computerized military exercise with the annual "foal eagle" exercise.
in the past few years, 500,000 south korean soldiers and 30,000 us soldiers were mobilized for rs0i exercise alone (including 20,000 us soldiers from the outside).
north korea accused the united states of launching the military exercise with an intention to provoke the war.
the official newspaper rodong sinmun even called the us-south korean joint military exercise a "declaration of war."
chinese media praises strategic missile corps
(beijing, afp) among the disputes over the us "nuclear posture review" that lists china as a target for potential nuclear attacks, china's government media praised its own strategic missile corps yesterday.
"pla daily," "people's daily" and other government newspapers all carried at the front page "forging a shield of peace for the republic" in high praises of china's second artillery corps that includes strategic missile and nuclear weapon units.
the article describes that this force uses "a strategic missile training simulation system" that simulates a nuclear attack from a hostile nation and the retaliation by the "red force", or china.
the "red force" uses modern procedures to rapidly design a war plan and deploy new types of mobile missile launchers to remote mountains and forests.
the article filled with technical jargons describes how the second artillery corps uses novel anti-jamming and anti-reconnaissance technologies to display their magic prowess.
the article goes on to say that one missile after another "rises into the sky from remote mountains and accurately hits its target," making the counter-attack a success.
with an estimated strength of 100,000 troopers, the second artillery corps is china's core unit in its effort to enhance the military capabilities and technologies.
this article that summarizes the growth of china's missile and nuclear weapon units from the late 1950s to the present is published at a time of renewed tensions between china and the united states.
china steps up security in embassy district to prevent north koreans from "storming embassies" again
(hong kong) the chinese police recently conducted an internal review over the incident that 25 north koreans stormed the spanish embassy last week.
it is estimated that in beijing alone, more than 150 north koreans are waiting for their chances to go to south korea. the authorities have stepped up security on major embassies such as those of south korea, japan and western nations in the embassy district so as to prevent "storming" incidents from happening again.
singtao reported yesterday that public security sources indicated that since 25 north koreans stormed the spanish embassy by surprise on march 14, beijing police, in addition to the increased security it has provided to those embassies of sensitive nations, has further stepped up protection for the embassies of non-sensitive nations while maintaining a closer contact with the officials of north korean and south korean embassies in beijing.
the sources pointed out, staff from the south korean embassy indicated to the chinese officials that south korea does not encourage north koreans to go to south korea through this means and south korea does not hope to see similar incidents again so that the relations between china and the korean peninsula are not affected. south korea also promises china that it will assist china in managing the south korean residents in beijing.
it is disclosed that about 10,000 ethnic koreans live in the eastern district of beijing and liangmahe in chaoyang district. among them are ethnic koreans from northeast china and those from north and south koreas. they are mainly engaged in korean style restaurant and bar businesses. since they belong to the same korean ethnic group, they get along quite well with each other no matter where they come from.
in the past, the authorities did not consider the ethnic koreans as the focus of their supervision because they were not big in number in beijing, nor did they get involved in so many criminal offenses like those people from xinjiang and henan.
it is reported that after the march 14 incident, the public security agency first "invited" the german doctor who assisted those 25 north koreans for a "talk" at the public security agency and then escorted him to the airport for immediate departure from china.
afterwards, the public security agency and the national security agency started an internal review.
the review mainly consists of two parts: the security protection of the embassy district and the management of the ethnic koreans in beijing.
in addition, the authorities also required the relevant agencies in regions such as jilin to take effective measures to prevent north koreans who have illegally crossed the border from entering beijing.
yellow sanddust eclipsing sun over korean peninsula, dust covers skies over pyongyang and seoul
(syndicated news from pyongyang and seoul) the sandstorm that just swept across northern china hit the korean peninsula violently yesterday. most of the regions, including pyongyang, capital of north korea and seoul, capital of south korea, were enveloped in a brownish dusty haze.
according to xinhua news agency, a strong sandstorm hit pyongyang early yesterday morning.
from early in the morning, the entire city of pyongyang was enveloped in a yellow dust.
this is the first sandstorm to hit north korea since this spring.
six airlines suspended flights
it is also reported by peopleweb in beijing that large areas in south korea were hit by "sandstorms" yesterday. except inchon international airport, flights of six domestic airlines were suspended.
"sandstorms" occurred in south korea nation-wide.
according to the tests by the south korean ministry of environment, the content of fine dust in the air in seoul before yesterday's noon already exceeded the average by 17 times, hitting 1,000 micrograms per cubic meter, the highest record in history.
affected by the dusty weather nation-wide, except inchon international airport that still keeps its normal operation, six domestic airlines routes such as daqiu, weishan, puxiang in south korea were suspended. passengers of more than 30 flights changed their means of transportation.
it is also reported by ap that due to the high concentration of dust in air, the south korean government yesterday ordered all the kindergartens and elementary schools in the country to close temporarily for a day so that children will not be affected by the air pollution.
dusty weather has so far occurred three times in seoul, south korea this year.
the south korea meteorological administration forecast yesterday: "large quantities of dust lifted up by a strong uprising current of air occurring in the desert areas of china and mongolia permeate the air over northern china and will travel with the northwesterly wind to pass through south korea."
asteroid powerful enough to destroy mid-size city brushed by earth
(florida, melbourne, ap) an asteroid large enough to destroy a mid-size city brushed the earth within a short distance of 463,000 km without being detected in advance. astronomers did not know the event until four days later.
about 50 meters in diameter, the asteroid came from the direction of the sun, making it very difficult for astronomers to discover it.
the asteroid brushed by the earth on march 8, but by the time it was discovered on march 12, the asteroid had gone far away.
williams from the international astronomical union's minor planet center located in cambridge, massachusetts had helped locate the position of the asteroid.
from the astronomical perspective, this asteroid is very close to the earth, because the moon is 402,000 km away from the earth.
williams told "florida today" on wednesday: "it is of critical importance the asteroid should have been detected before it came from the direction of the sun."
in this way, astronomers will be able to verify the orbit of the asteroid as soon as possible and predict whether it will bump into the earth.
in 1908 when an asteroid about the same size hit the earth, it caused a pit as wide as 32 kilometers in the forests of siberia.
interior minister confirms senior italian government advisor shot by "red brigade"
(rome, afp) italian interior minister scajola confirmed the day before yesterday that the senior italian government advisor biagi was shot to death by a branch unit of the extremist left-wing guerrilla "red brigade."
scajola said, the two men who killed biagi even used the same pistol that was used to carry out a similar political assassination three years ago.
on the other hand, after biagi's assassination, the italian prime minister berlusconi offered to invite the labor union leaders back to the negotiation table and to discuss the employment reform plan he proposed.
biagi, the 52-year-old advisor for the ministry of labor, was also an economist and law professor.
he was killed by a gunman on a motorcycle when he was riding his bike back to his home in the northern city of bologna. the shooting shocked the italian political circle.
biagi had assisted in drafting an employment reform plan that was strongly opposed by the labor union and the leftists.
they believed the plan would make it easier for employers to fire workers.
eyewitnesses said that biagi was lying in a pool of blood alongside his briefcase.
the door of biagi's home was also found to be carved with a red brigade symbol of five stars, but at this time it is not clear when the symbol was carved.
established in 1973, red brigade was suspected in many bombings and assassinations in italy during the 70s and 80s, including the abduction and murder of the former prime minister moro in 1978.
chinese american engineer sentenced to 5-year imprisonment for illegally obtaining china's state secrets and bribery
(beijing, ap) beijing no.1 intermediate people's court yesterday sentenced the chinese american engineer fang fuming to 5 years in prison on charges of illegally obtaining state secrets and bribing on behalf of a company.
the case had aroused protests from the united states.
the spokesman for the us embassy in china said that fang fuming will be deported from china after he serves his time.
the time of his sentence will be adjusted according to the time he has already served.
the us embassy had sent a diplomat to attend the hearing.
the attorney representing fang fuming said that his client has already been imprisoned for two years, but china said it was not that long.
xinhua news agency confirmed the ruling.
it said, from 1995 to 1999, fang fuming obtained 35 documents containing state secrets and gave 245,000 us dollars (about 450,000 singapore dollars in current value) in bribes to state workers to assist foreign investors bidding for china's power construction projects.
fang fuming was an electrical engineering consultant for a foreign company in its china and other asian offices.
cohen, the attorney representing fang fuming, said that fang fuming denied giving bribes and said he was a victim to the embezzling chinese officials in the power industry.
once a chinese official in the power industry, fang fuming became a us citizen in 1994.
in the past two years, a number of us citizens and residents were accused of violating the chinese national security laws. fang fuming was one of them.
the arrest of fang fuming had temporarily caused tensions between china and the united states.
the us government repeatedly protested against the way china handled the case of fang fuming, accusing the chinese authorities of violating the international norms by detaining fang fuming for several months without any trial.
the family members of fang fuming said he was badly treated.
his wife and two children are all us citizens.
cohen said, fang fuming was detained on february 28, 2000, but the date of custody set by the chinese foreign ministry is august 28, 2000.
china called off naval fleet's visit to the us, declined to confirm whether hu jintao will visit us as planned
(beijing, syndicated news) the sino-us relation that was heated momentarily by the us president bush's visit to china is cooling down rapidly. china confirmed yesterday that it has called off its naval fleet visit to the us ports this year and refused to confirm whether the country's vice president hu jintao will visit the united states as planned.
the foreign ministry spokeswoman zhang qiyue said while answering reporters' questions at a routine press conference: "as far as i know, china's naval fleet is preparing for a visit as planned; its itinerary does not include the us ports."
when a reporter asked her twice whether hu jintao's plan to visit the united states is affected and whether she can clarify that an earlier answer can be interpreted as an indication that hu jintao will visit the us in april as scheduled, zhang qiyue would not make any further comments nor would she confirm anything.
zhang qiyue only repeatedly accused the us of "doing a series of things that violate the three joint communiques between china and the us" within a short period of one month after president bush's visit to china and demanded that the us "stop using the issue of taiwan to interfere in china's internal affairs."
on the other hand, in washington d.c., the us ignored on wednesday china's warning that a "chilly wind" is blowing over the sino-us relations and insisted that there is nothing wrong with the us permission of taiwan's defense minister to attend "us-taiwan defense summit" held in florida.
beijing repeatedly attacked the us for issuing a visa to taiwan's defense minister tang yiau-ming earlier this month and allowing him to attend a conference sponsored by the us arms manufacturers.
tang yiau-ming also met with two senior us officials at the time.
at a routine press conference, state department spokesman boucher was hounded by reporters asking about china's complaints over this issue, but obviously he was trying his best to avoid a battle of words with china.
he said: "after this meeting, our position is well-known to all.
if you want to ask me about this every day, i am willing to explain it every day. if china wants to ask about this every day, we are willing to explain it every day."
he said: "the position hasn't changed. these are our normal contacts with the taiwanese. we will continue to do so."
zhang qiyue also confirmed yesterday the russian media's report, saying that the chinese president jiang zemin called the russian president putin by phone at his request the night before, and both sides exchanged their opinions on cooperations between china and russia based on mutual benefits.
both sides believe it is in the interest of both nations and peoples to develop mutually beneficial cooperations between china and russia.
Scientists Complete Sequencing of the Chromosome Linked to Early Dementia
(AFP, Paris, January 2)  An international team of scientists said that they have completed the sequencing of human Chromosome 14 that is linked to many diseases, including the early-onset Alzheimer's that may strike people in their 30s.
This is the fourth chromosome whose sequence has been completed to date.  It comprises more than 87 million pairs of DNA.
This study published in the weekly British scientific journal Nature illustrates that the sequence of Chromosome 14 comprises 1,050 genes and gene fragments.
The goal of geneticists is to provide diagnostic tools to identify defective genes that cause diseases so as to arrive eventually at treatments that can prevent those genes from malfunctioning.
The international scientists led by Genoscope, a French gene research center, said that Chromosome 14 contains two clusters of genes that are linked to the function of our immune system and more than 60 disease genes.
Chromosome 14 has been identified in earlier studies on a great number of diseases such as spastic paraplegia that afflicts young children, missing teeth, several forms of vision and hearing impairments and early-onset Alzheimer's.
About 200,000 Americans suffer from early-onset Alzheimer's, accounting for 5% of Alzheimer's patients in the entire United States.
Humans have a total of 23 pairs of chromosomes.
In the past three years, the sequencing of three chromosomes has been completed, including Chromosomes 20, 21, and 22.
Australia Reopens Embassy in Manila
(AFP, Manila, January 2)  Australia reopened its embassy in the Philippines today, which was shut down about seven weeks ago due to what was described as a specific threat of a terrorist attack.
The Philippine Foreign Department said in a statement that Pearce, Australian ambassador to Manila, has telephoned the Philippine Foreign Secretary Ople to announce the resumption of full operations of the embassy.
Like Australia, Canada and the European Union closed their embassies on November 28 and reopened them earlier this week.
Ople said that all three ambassadors are satisfied with the heightened security measures the Philippine government has taken.
The closure of the embassies had angered the Philippine government, which said the alleged threat was exaggerated and the closure of the embassies harmed the image of the Philippines.
Manila fired the police intelligence official because he leaked the unverified intelligence about terrorist threats upon the Australian and Canadian embassies.
The EU office and the Australian embassy are housed in the same building.
Around the anniversary of the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks on the United States, Western diplomatic missions across Southeast Asia shut down one after another because they received threats linked to Osama bin Laden's al-Qaeda network and its regional allies.
Australian Foreign Minister Says North Korea's Bad Behaviors Will not Gain More Aid
(AFP, Sydney, January 2)  Australia has called on the international community to work together to convince North Korea that holding Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty in contempt or other "bad behaviors" will not gain it more aid or other concessions.
Australian Foreign Minister Downer noted today that Pyongyang's decisions to reactivate a controversial nuclear facility and to expel UN monitors are obviously aimed at forcing the international community into making aid and trade concessions.
Australia is one of the few countries that have diplomatic relations with North Korea.
Downer said: "We think what North Korea wants to do is to gain concessions, aid and trade, etc. from the rest of the world, including the United States, by violating the agreed framework signed in 1994."
In an interview with the Australian Broadcasting Cooperation, Downer said: "One point we'd like to make to North Korea and a very important one at that, is that bad behaviors will not be rewarded."
Downer pointed out: "Such behaviors as expelling UN monitors and reactivating the nuclear facility at Yongbyon are going to prevent the international community from providing support."
"It's going to produce the reverse effect.  We hope these diplomatic measures will be effective."
"On the other hand, if we overreact, we will fall for North Korea's trick.
We don't want to do that."
Downer indicated that Australia is working closely with the United States and other major allies to pressure North Korea to cancel its recent steps to reactivate the frozen nuclear program.
Downer said: "What we want to do is to ensure that the international community make concerted efforts.  We don't want to take any uncoordinated special countermeasures."
Bush Defends his Economic Stimulus Package
(AFP, Washington, January 6)  US President Bush vowed that the economic stimulus package he is going to unveil will benefit the "working people," and not just the wealthy.  It is generally believed that the wealthy can expect to benefit the most from this plan that urges dramatic tax cuts.
Bush told reporters who are expecting him to officially announce this package in Chicago: "Tomorrow, all of you will hear me saying: the US economy is one of the strongest in the world.
However, we believe the US economy can be even stronger than it is now."
Bush is expected to unveil an economic stimulus package that carries a 10-year price tag of 600 billion US dollars, half of which will be used towards eliminating taxes on dividends paid to shareholders.  He will also call for accelerating the tax rate cuts approved by the US Congress in 2001.
Whether the package can be smoothly promoted is viewed as the front battle of the 2004 US presidential election.  The Democrats attacked Bush's blueprint as an additional bonus to the wealthy, unlike the Democratic proposal which is intended as an aid to the most needy.
The eight-point proposal put forward by the Democrats centers around an incentive measure of 136 billion US dollars to stimulate consumer spending which will cost 100 billion US dollars over a period of ten years.
House Democratic leader Pelosi said at a joint press conference with other opposition lawmakers: "This is a fair, fast-acting, and fiscally sound plan."
Bush led the White House in refuting the accusation from the media that his package only benefits the wealthy, claiming that the economic stimulus package he is going to unveil is chiefly targeted at "revving up economic vitality and growth."
Bush said: "This package will provide tax relief to the working people.
The idea behind the package is that when people have extra money, they are likely to spend it, which can create more jobs."
US Willing to Negotiate with North Korea but Not to Pay More Compensation
(AFP, Washington, January 7)  The United States expressed today its willingness to negotiate with North Korea, a hostile nation on the "axis of evil," but will not provide any fresh inducements to this financially struggling communist nation so as to make it abandon its nuclear program.
US President Bush's administration is currently facing a double crisis with Iraq and North Korea.  The Bush administration officials issued a statement after their talks with senior Japanese and South Korean diplomats, saying that this signals "a step forward" in the US policy toward Pyongyang.
The statement said: "The US delegation is willing to talk with North Korea about how it should meet its obligation to the international community.
However, the US delegation emphasized that the United States will not provide any compensation for North Korea to live up to its existing obligation."
The US officials insisted with carefully worded diplomatic rhetoric that although they are willing to negotiate with North Korea, they will not consider any negotiation procedures before North Korea abides by various agreements on banning nuclear weapons.
The State Department spokesman Boucher said: "We are not willing to pay again for the agreements that have been reached already."
Before that, the Bush administration indicated that the United States will refuse to have talks with North Korea before this Stalinist nation abandons its nuclear program based on enriched uranium and plutonium.
Former Executive of a US Online Real Estate Company to Plead Guilty to Fraud Charges
(AFP, Los Angeles)  Prosecutors said that a former chief executive of "Homestore," a US online real estate company, has agreed to plead guilty to fraud charges and reached a settlement over the lawsuit that originated from the insider trading scandal.
Special Assistant US Attorney Wilner said that Kalina, Homestore's former senior manager of mergers and acquisitions, has entered a plea bargain deal and agreed to plead guilty to one count of securities fraud involving insider trading.
Fuchs, another prosecutor, said that Kalina also agreed to pay 70,000 US dollars to settle a civil lawsuit against him by the US Securities and Exchange Commission.
Wilner said that the maximum sentence for securities fraud can be ten years of imprisonment.  However, according to the plea bargain deal, the aforementioned term is expected to be "dramatically shortened."
The prosecutors and investigators pointed out, in the financial fraud scheme in which Kalina was involved, Homestore's chief executives misled investors by overstating the 2001 revenues.
Fuchs said, when Kalina became aware of the artificially inflated stock price, he dumped his Homestore shares to make a profit.  "The Wall Street wasn't aware that the key portion of Homestore's revenues was bogus."
Desimone, Homestore's former vice president who has been charged with similar insider trading, has pleaded guilty.  The court is scheduled to announce sentencing on April 21.
Homestore's Chief Operating Officer Giesecke and former Chief Financial Officer Joseph Shew have pleaded guilty to conspiracy to commit securities fraud.
Prosecutors said that Giesecke and Joseph Shew, together with other company chief executives, have been charged with overstating revenues by falsifying Homestore's accounting.
Days of Heavy Snow in Europe Left Many Dead and Transportation Disrupted
(AFP, Vienna, January 8)  Days of heavy snow, low temperatures from Siberia as well as high winds across Europe have caused many deaths while disrupting road, rail, air and sea traffic.
The temperatures in Moscow, capital of Russia, dropped to such low levels last night that even locals felt freezing cold.  Six people died as a result, bringing up the death toll due to coldness this year to 239.  Most of the dead were the homeless and the elderly, including many who were drunk.
Three people died last night in Lithuania, and many others had to have their legs and fingers amputated due to frost bites.
The temperatures in Varena region in the south of the country plummeted to a new low of minus 32.6 degrees Celsius in 16 years.
In Slovakia, three illegal immigrants from India also died of cold and exhaustion on Monday when the local temperatures dropped to minus 20 degrees Celsius.
In the meantime, civil defense services across the European continent and beyond all indicated that snowfalls have blocked roads, delayed trains and paralyzed airports.
Frozen railroad points and road accidents in Britain have paralyzed transportation in some areas.  Heavy snow, after covering the eastern region, is now moving westward.
In the Czech Republic, which was ravaged by serious floods last summer, the temperatures in its border region adjacent to neighboring Slovakia plunged to minus 18 degrees Celsius.
Worldwatch Institute Praises Environmental Revolution
(AFP, Washington, January 9)  In its annual report "State of the World," Worldwatch Institute, an environmental research organization, praised with unusual optimism the advent of "environmental revolution," pointing out that many countries are successfully curbing or solving environmental, health and social problems.
Flavin, head of Worldwatch Institute, said on the 9th: "Building a world that not only meets our needs but also allows future generations to enjoy a healthy society is no longer a day dream."
This edition of State of the World report points out that one of the encouraging achievements is the increasing use of renewable energies such as "solar energy and wind power" in Germany, Japan and Spain.
Speaking about the success of promoting the strategy of renewable energies, Flavin said: "We're entering a new era."
The above-mentioned report says that in the 1990s, the worldwide production of chlorofluorocarbons, "the No. 1 culprit in destroying the ozone layer," has decreased by 81%.
In addition, the anti-polio campaigns promoted by the World Health Organization have reduced polio cases globally from 350,000 in 1988 to 480 in 2001.
This Washington-based environmental research organization also praised local successes in environmental protection.  For example, the Netherlands has achieved an 86 percent recycling rate for automobiles; Denmark has totally banned the use of aluminum cans in favor of recyclable glass bottles; and Brazil has been using renewable energies since 2001.
The organization's report says that the past achievements have brought hopes for relieving serious global threats, which include malaria that claims 7,000 lives every day, and the food, air, and water pollution that leads to the untimely deaths of 5,500 children every day.
AOL Time Warner Chairman Case to Resign in May
(AFP, Washington, January 12)  AOL Time Warner Chairman Case announced tonight that he will resign in May, saying that this move is "the best for the company."
While explaining his decision, Case said that he has decided on the steps to take in order to prevent shareholders' criticism of him from "hindering our ability to cooperate as a team and to focus fully on our businesses."
Case, who oversaw America Online's merger with Time Warner which was approved by the US Federal Trade Commission in January 2001, will remain as a board member of AOL Time Warner.
The merger was valued at 155 billion US dollars when it was announced in January 2000.  The merger was approved by the European policy makers later that year.
Case said in a statement: "As you expected, this decision is personally very difficult for me, because I hoped to serve as chairman of this conglomerate for years to come.  And as an architect of the merger, I have always thought it was important that I stay as chairman and help get things back on track."
He stressed: "First of all, this company does not need uneasiness at this critical moment.  As some shareholders still focus their dissappointment with the company's post-merger performance on me personally, I have decided that we should take steps now to prevent it from hindering our cooperation as a team and to focus fully on our businesses."
AOL Time Warner's Internet arm, America Online, said that it expects its advertising and commerce sales for 2002 to drop to between 1.5 to 1.6 billion US dollars from  2.7 billion in 2001.
Whereas, the total revenue will be between 8.8 to 9 billion US dollars against the 8.718 billion US dollars in the preceding year.
The company estimates that America Online's total revenue for 2003 will remain about the same as that in 2002, while revenues from advertising and commerce sales will drop by 40-50%.
North Korea Withdraws from Nuclear Non-Poliferation Treaty to Defy the Entire World
(AFP, Washington, January 15)  The showdown between the United States and North Korea has escalated from such peripheral issues as "the axis of evil" to an international crisis, threatening to ruin decades of global efforts at nuclear non-proliferation.
Pyongyang declared its withdrawal from the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty on the 10th of this month, resulting in a stand-off with Washington.
Analysts said that at present, the global efforts aimed at nuclear non-proliferation are threatened with failure.  The treaty has already been seriously undermined when the non-signatories India and Pakistan joined the nuclear club in 1998.
Four days after Pyongyang made the above move, five permanent members of the UN Security Council have all taken preventive diplomatic actions on this crisis.
Russia said it will send a special envoy to Pyongyang to suggest an end to this stalemate, while China proposed that the United States and North Korea hold a dialog to reach a compromise.
Meanwhile, in London, Britain and France are discussing this crisis.
International Atomic Energy Agency has warned that if North Korea refuses to abandon its nuclear program, the agency may request the Security Council to take actions.
As far as Russia's and China's moves are concerned, many US observers think such talks may force Moscow and Beijing to decide whether or not to vote against North Korea.
Other countries with nuclear capabilities, such as Iran and Libya, will surely be on close watch for the development of North Korea crisis.
They would notice that North Korea withdraws from the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty with impunity, or gets huge sums of funds from the United States in exchange that it stop developing nuclear weapons.
Einhorn, a former arms control official of the State Department, said: "If North Korea is considered capable of withdrawing from the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, they may figure they can make the same move without paying any cost."
Noland from the Institute for International Economics believes that North Korea may have made a tactical mistake because its decision to withdraw from the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty will make the international community more determined than ever to resolve this issue.
Japanese Court Rejects Multi-million-yen Compensation Lawsuit by Former Chinese Slave Laborers
(AFP, Tokyo, January 15)  A Japanese court today rejected a 132 million yen (1.1 million US dollars) compensation lawsuit filed by six Chinese who were forced to work as slave laborers in a nickel mine in Japan during World War II.
Kyoto District Court Judge Shin Kusumoto said that although what the government and Nippon Yakin Kogyo Co. did in 1944 jointly was illegal, he rejected this lawsuit based on the Civil Law that allows a 20-year statute of limitations.
Kusumoto said: "The defendants' obligation has expired."
Five former Chinese slave laborers, including the 72-year-old Liu Zonggen and a family member of a deceased slave laborer, have sought unpaid wages, compensations and apologies from the Japanese government and Nippon Yakin Kogyo Co.
The six people worked as slave laborers for Nippon Yakin for a period of one year during which they were often beaten up and poorly fed and clad.
Nippon Yakin argued that the company was in no position to oppose the national policy, while the Japanese government, on the other hand, said it has no need to provide compensation to the plaintiffs according to the constitution at that time.
Jiji Press reported that after the court announced its ruling, Liu Zonggen said at a press conference: "This is an inhumane ruling."
He said they will file an appeal.
Liu Zonggen said: "I've got the support from many Japanese friends.  I'll fight to the end."
The plaintiffs' attorney pointed out that this ruling "violates the historical record," and demanded that the Japanese government and Nippon Yakin pay compensations and offer apologies to resolve the issue.
Kyodo News reported that this is the first time such argument has been rejected in lawsuits involving war compensation.
In 1944, the Japanese military abducted about 200 Chinese and then sent them to work as slave laborers in Oe Mountain Nickel Mine in Kaya Cho, Kyoto Prefecture.
Alcatel Says Sales in Fourth Quarter Last Year Grew Nearly 30%
(AFP, Paris)  Alcatel, the French telecommunication equipment manufacturing giant hit hard by the downturn in the telecom sector, said that its sales in the fourth quarter of 2002 should show a growth of nearly 30% over the preceding quarter.
The sales growth reflects the stronger-than-expected seasonal factors as well as the sustained sales of the broadband and mobile infrastructure equipment.
Alcatel noted that after taking into account reserves on inventories of 150 million euros (158.4 million US dollars), the fourth quarter income from operations will be around the break-even point.
Alcatel issued a statement saying that cost-cutting measures are being carried out as planned.
The stock market in Paris welcomed Alcatel's announcement, and Alcatel shares surged by 16.91% to 6.5 euros in the early afternoon trading.
Balcon, an analyst with Global Equities, said: "The upward revision in the fourth-quarter sales figures came particularly unexpected."
Alcatel's Chairman Serge Tchuruk said he still expects Alcatel to reduce the break-even point to 3 billion euros by the end of 2003, which means profitability can be achieved with less sales.
Alcatel added that the company's annual income will be announced on February 4.
Japan Unlikely to Expect a Real Growth of 1.5% until 2006
(AFP, Tokyo)  Nihon Keizai Shimbun reported today the Council on Economic and Fiscal Policy (CEFP) of the Japanese government has deferred the estimated time for Japan's economy to reach a real growth of over 1.5% by two years to fiscal 2006.
CEFP also forecasts that in the next five years the total issuance of annual government bonds will reach 40 trillion yen due to the longer-than-expected time it takes to reduce budget deficits.
The report said that the mid-term economic outlook that aims at mapping out the guidelines for the economic and fiscal operations for the next five years is scheduled to be finalized on the 20th of this month.
The mid-term economic outlook report was worked out in early January last year, and CEFP is currently working on its revision which is expected to be approved at the Cabinet meeting by the end of this month.
It is reported that the current edition of the mid-term economic outlook report and a test calculation done by the Cabinet expect a real growth of 1.5% for fiscal 2004 and a nominal growth of 2.7% for fiscal 2005.
However, the revised edition projects the real growth rate in 2004 will be only 0.9% and the nominal growth rate only 0.8%.
The report said the revised edition also forecasts that a real growth rate of 1.5% or over will not materialize until fiscal 2006.
A nominal growth rate of 2.5% or more will not occur until fiscal 2007, postponing the original dates by two years.
The report pointed out the revised outlook also extends the timetable to end deflation by two years.
Australia Faces Most Devastating Bush Fires in 50 Years; 1 Feared Dead
(AFP, Sydney, January 18)  Bush fires are ravaging Australia, having destroyed nearly 40 homes as of today, and are threatening residential houses in the suburbs around the capital city of Canberra.  With gusty winds and rising temperatures, the fires are expected to spread further.
Australian officials said that according to unconfirmed reports, the blaze that has spread to dozens of suburban towns of Canberra and other areas in the ACT has already left one person dead and several missing.
Brown, an officer with the Federal Police, said that the police are trying to verify the report that at least one person has died in the inferno, but some people have already been confirmed missing.
As strong winds have fanned the bush fires out of control in the northern, southern and western mountainous areas in Canberra, the ACT authorities have declared a state of emergency today for the entire region.
On the other hand, fire service authorities said as bush fires are approaching heavily populated areas, the military has been called in to join thousands of firefighters in putting out the fires.
Threatened by the bush fires that some officials described as the most devastating in 50 years, rural town residents in the mountainous regions within the Snowy Mountains in New South Wales and Kosciuszko National Park have all been immediately evacuated.
Rural Fire Service Commissioner Koperberg said: "It is a serious situation.  The Snowy Mountains may be facing the most serious threat in 50 years."  Over a thousand firefighters are fighting a losing battle, unable to prevent the blaze from engulfing the 80,000 hectares of bushland in New South Wales.
Japanese Emperor Akihito's Surgery to Remove Cancerous Prostate Gland Successful
(AFP, Tokyo, January 18)  Japanese Emperor Akihito underwent surgery today to have his cancerous prostate gland removed.  Doctors of the imperial household said the operation went smoothly and the cancer cells didn't seem to have spread to other organs.
Ichiro Kanazawa, medical supervisor of the Imperial Household, said at a press conference held at University of Tokyo Hospital: "The operation went smoothly as planned and was successfully completed.
His Majesty has waked up from anesthesia and had a few words with Empress Michiko and Princess Sayako."
He added: "Judging from appearances, we don't think the (cancer) has spread."
Kanazawa said that doctors will perform additional tests to make sure that the cancer is limited to prostate gland only.
The surgery, jointly performed by six doctors, lasted 3 hours and 40 minutes and removed Akihito's entire prostate gland.
The 69-year-old Akihito assumed the throne in 1989, and this is the first time ever that an emperor has undergone an operation at a hospital other than the Hospital of the Imperial Household.
Doctors said that Akihito is scheduled to recuperate for about a month.
Kanazawa indicated as Akihito did not bleed much during the operation, the doctors used his own blood for transfusion.
Prior to the operation, the doctors stored Akihito' blood in advance.  The quantity is not specified.
Chief Cabinet Secretary Yasuo Fukuda said that the government is relieved with the emperor's successful surgery and hopes for his recovery at the earliest time.
Shortly before Akihito was admitted to hospital, government officials said, the 42-year-old Crown Prince Naruhito had assumed the emperor's constitutional duties on a temporary basis.
This is the first time that a Japanese emperor has transferred his duties due to hospitalization.
Philippines Masses Troops to Combat Threats of Communist Guerrilla
(AFP, Manila, January 20)  The Philippine security forces are massing various units in order to combat the numerous attacks by the communist guerrilla in some areas of this Southeast Asian archipelago.
Brigadier General Purificacion said today that the New People's Army is "attempting to mass troops in some areas," including the northern Philippines, provinces south of Manila and some central islands.
He added: "They are intensifying attacks on some areas that they think are weak in military strength," or "attacking and harassing the troops in scarcely populated areas."
Other officials said that the NPA has intensified attacks on the so-called "soft" targets such as telecommunications and power facilities.
Last week, the national police chief Ebdane required the telecommunications firms to invest hundreds of millions of US dollars in security protection to guard against the NPA attacks.
Purificacion said: "The armed forces have redeployed more troops in areas most prone to threats."
Purificacion said the number of the NPA troops has declined at least 23% to about 9,000 from 12,000 to 13,000 two years ago.
At least 5,000 of them are "armed regulars," which were about 6,000 in early 2001.
He said the government forces repelled them from more than 400 villages where the NPA frequented.
He said: "We're slowly but steadily winning back people's confidence."
National security advisor Golez said last week that the serious political and military setbacks the NPA suffered would force it and its mother organization, the Communist Party of the Philippines, back to the negotiation table.
After the rebels assassinated two Philippine legislators, Philippine President Arroyo ceased negotiations with the communist party in mid 2001.
Last year, the United States included the NPA and the CPP in its international blacklist of "foreign terrorist organizations."
Washington, Canada, and many Western European governments also agreed to track down and stop the foreign funding sources of the rebel troops and freeze their overseas assets.
Growth of Mobile Phone Users in Mainland China to Slow Down
(AFP, Beijing, January 21)  This year, the number of new mobile phone users in mainland China is expected to decrease to 52 million.
It was 61.9 million last year.
However, Beijing Morning Post, citing the forecast by the Ministry of Information Industry, said that the target may be underestimated.
In January last year, the Ministry of Information Industry forecast that there would be 55 million new mobile subscribers that year, but the actual figure turned out to be 61.9 million.
There were 206.6 million mobile phone users in mainland China at the end of last year, up 42.7% from the previous year.
Beijing noted that mainland China became the largest fixed-line and mobile phone market in the world in July last year.
The year before that, the number of mobile phone users alone already topped the world.
The report said that in the meantime, Wu Jichuan, minister of Information Industry, projected that the decline of investment in the fixed assets in post and telecommunication industry last year will come to an end this year, but the amount of investment may remain the same.
Last year, the investment in the fixed assets of post and telecommunication industry fell by 20% to 210.6 billion yuan.
Investment by telecom companies accounted for 97% of the total investment.
Wu Jichuan predicted that this year, investment in the fixed assets of post and telecommunication industry will reach 210 billion yuan, slightly less than that of last year.
The report said that the Ministry of Information Industry forecasts that the number of new fixed-line phone users this year will be 33 million, below the 35.40 million last year.
At the end of December last year, the number of the fixed-line phone users in mainland China reached 214.4 million, up 35 million from the previous year.
Wu Jichuan also pledged to boost competition and speed up the establishment of a telecom regulator.
He said: "The optimization of telecom regulations has become the most crucial issue in the industry.
We will accelerate the drafting of telecommunications laws and revise the postal laws and the regulations on wireless telecommunications."
WHO Starts to Elect New Director-General
(AFP, Geneva, January 21)  The nomination for the World Health Organization's new director-general will unfold in the coming week.  Mocumbi, prime minister of Mozambique, Piot, the Belgian who heads the UN AIDS prevention agency, and Jong-Wook Lee, a tuberculosis specialist of South Korea, are the three most likely people to come through.
The WHO executive board meeting will start from today to eliminate the number of candidates to five and nominate one person on January 28 to succeed Ms. Brundtland, the Norwegian who will soon leave her post as director-general.
However, the nominee will still need to be finally confirmed by the WHO's 192 member states in May.
Diplomatic officials said that of the candidates running for the director-general, three are most promising: Mocumbi, prime minister of Mozambique, Piot, UNAIDS executive director, and Jong-Wook Lee, director of WHO's Stop TB program.
According to an unofficial rule, the United Nations always tries its best to let people from different parts of the world serve as directors of its chief agencies.
Some Western diplomats admit that Piot, as a European, has been at a disadvantage from the very beginning.
A diplomat said: "Now it's time for people from southern nations to take the lead."
Robert Redford Calls on Independent Filmmakers to Help Protect Freedom of Speech
(AFP, Park City, Utah, January 20)  Amid the US-led war against terror, Robert Redford, the screen icon, called on independent filmmakers to help prevent the freedom of speech from being eroded.
Yesterday, at his Sundance Independent Film Festival, Redford spoke out candidly for the freedom of citizens both at home and abroad.  His remark was obviously an indirect attack on the Bush administration's policies.
Redford warned that the US freedom of speech and other basic rights are under threat, but independent movies can help keep alternative artistic and political views alive.
He said: "One of the virtues of independent filmmaking is that it is not only unburdened by commercial dogmas but it also is not restricted in expressing different points of view."
Redford, founder of the Sundance Film Festival, said that he is planning to revise the rules for this annual independent filmmakers' festival so that their works can be shown in major US cities.
Park City, Utah, has been hosting this film festival for 22 years.
Redford, who starred in "Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid" and "All The President's Men," said: "Freedom of speech is our most precious virtue, and we must keep it in mind to guard it well."
OPEC Founder: War on Iraq will Cause Oil Price to Soar up to 100 Dollars
(AFP, Doha, January 21)  According to Yamani, former minister of oil of Saudi Arabia, if Iraq sets the oil fields on fire in the event of a US-led war, the price of crude oil will soar up to 100 US dollars a barrel.
This OPEC co-founder said last night that Hussein "will destroy Iraqi oil wells, which will lead to the decline of the strategic oil reserve and cause the oil price per barrel to soar up to anywhere between 80 and 100 US dollars."
He said at a press conference in Doha, capital of Qarta, that if the United States "attacks Iraq, it may trigger a global disaster."
He further pointed out: "Bombing the oil reserve and oil industry in Iraq may lead to a dramatic rise in crude oil price to the range of 80-100 US dollars."
Yamani said: "(The US) military actions against Iraq will destroy the oil wells and cause serious turmoils in Iraq.  Consequently, the oil price will surge, which will lead to a global recession."
North Korean Delegation: North Korea has no Intention of Making Nuclear Weapons
(AFP, Seoul)  South Korean officials said that the North Korean delegation to the inter-Korean ministerial talks indicated today that North Korea has no intention of making nuclear weapons.
Rhee Bong-Jo, a spokesman for the South Korean delegation, said: "North Korea emphatically pointed out that it has no intention of making nuclear weapons."
While briefing on the first official talks that lasted an hour, Rhee Bong-Jo noted that the North Korean delegation made the above remark after South Korea urged the Pyongyang regime to abandon its nuclear ambition.
Rhee Bong-Jo said: "South Korea stressed there will be no further progress in the entire inter-
Rhee Bong-Jo added: "Through this round of talks, we hope to persuade North Korea to take more concrete steps," and reverse its decision to reactivate the nuclear facility that is capable of producing weapons-grade plutonium.
The focus of this inter-Korean ministerial talk is on peaceful reconciliation and humanitarian issues, but South Korea, as a traditional US ally, has already indicated that Seoul authorities have decided to use this opportunity of inter-Korean talks to express the international concern over the nuclear stand-off.
North Korea claimed that the nuclear stand-off is a bilateral issue involving only the United States, and the intervention of other nations will only make the issue more complicated.
Largest US Chain Retailer Kmart May See Profit Sooner
(AFP, Troy, Michigan, January 26)  Kmart Corp, the largest chain retailer in the United States, said that after a year of restructuring, the company will get out of bankruptcy and return to profitability by 2004.
The reorganization plan that Kmart Corp. proposed the day before yesterday mainly relies on two investment firms, ESL Investments Inc. controlled by the millionaire Lampert of Connecticut and Third Avenue Value Fund of New York.  The two investment firms are going to invest 352 million US dollars to bail out Kmart Corp.
However, the reorganization plan is not yet approved by the creditor banks, investors and suppliers.
The chain retailer with a history of a century said that it will continue to communicate with the creditor's committee and hope to emerge from bankruptcy before April 30.
US FBI, the SEC and the House Committee on Energy and Commerce are investigating Kmart Corp. on grounds that its top executives are suspected of financial fraud.
The company's board of directors is also conducting internal investigations and noted the night before that it has found "reliable and convincing evidence" that show ten chief executives violated management responsibilities.
Kmart Corp. declared bankruptcy a year ago after losing 2.4 billion US dollars in 2001.
It estimates a loss of 3.26 billion US dollars in 2002, and said the night before that the company will lose another 286 million US dollars this year.
Kmart Corp. has already closed 283 stores and laid off 22,000 employees.  At present, it plans to close 300 more stores and lay off 37,000.
Powell: US Gets Support from over Ten Allies for its Strikes on Iraq
(AFP, Davos, Switzerland, January 25)  US Secretary of State Powell said that the US plan to attack Iraq has got the support of over ten allies.
At this time, he is preparing his speech on the US policy for his attendance at the World Economic Forum.
Under tight security measures, Powell arrived at the Swiss ski resort of Davos to address the annual meeting of the global political and business leaders on Sunday.
In the meantime, anti-globalization protesters are also gathering here.
Concerns about a possible Iraqi war have cast a shadow over this year's meeting.
The participating OPEC nations are trying today to ease the concern that the world oil supply may be disrupted once the United States attacks Iraq.
Powell told reporters who traveled with him to Davos for coverage: "Quite a number of countries have already indicated ... (they) will act with us in unison;" even if the UN Security Council does not back the war, he added, these countries will not change their stances.
Powell said: "We'd not be alone; that's for sure.
I can name over ten countries just by memory, and I think more countries will show their support."
US officials said Powell will talk respectively with Turkish Prime Minister Gul and Australian Prime Minister Downer during the meeting in Davos.
Turkey, the most important NATO ally of the United States, is resisting pressure so that it can join the US-led war against Iraq.
Whereas, the Australian government has pledged to send troops to join the war regardless of domestic opposition.
Daschle Says President Bush Should Come Forward with Solid Proof of Hussein's Violations
(AFP, Washington, January 28)  Senate Democratic leader Daschle challenged President Bush's way of proving Iraq has weapons of mass destruction.  He went on to doubt whether the White House has already had a "guiding principle" to prove attacks on Husseins are justified.
Daschle asked: "If we hold the proof that Iraq possesses nuclear and biological weapons, why don't we show that proof to the world ? - just as President Kennedy did 40 years ago when he held the photographs of offensive missiles in Cuba and immediately instructed Stevenson, the US ambassador to the United Nations to announce them at the UN General Assembly."
It was during the time when the UN arms inspectors were reporting to the UN Security Council on Iraqi compliance with arms reduction orders that Daschle vehemently assailed President Bush in his report at the National Press Club.
He said: "At a time when we have begun to fight the war on terror, the American people have the right to know why thousands of the US troops are sent to the battlefield at the risk of their lives and why the United States wants to spend billions of dollars, risk offending allies and inflame adversaries to attack Iraq."
Daschle said: "In a democratic country, the president should do all he can to clear people's doubts, which is very important."
He was referring to the polls that show a decreasing support of the American public for President Bush.
White House has been rotating all kinds of reasons to explain the urgency of overthrowing Hussein, including its threat to the neighboring countries, poisoning of the Kurds, attempt to kill the former President Bush, alleged involvement in the Sept. 11 attacks, manufacturing weapons of mass destruction and so on, making people wonder which one is to believe.
He said: "It makes people doubt the government has already had a supreme guiding principle."
Parts of Northwestern Australia Devastated by Floods
(AFP, Townsville, Australia, January 28)  While many areas in Australia are being ravaged by droughts and forest fires, parts of the remote northwestern region are devastated by floods.
Today, disaster relief authorities must send fresh food supplies to Burketown in Gulf of Carpentaria area in Queensland.  The area has been marooned by floods for nearly three weeks.
Burketown has seen frequent flooding and once lost contact with the outside world for months due to floods.
However, the local council chief executive Turnour said that this year's flooding came upon the town all of a sudden.
He said: "No fresh milk, fruits or vegetables; the supply of bread is also limited.  There are only a few foods left in stock before the roads are reopened."
"The flood came with such suddenness that the last freight truck entering town also got stranded.  The truck came into town on the 22nd, and we were cut off from the outside world the very same night."
Turnour said the water level has fallen in the past few days; if no more rain keeps coming, the roads should become accessible this week.
Trad, a bar owner in Burketown, said he has been careful to ensure the supply of beers because people, unable to work due to floods, flocked to his bar for drinking.
Trad said: "They're drinking, playing cards and fishing to while away the time."
"The expanse of water is now replaced by mud.  So even if water is receding from the roads, they are still impassable."
Thousands of Century-old Olive Trees to Adorn Olympic Venues in Athens
(AFP, Athens, January 28)  About 4,000 century-old olive trees will be transplanted to line the 2004 Olympic Marathon route and other Olympic Games venues.
These olive trees will be transplanted from the remote islands of Crete and Zakynthos.
According to the Athens Olympics Organization Committee (ATHOC), these trees would have been uprooted sooner or later anyway due to local construction projects.
ATHOC said that at present these olive trees are temporarily stored; 1,500 century-old ones will be replanted in the future along the 42.2-kilometer Marathon course.
The rest of the old trees will be planted at other Olympic Games venues.
Olive trees are common of the Greek landscape.  The shape of the recently unveiled Olympic torch is exactly that of an olive leaf as inspired by the tree.
An official from the Olympics Organization Committee said: "This proposal represents the committee's sensitivity to environmental protection."
3 million euros will be spent on landscaping along the marathon course.
Protesters and people from adjacent communities say the marathon course mars the local environment as some of the roads on the route will be broadened, which will destroy the pristine scenery still unspoiled today.
Environmental protesters also complain that many trees have been uprooted in some parts of Athens due to the project of the Olympic Games-related tram route.
Exit Polls: Sharon-led Likud Party Wins Israeli General Election
(AFP, Jerusalem, January 28)  Israel held its general election today.  According to the results of exit polls, the right-wing Likud Party led by the incumbent Prime Minister Sharon has secured a victory, taking 32-36 seats in the 120-seat parliament.
Sharon's office said that, Mitzna, leader of the main opposition Labor Party, has conceded the election and telephoned Sharon for congratulation.
It is estimated that the Labor Party will get 17 to 19 seats, fewer than the original 25 seats, the worst election result for the Labor Party since Israel established itself as a country in 1948.
The centrist Shinui Party is expected to gain a substantial number of seats, from the mere 6 in the last parliament to between 14 to 17 seats, threatening the Labor Party's position as the second largest party.
The Shas is expected to win between 9 to 13 seats, fewer than the current 17 seats.
The above estimated results are released after polling stations were closed at 10:00 p.m. by the public TV station and the privately-run Channel 2.
The Labor Party leaders said talks have been started in the hope of forming a workable coalition.  However, the Labor Party leader Mitzna has ruled out the possibility of joining the Sharon administration.
US Senators Plan to Reorganize USOC Torn by Internal Bickering
(AFP, Washington, January 29)  US senators reprimanded the bickering leaders of the US Olympic Committee and vowed to reorganize this world's best funded national Olympic organization.
The USOC has been doing a poor job and been recently torn by fierce internal bickering.
The Senate plans to hold a hearing in February to study relevant measures while the senators who founded the USOC in 1978 will now start about its reorganization so as to inspire faith in the US athletes, supporters, and business sponsors.
Sen. McCain, chairman of the relevant Senate committee, said: "If we want to rebuild the public's confidence in the USOC, we must restructure the organization.
We must propose ways to reorganize the USOC so as to prevent the current problems from resurfacing."
Fierce and childish bickerings broke out among Ward, the scandal-embroiled USOC chief executive, Mankamyer, the USOC president, and Rodgers, the former USOC compliance officer who resigned last week.
Republican Senator Campbell said: "If there were a gold medal for bickering, the USOC officials involved in this bickering would deserve the award."
8 European Countries Sign Joint Letter in Support of US Strategy against Iraq
(AFP, London, January 29)  Leaders of eight European countries, excluding France and Germany, have signed an open letter published in the Times today, calling for Europe to form a united front with the United States in an effort to disarm Iraq of its weapons of mass destruction.
Leaders from Britain, Spain, Portugal, Italy, Hungary, Poland, Denmark and the Czech Republic said that the United Nations must force Iraqi President Hussein to abandon weapons of mass destruction, warning the UN credibility is being tested.
The letter published in the Times said: "Our strength comes from unity," and pointed out that the report submitted by the UN weapons inspectors on the 27th testifies that Hussein has been consistently "cheating, denying and failing to cooperate."
The letter was signed by Blair of Britain, Aznar of Spain, Berlusconi of Italy, Barroso of Portugal, Medgyessy of Hungary, Miller of Poland, Rasmussen of Denmark and Havel of the Czech Republic.
They affirm that Hussein's weapons of mass destruction are obvious threats to the world security.
"We must keep united and insist that the Hussein regime be disarmed.
The solidarity, cohesion and determination of the international community are where lies our hope of achieving this goal peacefully."
Thai Authorities Sent Planes to Evacuate Thai Nationals from Cambodia
(AFP, Bangkok, January 30)  Due to an anti-Thai clash that broke out in Phnom Penh, the Thai authorities have sent military transport planes to Phnom Penh to evacuate about 560 Thai nationals.  Today a few hundred Thais have arrived in Bangkok by plane.
Military officials said that Thai Prime Minister Thaksin and top military officials welcomed the first C-130 Hercules plane at Bangkok's military airport as it arrived from Phnom Penh with 170 Thai nationals on board.
The second plane followed, carrying 150 Thais back home.
Two more planes are scheduled to bring another 170 in total back to the country.
Diplomatic staff will take the fifth plane home.
Thailand's supreme Commander in Chief Surayud told reporters at the airport: "We're going to evacuate all of them by this afternoon."
Surayud said five Thais, who suffered minor burns, have already been sent to the hospital near the airport for treatment.
In Cambodia, hundreds of protesters attacked and torched the Thai embassy in Phnom Penh on the 29th.
This incident of Cambodians attacking Thais that broke out in Phnom Penh was ignited by a popular Thai actress, who claimed that Cambodia's famous ancient temple complex of Angkor Wat was stolen by Cambodians from their neighboring country.
Angry protesters looted Thai-owned stores in Phnom Penh.  The Royal Phnom Penh Hotel owned by Thais reportedly has been reduced to ashes.
Ethnic Chinese in Asia Celebrate Year of Goat and Hope for Economic Prosperity in New Year
(AFP, Hong Kong, February 1)  As Asia ushered in the Lunar New Year today, tens of thousands of people swarmed into the temples to pray for a turn of better luck and prosperity after having weathered one more year of economic downturn.
In Hong Kong's famous Wong Tai Sin temple, thousands of people poured into the temple as soon as the clock struck midnight, vying to be first to offer prayers on the Year of the Goat.
A middle-aged man, after squeezing through the heaving crowds to offer joss sticks, said: "I prayed for world peace and for the Hong Kong people to make more money."
His female companion said: "I prayed for good health, and no more wage cuts for workers."
In Taiwan, about 20,000 people waited in a line of several kilometers to get the red packets of NT$200 from President Chen Shui-bian when he returned to his home town to give out red packets.
As the Presidential Office had prepared only 15,000 red packets, thousands had to go home disappointed.
In China, three quarters of the entire population of 1.3 billion reportedly celebrated the Spring Festival by watching television.
State-run CCTV claimed that its four-hour Spring Festival special program attracted as many as  975 million viewers.
Of those who were able to tear themselves away from the TV screen, many celebrated the New Year by eating dinners at their cities' restaurants.  Many famous restaurants were reported to be fully packed.
In Indonesia, this is the first time that the Lunar New Year has been designated as a national holiday, a victory of the ethnic Chinese's fight against the extensive discrimination they have long suffered.  Now they can celebrate the Spring Festival with joy.
Russian Experts: Space Shuttle Disaster May Lead to Temporary Suspension of ISS
(AFP, Moscow)  A Russian space expert pointed out that the tragedy of the US space shuttle Columbia's disintegration on its way back to Earth may lead to the temporary suspension of manned missions on the International Space Station which rely on the US space shuttles and Russian spacecraft.
This Russian space expert, who did not wish to be named, told the Russian media Interfax that the accident of Columbia's disintegration on its re-entry of the earth's atmosphere will force the astronauts on the ISS to return to Earth and switch the ISS to automatic pilot operation for some period of time.
He noted if the age of the space shuttle is confirmed as the cause of the accident, the United States will freeze all space shuttle missions to prevent similar diasters from happening again.
He further pointed out it is very likely that the United States will not send astronauts again to the ISS until 2007 or 2008 and must build new spacecraft.
If the US space shuttles stop operation, only Russia can send astronauts to the space station by its spacecraft Soyuz.  However, as the Russian Space Agency is currently having severe financial problems, the United States and Russia may reach an agreement to use Soyuz to maintain manned missions on the space station while using Progress cargo vessels to send supplies to the ISS.
According to the Russian expert, the astronauts currently at the ISS were originally scheduled to take the US space shuttle Atlantis back to Earth on March 1 and should now be expected to continue their stay at the space station.
The participants of the ISS program include 16 countries such as the United States, Russia, Japan, Canada and France.
The Russian expert pointed out the tragedy on the 1st illustrated the unreliability of the space shuttle.  Russia had an accident too in 1971 when a Soyuz-11 craft crashed while returning to Earth, killing the three astronauts on board.
Havel Steps down as Czech President with New President not yet in Sight
(AFP, Prague, February 2)  Havel, the playwright who became a democracy movement hero during the reign of the Czech communist party, said farewell to his public service job today and stepped down from his democratically elected presidential post which he has held for 13 years.
In a televised address, Havel thanked the people for their trust in him, saying: "Without your understanding and goodwill, I wouldn't have been able to stay in office for a brief moment."
Although suffering from serious health problems, Havel still withstood the great pressure of the top position and stepped down as his term ended even if no successor has yet been chosen.
Havel took office on December 29, 1989 and made his first speech to the public on the balcony of Prague Castle on the very same day.  Earlier today he also greeted hundreds of well-wishers on the same spot, saying: "I bid all of you farewell after being your president for 13 years."
The 66-year-old playwright is a dissident-turned-world-class politician, which itself symbolizes the triumph of democracy over totalitarianism in Europe.
After revolution broke out in Czechoslovakia, Havel, once a prisoner under the communist regime, became the president.
Three years later, Czechoslovakia split into two countries, the Czech Republic and Slovakia.  Havel continued to be the president of the Czech Republic.
Today, Havel handed over the presidential seal to Prime Minister Spidla and Zaoralek, the speaker of the Parliament's lower chamber.  They two are scheduled to share the presidential power temporarily starting from tomorrow until a new president is elected.
The Czech Parliament convened to elect a new president last month, but neither of the voting on January 15 and January 24 yielded any result.
Britain Expects Chirac to Eventually Support Security Council Resolution Authorizing Military Attacks on Iraq
(AFP, London, February 3)  The British government is confident that the French President Chirac will eventually support the UN Security Council's second resolution authorizing military attacks on Iraq.
The British media reported today that Chirac and the British Prime Minister Blair will meet in Le Touquet in northern France tomorrow to exchange views on the latest development on the Iraqi crisis.
The headline of the left-wing newspaper The Guardian reads: "Downing Street predicts Chirac will change stance on Iraq."  The Guardian also quoted sources from the office of the British Prime Minister as saying that there are four factors which will influence Chirac into accepting the British way of thinking.
The center-right The Times also reported, citing British top officials, that Chirac has realized his anti-war position has "gone too far," as he was taken by surprise that seven European countries sided with Britain and signed a pro-US letter on the issue of Iraq published by the international media last week.
Quoting a British diplomat, the Times reported that Chirac likes to be in the spotlight and to be coaxed with sweet words, but he is far from dumb.  It may be too much to expect Chirac to make a 180 degree change tomorrow, but it is still hoped that the summit meeting between the two countries may see signs of Chirac's attitude change.
US Freezes Transfer of Nearly 3,000 Troops in South Korea
(AFP, Seoul, February 3)  The US military claimed that the transfer of some 2,900 US officers and soldiers scheduled to leave South Korea in the coming three months has been frozen so that the stationed troops can maintain readiness for war.
The freeze on this military order of transfer has no direct links with the nuclear crisis in North Korea, but it illustrated the inadequacy of the United States in tackling both Iraq and North Korea.
The US 8th Army stationed in Seoul said today that they have received the rotation freeze order  to maintain the scale of the US troops in South Korea; while similar military deployments are being carried out near Iraq and Afghanistan, the suspension of replacement from US-based military units has also been announced.
The US 8th Army commander Lieutenant General Campbell said in a statement that the freeze of transfer order is intended to ensure the US military strength in South Korea.
Under a defense assistance treaty signed between South Korea and the United States, currently some 37,000 US troops are stationed in South Korea.  The US military in South Korea has been on alert ever since North Korea's ambition to develop nuclear programs was disclosed in December last year.
Suspected Space Shuttle Debris also Spotted in California and Arizona in Western US
(AFP, Houston)  NASA said that suspected debris from the disintegrated space shuttle Columbia have also been spotted in the states of California and Arizona in western United States, which may provide important clues to why the space shuttle broke up in the air.
NASA's Associate Administrator Kostelnik said: "We have received quite a few reports that debris have been found in California and Arizona."
He said a team of experts has been dispatched to various locations in those states to examine the debris yet pointed out cautiously that so far it is not clear what those pieces are.
Dittemore, the space shuttle program manager, said on the 3rd that NASA has formed a special team to search for debris in areas west of Texas and Louisiana where most of the space shuttle Columbia's wreckage has been found.
Dittemore pointed out such debris can be crucial because it may provide the critical missing part about the cause of the accident.
The space shuttle Columbia was preparing to land at Kennedy Space Center in Florida at 9:16 a.m. (10:16 p.m. Taipei time) on the 1st when it broke up in the air into pieces of burning wreckage.  The seven astronauts on board the space shuttle were all killed.
Investigators are trying to understand why there was a sharp rise of temperature to as high as 16 degrees Celsius on the left side of the space shuttle minutes before the communication broke off while about simultaneously an unusual drag resistance occurred on the left side of the space shuttle, causing the space shuttle to lose control.
Kostelnik indicated that the possibility of finding debris in locations farther west than originally expected can be crucial in determining the cause of the accident.
He said: "It's of critical importance to examine the debris in the early stage of the accident."
South Korea's Special Envoy Calls for Dialogs between US and North Korea
(AFP, Washington, February 4)  US President Bush is faced with strong demands from the next government of South Korea and important allies in the US Congress to urge Washington to hold direct talks with North Korea so as to prevent the nuclear crisis from going out of control.
One day after giving the order to have heavy bombers on alert and ready for deployments, which inflamed North Korea, Bush's senior aides has to defend Washington's policy toward North Korea.
After his talks with Secretary of State Powell, Chyung Dai-Chul, a special envoy for South Korea's President-elect Roh Moo-Hyun, emphasized South Korea's position, saying: "We hope the United States will play a more active role and have dialogs with North Korea."
He added that dialogs between the United States and North Korea should be conducted multilaterally in an international setting.
In the meantime, Lugar, the Republican senior senator on foreign affairs, also urgently called for the United States to engage in dialogs with North Korea.
Lugar said: "In my opinion, the US officials should have talks with North Korean officials to discuss how to end North Korea's nuclear weapons program through an agreement to a complete international inspection."
Powell's deputy Armitage told Lugar's Senate Foreign Relations Committee that the US talks with North Korean officials are just a matter of time, not whether to have or not have talks.
Armitage said: "Of course we'll have direct talks with North Korea; there's no question about that."
However, he said that dialogs will take place only when Washington is convinced that a "strong international opinion" in support of ending Pyongyang's nuclear program has been established.
Germany's Unemployment Rate in January Climbs to New High in 5 Years
(AFP, Frankfurt, February 5)  Official statistics show that the bad weather in winter and the prolonged economic downturn have pushed the January unemployment rate in Germany to a new high in five years, dealing another heavy blow to German Chancellor Schroder, who has been just over 100 days into his second term in office.
In addition, the threat of a possible war in Iraq further dimmed the economic outlook in Germany, the biggest economy in the euro-zone.
It seems likely the hiring freeze in Germany's labor market will continue for months to come.
Statistics released by Germany's Federal Labor Office in Nuremberg show that the number of people looking for jobs in Germany jumped to 4.623 million, or 11.1% of the German working population.  The unemployment rate in January hit a new high of monthly unemployment rate in five year since March 1998.
Last December, the total number of the jobless people reached 4.225 million at an unemployment rate of 10.1%.
The unemployment in winter months in Germany usually increases for seasonal reasons as most of companies, especially those in the construction industry, lay off employees due to bad weather.
However, even after taking this reason into account, the lines for unemployment benefits application last month still continued to grow longer.
Seasonally adjusted data released separately by Germany's Frankfurt Central Bank show the total number of the unemployed in January surged to 4.274 million from 4.212 million last December.
Meanwhile, the seasonally adjusted unemployment rate rose to 10.3% from 10.1%.
Gerster, the head of the Federal Labor Department, attributed the sharp rise in the number of people looking for work to two factors, the common effect of the winter weather and the poor state of economy.
Singapore's Economic Review Committee: Economy Expected to Fully Recover by 2004
(AFP, Singapore, February 6)  Singapore's Economic Review Committee said that due to the global geo-political and economic tensions and uncertainties, Singapore's economy will have to wait till 2004 for a full recovery.
Singarpore's ERC said in its annual economic review report: "Singapore's economy has not yet completely recovered from the recession in 2001.  The short-term economic prospect in Singapore is dimmed by too much instability in the region, the economic slowdown in Europe, the United States and Japan, the imminent Iraqi war and the trememdous challenges from China."
However, Singapore's economy this year still has reasonable chances of growth, though a full recovery may not be expected until 2004.
Singapore government estimates that following a 2.2% economic growth rate of last year, this year may see a growth rate of between 2% to 5%, though still far below the average annual growth rate of 7.3% that Singapore has enjoyed since 1985.
ERC also recommends that the government defer the restoration of the Central Provident Fund  contribution rate for employers and consider no raise of the CPF contribution rate for two years to avoid burdening employers during the current difficult time and to help reduce unemployment rate and send a strong message to foreign investors.
Yao Ming Feels NBA Stardom Comes Too Fast
(AFP, Atlanta, Georgia, February 8)  After signing a contract to advertise for the beverage product Gatorade by shooting a commercial with the baseball star Jeter and the American football star Manning, Yao Ming, the Chinese giant who has become the newest US basketball icon, was met with more than a hundred reporters trying to capture his every word and movement.  He could not but feel all this has come too fast though he managed to carry himself amidst such chaos with the composure and wisdom of a Confucius.
The 22-year-old Huston Rockets center will be the starter in the 52nd NBA All-Star Game to be held here tomorrow and become the first Asian NBA star.
Other NBA stars such as Duncan and Iverson all suffered considerable loneliness by comparison with this Chinese giant who has drawn the attention of a global crowd of fans.
Yao Ming said: "The attention I received is obvious.  This is only one aspect of the pressure I've got.  This is something very special.
I wish to stay in my hotel room, but as a basketball player, this might be the luxury I can't have."
Well, it might be indeed a luxury to wish for when most people can usually only see your tummy at eye level and your face frequently appears in TV commercials.
When you are making money by the millions and replacing Air Jordan to become the chief pitchman of basketball, your life is inevitably a hustle and bustle.
Yao Ming said: "All this is happening too rapidly, too fast.
You don't want to get everything at the very beginning, you want to slowly merge into NBA, not like this.
But all this is beyond your control."
Content with Life, Hingis Has No Desire to Return to Tennis
(AFP, Paris, February 7)  Hingis, the Swiss female athlete who was formerly ranked No. 1 worldwide in women's tennis after winning 5 Grand Slam singles championships and 8 doubles championships between 1997 and 2000, indicated today that she has no desire to return to tennis.
However, the 21-year-old Serena Williams believes that Hingis, who started her career at 14, peaked too early and got burned out both physically and mentally.
Younger Williams said after she made the top four in Paris indoor tennis tournament: "I don't think Hingis has officially retired from tennis.  She is just tired.  She had been around in the tennis world for years while I was still goofing around before I was 17.  Sometimes I felt tired of it too, and I could really understand how she felt."
Hingis has recovered from an ankle ligaments surgery she took last year.  The operation left her unable to participate in the French Open and the Wimbledon tennis tournament, but she was eliminated by Seles in the third round at the US Open after her comeback.
Her last match was at Filderstadt in Germany on October 10, 2002, where she was beaten
Younger Williams, who has won 4 straight Grand Slam titles, frankly admitted that Hingis has been a big encouragement for all she has achieved today.
Bush Vows to Disarm Iraq One Way or the Other
(AFP, Washington, February 14)  US President Bush vowed today to disarm Iraqi President Hussein's regime "one way or the other."
He said: "Hussein has weapons of mass destruction, and he has used them.  He is used to deceiving the world, and continues to do so.
Hussein has also formed ties to terrorist networks."
In his speech at the FBI headquarters, explaining various kinds of efforts to prevent terrorist attacks such as those on Sept. 11, 2001, Bush sternly declared: "Hussein is a danger, and that's why he shall be disarmed -- one way or the other."
This is the first public response Bush has made to the UN Security Council meeting held today in New York.
The meeting is mainly intended to hear the UN arms inspection chief's report on whether Iraq has complied with the UN Security Council Resolution 1441 passed on November 8 last year, which orders Iraq to disarm.
White House Spokesman Fleischer said Blix hasn't provided any reason for people to believe that Iraq is complying with the Security Council Resolution 1441.
He told reporters: "Today the world hasn't got any relief from the news coming from New York, convinced that Hussein has shown arms inspectors that he is disarming.
The situation is exactly the opposite."
Asked when the United States will propose a follow-up resolution aimed to implement the Security Council Resolution 1441, Fleischer indicated "it's too early to tell," but the United States will discuss with its allies on its content and terms.
Countries such as France, Russia and China still propose tougher arms inspection for Iraq instead of a US-led war against Iraq.
Fleischer noted that President Bush also considers military actions as the "last resort."
However, he insisted on the timetable Bush has set, saying that the United Nations has got only "a few weeks not months" to test peaceful disarmament with Iraq, which will then be followed by military actions.
New York Times: White House Studies Sanctions against North Korea
(AFP, Washington)  Citing US officials, the New York Times today reported that White House is studying sanctions against North Korea once Pyongyang fails to abandon its development of nuclear weapons.
The report pointed out that these sanctions will include interdicting North Korea's arms shipment and cutting off the channels through which North Koreans in Japan send money to North Korea.
The report pointed out that the Pentagon and the State Department are working on the detailed plans for sanctions so that the United States can respond promptly any time when North Korea takes its new steps to pursue the development of nuclear weapons.
According to the New York Times report, the first step will be to urge the UN Security Council, perhaps in the next two weeks, to denounce North Korea's recent measures to develop nuclear weapons such as withdrawing from the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty and reactivating its frozen nuclear facility at Yongbyon that is capable of producing weapons-grade plutonium.
Yet, the Pacific allies of Washington authorities are still opposed to the idea of sanctioning against North Korea, while the UN Security Council may still focus on the issue of Iraq for the next few weeks.
In the meantime, the New York Times report pointed out, many US officials are concerned if the United States launches attacks against Iraq, North Korea may use the opportunity to promote its weapons production.
US Troops to Conduct Training on Philippine Hostage Island
(AFP, Manila, Philippines, February 17)  The US military trainers will be sent to the hostage island of Jolo in the Philippines this year to assist the country in coping with the terrorist threat from the rebel Islamic groups.
Bunye, a spokesperson for Philippine President Arroyo, said: "This military exercise will be part of overall and ongoing defense and security cooperation activities between the Philippines and the United States, and will continue to focus on enhancing our ability to combat terrorist threats and defend ourselves."
He pointed out in a statement: "The detailed numbers of the US personnel and supporting troops as well as the timeframe of the military exercise are still to be discussed and decided by the Philippine government and the United States."
Philippine Defense Secretary Reyes told media reporters that the US Major General Weber will arrive in the Philippines soon to "discuss all kinds of conditions and details regarding the operation in Sulu."
Sulu, the archipelago in the southern Philippines, includes the island of Jolo.
Golez, Arroyo's national security advisor, said that the military exercise in Sulu will "give the Philippine armed forces the maximum training in counter-terrorism."
Since the terrorist attacks on the United States in 2001, the US government has been increasing its military assistance to the Philippine government, concerned that the al Qaeda Islamic militants driven out by the US-led military actions in Afghanistan may have established their base in Southeast Asia.
The above concern has been fully confirmed by the bombing incident in the resort island of Bali in Indonesia last year, which killed nearly 200 people.
Most of those who died in the Bali bombing were Western tourists.
Schmid, Founder of German Telephone Operator MobilCom, Declares Bankruptcy
(AFP, Hamburg, February 18)  Schmid, the founder and also the former chairman of German telephone operator MobilCom, has declared himself insolvent today due to the sharp decline in the value of his shares and has filed the application with Flensburg Court in northern Germany.
Schmid holds about 40% of this company that he founded.  Over the past year, the company has been financially struggling on the brink of bankruptcy, which led to the sharp drop of its share price.
The statement pointed out that Schmid's personal assets and properties are also affected.
The court has appointed accountant Gellert to be in charge of his bankruptcy case.
Schmid has been spending so much on the next generation UMTS network development over the time that he was ousted last year by France Telecom, the major shareholder of MobilCom.
MobilCom said in a statement later today that Schmid's personal bankruptcy has no effect on the company's operation or contract.
The statement added that there will be no change on the rescue plan of about 7 billion euros undertaken by France Telecom.  According to this rescue plan, the German government and financial institutions will provide about 100 million euros of financing to MobilCom, which currently employs about 5,000 people.
US-South Korean Military Exercise to be Held in March; North Korea Threatens to Quit Armistice Agreement
(AFP, Seoul, February 18)  South Korea and the United States are going to conduct a large-scale military exercise starting from early March, that will last nearly a month.  North Korea, in response, threatens to quit the Armistice Agreement that ended the Korean war.
At a time when the tensions caused by the nuclear stand-off on the Korean Peninsula have continued for four months and showed no sign of easing off, North Korea's threat to quit the Armistice Agreement can be generally interpreted as Pyongyang authorities' response to the announcement made by the United States and South Korea yesterday of the joint military exercise to be held in March.
The statement issued by the North Korean military accuses the United States of repeatedly violating the Armistice Agreement: "If the US side continues violating and misusing the Armistice Agreement as it pleases, there will be no need for North Korea to remain bound to the Armistice Agreement uncomfortably.
The future development will depend entirely on the US attitude."
However, the US top military officials said that North Korea had said they would no longer be bound to the Armistice Agreement as early as in 1994.
US authorities announced yesterday that the United States and South Korea will hold their annual joint military exercise on the Korean Peninsula from March 4 to April 2.
A South Korean government official said that South Korea issued an invitation to North Korea yesterday, asking them to send observers to watch this military exercise.
The official, who did not want to be named, said: "North Korea's statement to quit the Armistice Agreement is obviously a response to the upcoming joint military exercise by the United States and South Korea."
Earlier, the United States ordered 12 B-52 bombers and the same number of B-1 bombers to get ready to go to areas around the Korean Peninsula.  North Korea strongly denounced this move.
In addition, the Japanese media reported yesterday that the United States has planned to step up its military deployment in Northeast Asia in order to guard against the concerns triggered by North Korea's nuclear weapons program.
Indonesian Authorities Reject Proposal to Increase Security Protection of US Embassy
(AFP, Jakarta, February 19)  The US embassy in Jakarta proposed to Indonesian authorities that a 3-meter-high surrounding wall be built to increase the security of the embassy, but the proposal was rejected.
"The Jakarta Post" and the state-owned "Antala" News Agency both reported today that Jakarta authorities rejected this proposal to build a wall to replace the fence that now separates the embassy and the residences from the outside on grounds that it is aesthetically unacceptable.
Jakarta officials, quoting Mayor Sutiyoso, pointed out that the wall can be built, provided that it be built five meters away from the existing fence inside the embassy compound.
In addition, the embassy must put sod and plant flowers in between the two fences to improve the look of the embassy compound.
Sutiyoso indicated that landscaping can reduce the feeling of the US embassy as a citadel.
Since around the time the United States led the military actions in Afghanistan aimed to overthrow the Taliban regime in 2001, its embassy in Indonesia has been endlessly confronted with protesting activities.
That year, when the former ambassador protested against the Jakarta police for failing to effectively stop the threat from the hardline Islamic groups on the safety of the Americans, the relevant authorities increased the security protection of the embassy.
It is generally expected that large-scale protests will become inevitable if the United States launches military actions against Iraq.
Sony to Actively Promote PlayStation 2 to Cyber World
(AFP, Tokyo)  Japan's electronics giant Sony Corp said that it will start the sales of broadband  connection units for the family PlayStation 2 in retail stores across Japan in May to promote the all-popular Sony game console further to cyber world.
As of the end of December, seven months after Sony promoted its online gaming service in the home market of Japan, Sony has only sold 190,000 broadband connection units.
The broadband connection unit, which consists of a hard drive and an adapter, is currently available for purchase only through Internet service providers.
The aforementioned actual sales figure is disproportional, considering there are 12.5 million PlayStation 2 users in Japan and as many as 50.4 million users worldwide.
Starting sales of connection kits in retail stores in tandem with promotion of more online games is part of Sony's strategy to encourage users to use PlayStation to play online games.
A spokeswoman for Sony Computer Entertainment (SCE), a Sony subsidiary, said: "We'll sell connection kits in stores so that more users can enjoy the fun of online games."
The spokeswoman noted that of the 874 PlayStation 2 games currently available, only one is authentic online game.  Two online games will be added in the coming few months.
About 20 games sold in Japan have some online capabilities.
The price of the broadband connection kit is not yet decided, but the one sold through ISPs is priced at 18,000 yen (150 US dollars) per kit.
Sony has already sold about 570,000 units of narrowband connection kits in North America at the price of about 39 US dollars and some 20 compatible games.
Asia to Have Largest Number of Programmers in the World in 2 Years
(AFP, Singapore, February 24)  A report released by International Data Corp. today pointed out that in the coming two years, there will be more computer programmers and other professional developers in the Asia-Pacific Region than in North America.
In 2001, North America had the largest concentration of professional developers, while the Asia-Pacific Region replaced Europe to become the area with the second largest number of professional developers.
However, the IDC report said that the strong growth in China and India is expected to push the Asia-Pacific Region to the top by 2005.
Asian regions, especially India, are the main source of IT professionals in North America.
IDC said: "In five years, the growth in the Asia-Pacific Region, especially in those big countries such as China and India, is expected to be much stronger than in North America."
IDC said that there were 7.8 million professional developers in 2001, and the number is expected to grow to 13.3 million by 2006.
The report pointed out that by the end of 2001, there were 1.7 million professional developers in Asia.
IDC noted that the drop in the number of IT professionals in North America is partly due to the decline of technology sector in the region.
Study Shows Father's Genes May Affect Timing of Birth
(AFP, Paris, February 28)  According to a report of a Danish study to be published on Saturday's "British Medical Journal," a father's genes may affect the timing of a child's birth.
About 5% of pregnant women go past their term, with a gestational length of 294 days.
At present, this problem is known to have effects on the health of both mother and child, but what causes it remains a mystery.
The Danish researchers tracked 43,000 cases of birth from 1980 to 1992.  The targeted women have at least two children and had a post-term pregnancy for the first delivery.
Only the data of their first two deliveries are used for analysis.
Overall, of those women who had a prolonged pregnancy for the first delivery, nearly 20% had the same experience for their second pregnancy.
However, when the first and the second child had different fathers, the rate dropped to just a little bit over 15%.
Olesen, the lead author of the research report, told AFP: "This is already a lot.
This means if you (with the second child) have the same partner, then compared with those who change their partners, your chance of having a prolonged pregnancy will be over 30%."
The research report said: "If a woman changes her partner every time she gets pregnant, it may reduce the risk of reoccurrence of post-term delivery.
We believe this is a new finding.
But the result means the timing of birth may be decided by a father's genes."
Belgium Demands Prompt Pumping of Fuel Oil from Anchored Oil Tanker
Xinhua News Agency, Brussels, January 4 (Reporter Liu Saijun)  Belgian authorities issued an ultimatum on the 4th to the owner of the Vicky, a Turkish ship that anchored in the Belgian waters, demanding that he start pumping the 700 to 1,000 tons of fuel oil carried on the tanker at the latest from 8:00 a.m. on the 5th.
The Belgian media quoted the head of a relevant agency as saying that the fuel oil carried on the Vicky is the same as the fuel oil on the Prestige, which has polluted the coastal areas off Spain, and that the owner of the tanker must ensure prompt pumping of the fuel oil to prevent a vast area of the Belgian waters from being polluted.
Belgian authorities said that if the owner of the Vicky does not meet the above demand, Belgium will seize the fuel oil on the ship and contract a professional firm at its own discretion to pump the oil at the owner's cost.
Bound for New York, the Vicky started out in Antwerp of Belgium on the 1st and anchored about 30 kilometers off the Ostend Coast in northern Belgium after it ran into the freighter Tricolor that had sunken last month while sailing through the Dover Strait.
Parts of Europe Battered by Floods
Xinhua News Agency, Berlin, January 4  Some areas in several European countries such as Germany, Belgium and the Czech Republic are recently hit by hurricanes and floods, which killed at least 7 people.
With water levels rising in many rivers, traffic on some of the major waterways are disrupted; and highway and rail transportation are also affected.
In the state of Bavaria in Germany, floods overflowed the river banks and inundated the adjacent areas on the 4th, forcing residents to wade through the waist-high water.
The small town of Wertheim is expected to experience the highest water level in 80 years.
Volunteers ferried local residents in rubber boats to the stores for shopping.
In addition, the government officials have platforms built in the old town areas to make it easier for people to get around.
The famous historic city of Cologne also narrowly escaped the disaster in the heavy rains.
The traffic on the 144-kilometer-long Rhine south of Cologne has to be suspended.
However, government officials said as the river water is continuously receding, the worst time is over.
The floods in the small Belgian town of Ninove, however, remain serious.  Two people are already missing.
The Belgian government has decided to call on the military to build sandbag embankments to prevent the villages and roads from further ravages.
Sri Lanka's Prime Minister Calls on the People to Work together for Permanent Peace
Xinhua News Agency, Colombo, January 6 (Reporter Zhang Yadong)  On the 5th, Sri Lanka's Prime Minister Ranil Wickremasinghe called on the people to work together to end the 19-year ethnic conflict in the country and bring about permanent peace.
On the very same night, Wickremasinghe said in a national televised address that the negotiations between Sri Lankan government and the anti-government Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) have entered a decisive stage where nothing could keep them away from the negotiation table as it is now the time to start a journey to permanent peace.
He emphasized that it is still a long way to go before peace can be finally materialized while solving the ethnic conflicts through political channels will ensure the interests of all ethnic groups.
He called on all the parties involved to put aside political differences and speak with one voice determined to seek peace.
Sri Lankan government and LTTE will start the four-day fourth round of peace talks on the 6th in Nakhon Pathom, Thailand.
One of the main topics for this talk is the settlement of Tamils, who have been displaced in the war, in the High Security Zones on Jaffna Peninsula in northern Sri Lanka.  However, the government and LTTE have been seriously divided on the issue lately.
Sri Lankan government forces proposed disarmament of LTTE as the condition for resettlement of Tamil civilians, but LTTE claimed that condition is "unacceptable and unrealistic."
Sri Lankan government and LTTE signed an agreement in February last year, and both sides started to enforce an official cease-fire.
Three rounds of peace talks have been held between both parties since September.
LTTE has indicated that it will no longer attempt to establish an independent Tamil state through war in the northern and eastern Sri Lanka and will instead seek autonomous rule of the region under a federal system.
Clay Sculpture of a Goat from Fengxiang, Shaanxi, Becomes Mascot of Chinese Year of the Goat
Xinhua News Agency, Xi'an, January 8  The clay sculpture of a goat, the work of Hu Xinming, a folk artist in Liuying Village, Fengxiang County in Shaanxi Province, has been voted simultaneously as the mascot of the Chinese Year of the Goat at the time it was selected as the design of the 2003 Zodiac stamp.
This is a mascot that Chinese have voted for the first time for their own new year.
Since the end of September 2002, more than 50 media agencies nationwide, including China's Central TV Station, have jointly held an open solicitation in the country for the mascot of the 2003 Year of the Goat.
Up till the end of December 2002, the review committee had received over 3,000 entries on the theme of the "goat."
Among "goats" of various features, the clay sculpture of a goat submitted by the folk artist Huxinming from Shaanxi, with its "charming naivety and auspicious merriment," won the hearts of most reviewers.
It eventually won the laureate of the mascot of the Year of the Goat by an absolute majority vote.
Baoji area in Shaanxi Province has long enjoyed the reputation as "the land of folk arts and crafts."  In 1995 and 2002, Piggy Pillow, a work of handicraft by a folk artist in Longxian County, Baoji, and the clay sculpture of a horse by the veteran folk artist Hu Shen from Liuying Village, Fengxiang County, were respectively selected by the China State Post Bureau as the designs of Zodiac stamps for the years, which were distributed both at home and abroad.
Hu Xinming's clay sculpture of a goat marks the third time a work of folk handicraft from Baoji area has been selected by the China State Post Bureau General as the design of a Zodiac stamp.
Hague Tribunal Medical Team to Verify Bobetko's Illness in Croatia
Xinhua News Agency, Belgrade January 8 (Reporter Yang Chengming)  From Zagreb: The Croatian media disclosed on the 8th that the Hague Tribunal will soon send a medical team to Croatia to verify whether Bobetko, the former Croatian army chief of staff and a war crime suspect wanted by the Hague Tribunal, is too sick to stand trial.
Bobetko was hospitalized for treatment in the middle of last November.
Racan, the prime minister of Croatia, once promised him that he will not be extradited to the Hague Tribunal while he is hospitalized.
A spokesperson for the International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia issued a statement on September 20 last year, saying that the tribunal had officially demanded that the Croatian government arrest and extradite Bobetko, who committed "crimes against humanity and war crimes."
Bobetko served as the Croatian army chief of staff from November 1992 to July 1995.
The Hague Tribunal indicted him for ordering his subordinates in killing over 100 Serbian civilians and soldiers and in burning down 300 residential houses in September 1993.
Bobetko issued a statement to the media on the very night, denying the Hague Tribunal's indictment and saying he would never yield to the Hague Tribunal, even if it costs his life.
US Defense Department Calls off 2 Missile Intercept Tests
Xinhua News Agency, Washington, January 8 (Reporter Tan Xinmu)  Lehner, spokesman for the Missile Defense Agency at the Pentagon, announced on the 8th that the US military authorities have decided to call off the two missile intercept tests scheduled for the first half of this year because the development of a new type of booster that launches the interceptor is behind the original schedule.
Lehner told the media here that the Missile Defense Agency this year will need to concentrate on solving the problem of the booster and that the next missile intercept test will be conducted after Boeing manufactures the new type of booster this fall.
Boeing originally planned to begin flight tests in 2000 on the new booster that carries the missile "interceptor," but the tests were postponed due to technical reasons.
After the failure to launch the booster in December 2001, Boeing decided to redesign it and planned to complete the design by this fall.
In the previous eight ground-based missile intercept tests, the US military used a modified "Minuteman" rocket as a surrogate booster, but the results of the tests on this kind of booster were not satisfactory.
The missile intercept tests conducted in July 2000 and last December were not successful because the "interceptor" failed to separate from the booster.
US President Bush ordered the Pentagon to start planning a missile defense system on December 17 last year and try to set up a preliminary missile defense system by September 2004.
However, many experts think as far as technologies are concerned, the time is not yet ripe to set up a missile defense system.
Kadish, director of the Missile Defense Agency, also indicated that if Boeing fails to manufacture the desired booster as scheduled, the entire missile defense system set-up will be affected.
Slovakian President Leaves Shanghai for Hong Kong by Air
Xinhua News Agency, Shanghai, January 10 (Reporter Zhou Jierong)  President Rudolf Schuster of the Slovak Republic concluded his visit to Shanghai on the morning of the 10th and left Shanghai for Hong Kong on a Slovakian charter plane.
Zhou Muyao, deputy mayor of Shanghai, went to see off Slovakian President Schuster and his entourage at the airport.
Schuster and his entourage arrived in Shanghai for a visit from Beijing on a charter plane at the noon of the 8th.
During their stay in Shanghai, Chen Liangyu, mayor of Shanghai, met with Schuster on the evening of the 8th and expressed his welcome for more Slovakian businesses to come to Shanghai for economic and trade cooperation.
On the afternoon of the 8th, Schuster attended a seminar by Chinese and Slovakian entrepreneurs.
On the 9th, Schuster attended the opening ceremony of Shanghai Office of the Slovakian Electric Appliance Design and Research Institute and toured Shanghai City Planning Exhibition Hall and Shanghai Museum.
The total trade volume of imports and exports between Slovakia and Shanghai has now reached 30 million US dollars with garments, pharmaceuticals, steel, furniture and auto parts as main commodities of trade on both sides.
Schuster came to China on January 4 for a state visit at the invitation of China's President Jiang Zemin.
Port of Shanghai Surpasses Kaohsiung as World's Fourth Largest Container Port
Xinhua News Agency, Shanghai, January 10 (Reporter Feng Yizhen)  News from the port industry indicated that last year the Port of Shanghai recorded a container throughput of 8.612 million TEUs against that of about 8.491 million TEUs completed by the Port of Kaohsiung in Taiwan, surpassing the latter to become the world's fourth largest container port.
The global economic rebound and sustained economic growth in China last year have infused fresh vitality into the development of the Port of Shanghai.
In 2001, the Port of Shanghai handled a container throughput of 6.34 million TEUs.  Last year its container throughput passed two milestones of 7 and 8 million TEUs to hit 8.612 million TEUs, a jump of 35.8% over the previous year.  Its total cargo throughput reached 260 million tons, up 19% over a year earlier while its foreign export volume exceeded 100 million tons for the first time by a 22% increase over the previous year.
With a vast economic hinterland as its support and a huge network with direct links, the Port of Shanghai has become a hub with the largest number of liner routes and voyages.
At present, the Port of Shanghai has liner routes to all the 12 navigational zones on earth and trade relations with more than 400 ports in the world.  It has daily voyages to Europe and North America and weekly voyages to the Mediterranean, the Persian Gulf, Australia and so on.
The number of voyages to all parts of the world each month is more than 1,300.
The container throughput of this year at the Port of Shanghai, which is speeding up the construction of its International Shipping Center, will exceed 9.5 million TEUs and efforts are made to reach 10 million TEUs so that the port will achieve its original goal one year ahead of schedule.
Turkey Allows US to Inspect Its Bases
Xinhua News Agency, Ankara, January 10 (Reporter Huai Chengbo)  According to the report of the Turkish newspaper "Milliyet" on the 10th, the Turkish government has agreed to let 150 US military personnel to inspect the Turkish bases and ports that may be used in the war against Iraq.
The report said that after rounds of negotiations between Turkey and the United States, the two sides finally reached an agreement on the document regarding the legal status of these US military personnel.
The document stipulates that these US personnel are subject to investigation pursuant to the Turkish Penal Law if they commit crimes outside the military facilities.
The Turkish legal authorities have the right to arrest, sentence and imprison them.
If the court permits, criminals may also serve their sentence terms in the United States.
According to the report of Anadolu News Agency, the Turkish and US officials can formally sign this document at any time.
The report said that the United States asked Turkey for permissions to open a "northern front" in its military strikes against Iraq from the Turkish territories and to use Turkish bases and ports and deploy 80,000 ground troops in Turkey so as to launch strikes on Baghdad from Turkey.
The United States hopes that its military experts can begin inspection and construction on the Turkish bases and ports as soon as possible so that the facilities can meet the requirements of the actual warfare.
The three bases that the United States proposed for use are Incirlik, Batman and Diyarbakir; the three ports are Tasucu, Mersin and Iskenderun.
All of them are located in southern and southeastern Turkey.
US Resumes Admission of Iraqi Refugees
Xinhua News Agency, Washington, January 10  Officials from the UN Refugee Agency said that the US government announced the resumption of its program of admitting Iraqi refugees on the 10th after it was briefly suspended.
Officials from the US Immigration and Naturalization Service said that the admission of Iraqi refugees has now resumed after being suspended for a few days, but they did not explain why the program was suspended or resumed.
On the 9th, the UN High Commissioner for Refugees representative in Washington received a phone call from a top US State Department official and was told that the admission program of Iraqi refugees had been suspended.
The refugees affected by this change are mainly scattered in Jordan, Syria and Turkey.
Lavinia Limon, the executive director of the US Committee for Refugees, blamed the plight of these refugees on Iraqi President Saddam because they had to flee their homeland due to the persecution they suffer at the hands of Saddam's regime.
The US government plans to admit 70,000 refugees in 2003.
Last year, the planned quota for refugees was also 70,000, but only fewer than 30,000 people were actually admitted.
(Entertainment Hotline)  Peking Opera of the Fairy Tale "the Wild Swans" to Debut on the Capital's Stage
Xinhua News Agency, Beijing, January 11  "The Wild Swans," a Peking opera based on Anderson's fairy tale performed by Peking Opera House of Hebei Province, will make its debut on the capital's stage -- Changan Theater on evenings from January 13 to January 24.
An elaborate integration of Chinese and foreign cultures, costumes and scenes, and a fine mixture of classic and contemporary languages, music and styles of singing, "the Wild Swans" retells the beautiful fairy tale in the form of Peking opera, which is not only pleasing to the eyes and ears but also highly entertaining.
In the play, the kind-hearted and innocent Princess Elisa, envied by her stepmother because of her beauty, is frantically persecuted.  She goes through a series of hardships and misery to rescue her brothers in distress.
In the end, truth, benevolence and beauty triumph over falsehood, evil and ugliness, and Elisa accomplishes her three beautiful leaps that lead to a magnificent life.
According to "Beijing Evening," the script, direction, style of singing and choreography of the play have no matches.
The renowned director Xie Ping-an has not only retained the overall features of a Peking opera in this play but also added some romantic and lively sentiments of a fairy tale.  He has employed many artistic techniques and a large number of theatrical expressions.  His rendering of group scenes, in particular, is phenomenally sophisticated and stylistically unique.
Elisa is played by Zhang Yanling, a Class-1 actress on the state level and a winner of "the Plum Blossom Award."
Her voice is clear, mellow and sweetly resonant.
Against a beautiful scenery of an exotic land, Elisa's heart bleeds for her beloved brothers.  An extensive piece of "fan er huang" is sung with such rich vocal and emotional expression that the heroine's feelings just speak for themselves.
Her life-like make-up in the play and her simple but pretty headdress only add to her brilliance.
Car Bombing in Colombia Left at Least 4 Dead
Xinhua News Agency, Bogota, January 16 (Reporter Yin Nan)  A car bomb exploded near a district prosecution office in central Medellin, Colombia's second largest city, on the morning of the 16th, killing at least 4 and injuring 26.
The Colombian police disclosed that a rental car parked at the parking lot of a shopping center near the prosecution office exploded at 8:05 a.m. local time.
The dead include a one-year-old child, and five of the wounded are in critical condition.
40 shops and 15 automobiles near the bombing site were damaged.
Authorities suspect that the Armed Revolutionary Forces of Colombia (FARC), an anti-government guerrilla organization, is responsible for the incident, because 68 members of the guerrilla organization have been captured in Medellin this week.
Medellin police chief Gallego announced that the police has offered a reward of 500 million pesos (about 172,000 US dollars) for the capture of the perpetrators.
Antioquia Province, where Medellin is in, is one of the areas that have seen the most violent armed clashes in Colombia.  Illegal armed forces such as the FARC, the National Liberation Army and the right-wing paramilitary group and so on have frequent activities in this area.
Multi-billion-dollar Diamond Deal Violates Antitrust Law, EU Concludes
Xinhua News Agency, Brussels, January 16 (Reporter Tian Fan)  The European Commission announced on the 16th that the EU preliminarily concludes the 4-billion-euro diamond sales contract signed between De Beers, the largest diamond supplier in the world, and Alrosa, a Russian diamond company, violated the EU's Antitrust Law.
De Beers, a company that has its headquarters both in South Africa and Britain, controls 60% to 65% of the world's rough diamonds.  Alrosa, the only diamond mining company in Russia, on the other hand, is also the world's second largest producer of rough diamonds.
Under the five-year multi-billion-dollar contract signed by the two companies, Alrosa agrees that it shall supply half of its annual diamond output, some 800-million-euro worth of rough diamonds, to De Beers, which will then distribute these diamonds to the markets.
The European Commission pointed out in a statement that the contract will restrict Russia's free competition with the world's diamond markets and lead De Beers to potential abuse of its dominant position to effectively control the quantity, quality and even price of diamonds on the world market.
Under the EU Antitrust Law, the two companies can appeal the European Commission's decision within two months and the European Commission will also continue its antitrust investigation of the two companies.
Gas Explosion in Lishu Coal Mine in Jixi
Xinhua News Agency, Harbin, January 21 (Reporters Wu Xiaodong and Yang Haibin)  At 9:42 on the 20th, a gas explosion occurred at Lishu Coal Mine No. 7 of Jixi Mine Group, killing 16 of the 97 people working underground.
As of the early morning of the 21st, the rescue work has completed.
According to Yu Jiahua, chairman of Jixi Mine Group, the coal mine where the accident occurred has been reorganized out of the bankrupt Muleng Coal Mine.  The annual output is about 200,000 tons.
The gas explosion did not take place in the digging area but in the exit tunnel.
At the time, workers underground were moving equipment.
The cause of the explosion is not yet clear.
After the accident, Jixi Mine Group dispatched more than 40 rescue workers to provide emergency aid.  Except for the 16 people who were killed, the rest have been all safely evacuated.
The remains of the victims have now been brought to the surface, and body identification and other aftermath care are currently underway.
The underground ventilation system has resumed normal operation.
Officials from the Coal Mine Safety Supervision Bureau of Heilongjiang Province and other related Jixi agencies arrived promptly on the scene after the accident to organize rescue efforts.  The cause of the accident is under investigation.
Japan's Central Bank Decides to Keep Current Financial Policies
Xinhua News Agency, Tokyo, January 22 (Reporter Yue Shaoyan)  At a policy board meeting of Japan's central bank that ended on the 22nd, it was decided that they should keep the current financial policies and maintain the total funds supplied to the market between 15 trillion to 20 trillion yen (1 US dollar equals about 118 Japanese yen).
As for the government and ruling party's request of "setting a moderate inflation target," it was agreed at the meeting that caution should be exercised.
It was agreed at the meeting that although the prospect of Japan's economy looks worse than before, the stock and financial markets have relatively stabilized.  With no substantial changes in the economic map, it was decided that they should maintain the current financial policies.
In regard to the request of the government and the ruling party that the central bank further relax its hold on cash and set a moderate inflation target, the central bank thinks that the current Japanese financial market has sufficient funds.
If the financial market shows any sign of insufficient supply of funds in the future, the central bank will pump more cash as needed.
It is learned that the Japanese government and ruling party hope that the central bank will induce the annual domestic inflation rate to 1-3%.
War in Iraq May Lead to Sufficient Supply on the World Oil Market
Xinhua News Agency, Riyadh, January 22  According to Saudi newspaper Al-Watan that quoted Algerian Minister of Energy and Mines Khelil on the 22nd, in the event of a war in Iraq, there is no guarantee that OPEC can make up for the shortfall of 5 million barrels of crude oil each day on the international market.
Khelil said that among the OPEC member states, only Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates have the actual spare capacity to increase production.
He believed, "OPEC will have problems meeting the market needs, because even if Saudi Arabia and the UAE have the spare capacity to increase production, they can increase 3 million barrels per day at most."
Since December last year, the price of crude oil on the international market has kept rising due to the general strike in Venezuela and the threat of war in Iraq.
On the 12th, OPEC decided in Vienna to increase the daily oil production by 1.5 million barrels starting from February.
However, as the threat of war in Iraq still looms large, and Britain and the United States continue to build up troops in the Gulf region, the oil price on the international market continued to rise on the 21st.
Khelil said that the international oil price is now more being driven by the tensions of the international political situation rather than supply and demand mechanism.
Shenzhen Luohu Customs Cracks down on Currency Smuggling
Xinhua News Agency, Shenzhen, January 25 (Li Nanling and Li Xiangzhi)  Shenzhen Luohu Customs, while ensuring a civilized and efficient inspection, spared no mercy in cracking down on the smuggling of currency by means of evading travelers' inspection.
Last year, the customs uncovered a total of 1,023 cases of currency smuggling, which involved an equivalent of over 150 million yuan.  Of these cases, 15 were individual cases involving more than 500,000 yuan (not including cases involving foreign currency notes).
As the largest port for travelers' inspection in the country, Luohu Customs is responsible for overseeing a daily flow of over 250,000 travelers.  If the relatively common practice of carrying cash beyond the legal limit were not strictly regulated, each day might see a considerable amount of capital flight.
In face of this situation, the customs has always taken tight monitoring measures such as frequent checks and careful inspection so as to effectively prevent the outflow of domestic currencies.
A little past 9 a.m. on February 19 last year, a middle-aged woman who walked quickly towing a suitcase caught the attention of the customs officers.
After the luggage went through the machine, the officers found the suitcase contained suspicious objects and opened it for inspection.  They were surprised to see three large bundles of Hong Kong currencies in 1,000-HK-dollar denomination packed in black plastic bags totaling 3 million HK dollars.
This was the largest case of a traveler carrying excess cash abroad the customs has uncovered in nearly two years.
In July and August last year, taking advantage of a larger outflow of travelers during the summertime and the crowded site due to the remodeling of the port facility, some overseas "underground money houses" attempted to smuggle a large quantity of foreign currencies out of the country.
The customs took this matter seriously and made key deployments there to effectively crack down on the foreign exchange smuggling by the "underground money houses."
From July 2 to August 1, Luohu Customs uncovered a total of 4 cases of foreign currency smuggling by the "underground money houses," involving an equivalent of more than 1.46 million yuan.
Spring Festival/Tibetan New Year Party Held in Tibet
Xinhua News Agency, Lhasa, January 27 (Reporter La Ba Ci Ren)  On the afternoon of the 27th, the Jiji Conference Hall of Lhasa Hotel was filled with atmosphere of joyous festivities, where more than 300 representatives from all walks of life, ethnic groups and various circles in Tibet attended the Spring Festival/Tibetan New Year party held by the autonomous region government.
At the party, Legqog, chairman of the Tibet Autonomous Region, gave his new year's good wishes to the people of all ethnic groups in the entire region, all the construction crews who are working hard on the Qinghai-Tibet Railway, the People's Liberation Army, the armed police and security officers stationed in Tibet, and overseas Tibetan compatriots.
He said, in the past year, with the kindly concern of the Central Party Committee and the State Council and with the selfless support of people of all ethnic groups in the entire country, especially the counterpart support provinces and cities and the key state-owned large enterprises, the Party Committee of the autonomous region and the government have stayed united in leading the people of all ethnic groups in the entire region, upholding the guiding principle of Tibet administration for the early period of the new century, working hard together, initiating new development and innovation so as to achieve a sustained, rapid and healthy growth in the national economy.
With a sensible administration supported by its people, Tibet now enjoys economic growth, social progress and unity of ethnic groups in a stable environment where people live and work in peace and contentment.
He pointed out that the coming new year will be the first year for Tibet to fully implement and carry out the key decisions made at the Party's 16th National Congress as well as a critical year for Tibet to promote accelerated growth and long-term stability and to lay the foundation for building an overall well-to-do society.
Tibet will fully promote a healthy and coordinated development of socialist material civilization, political civilization, and spiritual civilization.
At the party, Song and Dance Ensemble of Tibet Autonomous Region and other groups performed magnificent shows.
Pagbalha Geleg Namgyai, vice chairman of Standing Committee of China's National People's Congress attended the party.
Association for Promoting Peaceful Reunification of China in Germany Commemorates the 8th Anniversary of President Jiang's 8 Propositions on Taiwan
Xinhua News Agency, Berlin, January 27  The Chinese Association for Promoting Peaceful Reunification of China in Germany issued a statement on the 26th to mark the 8th anniversary of President Jiang Zemin's important speech entitled "Continuing to Strive for Promoting the Accomplishment of the Great Cause of Reunification of the Motherland."
Looking back at the history of development of the cross-Strait ties and many activities by overseas Chinese compatriots in recent years in their common cause of "fighting against the division and Taiwan independence and of promoting the peaceful reunification of the motherland," the statement recognized that overseas Chinese compatriots from both sides of the Straits have had full and effective cooperation.
The statement said that this important speech by President Jiang Zemin has laid the solid foundation for Chinese on both sides of the Straits and overseas compatriots to achieve healthy and interactive cooperation.  It not only adheres to the core principle of one China but also expresses the feelings that Chinese on both sides of the Straits are brothers.  With its striking contemporary characteristics that keep pace with the times and highly realistic focus, the speech demonstrates the flexibility, tolerance and stability needed to reach the final solution.
The statement pointed out that President Jiang's 8 propositions fully maintain and represent the most fundamental interests of Chinese on both sides of the Straits and their overseas compatriots.
The statement called on the overseas Chinese to continue making new efforts to promote the reunification of their motherland.
Chinese Culture Festival Opens in Ankara
Xinhua News Agency, Ankara, January 28  (Reporters Zheng Jinfa and Huai Chengbo)  The "Chinese Culture Festival" with "joint celebration of China's Spring Festival by Chinese and Turkish peoples" as its theme opened on the evening of the 28th in the hall of Trade Center in Ankara, the capital city of Turkey.
Hebei Song and Dance Theater's opening performance of dances, acrobatics and other wonderful shows greatly captivated an Turkish audience of over 1,500.
That night, many people came very early to get the best seats in the hall.
Even before the show started, the hall was packed to full capacity and many people had to stand like sardines along the corridor of the hall.  Quite a few children had to watch the show by the Chinese performers by looking through the cracks in the curtains.
"Trotting Donkeys," a dance with local Hebei characteristics, depicts comical events that take place while a young couple, each on a donkey, are on their way to visit the wife's parents.
The Turkish audience burst into laughter from time to time with the excellent performance of the entertainers and the humorous plots in the story and showed their appreciation with warm applause.
When the Chinese singer Zhai Fang started to sing in her clarion voice the famous Turkish folk song "Great Mountain," the hall was simply rocked with thunderous applause.
When the performance ended, many Turks from the audience fought their way to the stage and took out pens and paper or held out their hands to ask the Chinese entertainers for autographs.  Some even climbed onto the stage to take pictures with the Chinese performers to capture the memory.  A few Turkish children were even in tears when they missed the chance to get the autographs or take pictures with the Chinese performers.
A young Turkish girl told Xinhua reporters: "This is the first time that I've seen such a beautiful Chinese dance.
I hope all kinds of Chinese art groups can often come to perform in Turkey so that we the Turkish people can get to know more about the Chinese culture."
(HK, Macau, Taiwan) Mainland Visitors, A Growing Clientele for HK Jewelry Shops
Xinhua News Agency, Hong Kong, January 29  Gu Tangfa, administrative manager of Chow Tai Fook Jewellery in Hong Kong, said that mainland visitors have become a major clientele for jewelry shops in Hong Kong.
During the Christmas and New Year season last year alone, said he, 30-40% of the jewelry shop's sales were by mainland visitors, who have now become top consumers for Hong Kong's jewelry industry.
Since the restrictions on mainland tourists to Hong Kong eased up in early 2002, the number of tourists from mainland China to Hong Kong has soared.
Last year, during the Lunar New Year, May 1 Labor Day, October 1 the Golden Week, Christmas and New Year, mainland tourists stimulated the retail industry in Hong Kong, especially the high-end consumer market there.
According to the estimation by the relevant agencies in Hong Kong, during the coming Lunar New Year season, 600,000 mainland tourists will visit Hong Kong.  Many shops, especially those upscale ones, are all focusing on how to consolidate and open up the market of mainland visitors.
Chow Tai Fook is expecting an increase of 5% in sales during the Spring Festival.
In order to meet the needs of mainland customers, some firms have started to change their ways of doing business and strategies.  Quite a number of firms have intensified training of their employees in learning to speak Mandarin Chinese and offered classes from time to time to enhance the quality of employees' service and their professionalism.
The well-established jewelry shops generally do not offer any discounts, but now as long as mainland tourists pay with cash, they all offer better prices to attract more mainland customers.
(International) Cambodian Protesters Set Fire to Thai Embassy in Cambodia
Xinhua News Agency, Phnom Penh, January 29 (Reporters Lei Bosong and Zhang Ruiling)  About a thousand Cambodians stormed into the Thai embassy in Cambodia on the night of the 29th, burned the Thai national flag, vehicles and set fire to the embassy building.
The Cambodian police, in an effort to control the situation, have sent out several fire engines to put out the fire.
At this moment, the Cambodian police are still unable to confirm whether there is any casualty.
The protest started on the morning of that day to protest Suwanan, a Thai movie star who remarked that "Angkor Wat belongs to Thailand."
Later, more and more protesters gathered in front of the Thai embassy in Cambodia, burned car tires, the Thai national flag and the portrait of that Thai actress.  Afterwards, the protesters stormed into the embassy.
It is also reported that Suwanan has already made a speech to reporters in Thailand and denied having made such a remark as  "Angkor Wat belongs to Thailand."
(International)  France Sends Gendarmes to Reinforce Peace-keeping Troops in Cote d'Ivoire
Xinhua News Agency, Paris, January 29 (Reporter Wang Jingcheng)  French Foreign Minister de Villepin announced at a parliamentary hearing on the 29th that to ensure the implementation of the peace accord reached by all parties in Cote d'Ivoire and to strengthen the French peace-keeping troops, France has just sent gendarmes reinforcements to the Cote d'Ivoire.
De Villepin did not disclose the number of the reinforcement troops.
He said, however, France has taken all necessary measures to ensure the safety of the French nationals in Cote d'Voire.
He indicated that with the support of the international community, France will assume the responsibility of monitoring the implementation of the Cote d'Voire peace accord and make joint efforts with all parties involved in Cote d'Voire to restore the national sovereignty of Cote d'Voire and safeguard its territorial integrity.
De Villepin said that the peace accord reached by all parties of Cote d'Voire in France on the 24th "is the surest guarantee to bringing about peace and national reconciliation in Cote d'Voire."
In order to push forward the implementation of the peace accord, he has kept in close touch with Gbagbo, the president of Cote d'Voire, and leaders of other parties.
He said the Air France flight between Abidjan and Paris that was suspended for three days has resumed on the 29th.
(International) Rally Held in Nicaragua to Protest US War on Iraq
Xinhua News Agency, Managua, January 30 (Reporter Yang Wenzheng)  Several hundred anti-war protesters gathered on the 30th in front of the US embassy in Nicaragua and demonstrated their strong opposition against the possible US military strikes on Iraq.
Janina Guerrero, president of the Nicaraguan Association of Peace Promotion who organized this gathering, delivered a speech at the rally, denouncing the US attempt to launch a war of aggression against Iraq in order to seize the Iraqi oil.
Demonstrators from the capital Managua and other cities held various kinds of banners, shouting slogans such as "No US War on Iraq; We Want World Peace" and demanding that the US immediately stop all war preparations.
Demonstrators said in their letter to the US embassy: "Let's fight together for a future of peace in the world, freedom and prosperity; let's learn to respect rights of others.  The issue of Iraq should be solved by Iraq itself under the constructive assistance of the international community."
(International) US Personal Consumption Expenditures Flat Last Year
Xinhua News Agency, Washington, January 31 (Reporter Wang Zhenhua)  A report released by the US Department of Commerce on the 31st shows that although the US personal consumption showed a relatively brisk growth last December, the annual growth rate only broke even with that in 2001 when economy was in recession.
During the last month of last year, personal consumption expenditures, the major driving force for the growth of the US economy, increased 0.9%, the strongest monthly growth since July last year.
Spending on durables rose 6.1%, while spending on non-durables and services only increased 0.2%.
This was a clear sign of slow sales in an otherwise busy holiday shopping season in the United States.
In the last quarter of last year, personal consumption expenditures, which account for about two thirds of the US GDP, rose only 1%, significantly lower than the 4.2% growth rate in the third quarter.  This is the quarter with the smallest growth since the first quarter of 1993.
Economic analysts think uncertain factors such as a possible US war on Iraq, the sharp decline in the stock market and a stagnant job market have mainly held back consumers from spending and consequently led to a sharp slowdown in the US economy in the fourth quarter.
For the entire year last year, US personal consumption expenditures grew 4.5%, matching the growth rate in 2001.
The report also shows that the US personal income rose 0.4% last December.
The annual increase of US personal income last year was 3%, down from the 3.3% increase rate in 2001.
With spending growth outpacing income, the US savings rate dropped from 4.5% in November to 4.1% at the end of the year.
(International) French Troops Attacked in Cote d'Ivoire
Xinhua News Agency, Abidjan, January 31  French troops stationed in Cote d'Ivoire were attacked by local protesters at Abidjan Airport on the 31st.  About 800 young Ivoirians hurled stones at the French soldiers, injuring one French soldier seriously on the face.
Since West African leaders again held talks in Senegal on the civil war in Cote d'Ivoire, the turmoil in Cote d'Ivoire has escalated.
Seydou Diarra, who is vastly respected in Ivoirian politics, was nominated as the new prime minister at the meeting and will return to the country on the 31st to start forming a coalition government.
However, the "Young Patriots," an organization that supports Ivoirian President Gbagbo, resents representatives of rebels taking up such key posts as defense and interior ministers in the future government.
They accused France of coercing Gbagbo into accepting the plan to form the coalition government and called Diarra "prime minister for the French," threatening that death is waiting for Diarra.
According to reports, although the runways at Abidjan Airport have been cleared, several hundred members of "Young Patriots" are staying in the waiting room, ready to boycott the return of Diarra.
The civil war in Cote d'Ivoire has been going on for four months already, leaving hundreds dead in the clashes.
The French Foreign Ministry suggested on the 31st that the 16,000 French nationals in Cote d'Ivoire be evacuated as soon as possible.
(International)  Planned Space Flights of Two Canadian Astronauts Set Back
Xinhua News Agency, Ottawa, February 3 (Reporter Hu Guangyao)  According to the local media reports on the 3rd, the plans of two Canadian astronauts to go to space on the US spacecraft in May and November of this year will have to be scrapped due to the accident of the US space shuttle Columbia.
Garneau, Canada's first astronaut and president of the Canadian Space Agency, said that the US investigation of the Columbia accident may hinder the planned missions of the International Space Station; some of the programs may have to be postponed or even canceled.
The Canadian astronauts, MacLean and Williams, were originally scheduled to take their space flights respectively in May and November this year.
The two people are currently receiving training in Houston, USA.
During the 1990s, three Canadian astronauts participated in space missions on the space shuttle Columbia.
Garneau also disclosed that the space science experiments aboard Columbia this time included two research projects sponsored by Canada.
The research projects involve the protein crystal growth with one of the objectives being the treatment of breast cancer and prostate cancer.
It is also reported that after the Columbia accident, NASA immediately cut short an astronaut training program in Canada.
The seven astronauts, who were receiving training last week at Valcartier military base near Quebec City in Canada, have finished their training and returned to the United States.
(International)  US Construction Spending Posted a Sharp Rise Last December
Xinhua News Agency, Washington, February 3 (Reporter He Ying)  The US Department of Commerce issued a report on the 3rd, stating that the construction spending in the United States last December rose 1.2% over November to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 858.3 billion US dollars.
The report said spending on residential construction last December reached 434.6 billion US dollars on an annualized basis after a seasonal adjustment, up 2.9% over November.
Analysts think that the low interest rate is a key factor for the robust growth in residential construction.
Currently, the US Federal Reserve still keeps the short-term interest rate at 1.2%, the lowest level in 41 years.
However, in contrast with the residential construction, the commercial construction spending in the United States last December was 158.6 billion US dollars on an annualized basis after a seasonal adjustment, down 1.9% from November.
Analysts think that given the current uncertainties about the economic prospect of the United States, businesses are reluctant to increase their investment in building factories and other facilities.
In addition, concerns about terrorist attacks have also adversely affected the commercial construction activities.  Although Bush signed the Terrorism Insurance Act in November last year, it is not sufficient to dispel investors' worries.
For the entire year last year, the growth rate of the US residential construction spending went down from the 2.7% in 2001 to 0.4%, the lowest level since 1991.
(International)  UN Inspectors Found Another Empty Chemical Warhead in Iraq
Xinhua News Agency, Baghdad, February 4 (Reporters Wang Bo and Liang Youchang)  UN arms inspection team spokesman Hiro Ueki said in a press release on the 4th that the inspectors found another empty chemical warhead on that day when they were inspecting some suspicious sites in Iraq.
Hiro Ueki said that the inspectors found this empty chemical warhead when they were inspecting the Al Taji Ammunition Depot in the northern suburb of Baghdad.
The warhead was tagged and kept in good condition.
He said this warhead is similar to those 12 empty chemical warheads that inspectors found at an ammunition storage area in southern Iraq on January 16.
Shortly after the inspectors found that batch of empty chemical warheads, Iraqi side announced they had found four similar warheads at al-Taji area and turned them to the inspectors.
Blix, chairman of the UN Verification, Monitoring and Inspection Commission, said while he was presenting an inspection report to the Security Council on January 27 that the Iraqi government should have voluntarily declared those empty chemical warheads in the arms report it submitted instead of letting inspectors go in search of them.
On the very same day, the inspectors also inspected seven sites near Baghdad, including a water purification facility, an agro-chemicals plant, two missiles plants and a former center for developing chemical weapons.
The inspectors in the northern Iraqi city of Mosul inspected a sugar factory and a yeast factory on the 4th.
Shanghai Police Confirm Two Men who Fell from Air France Jetliner Were Turkish Nationals
Xinhua News Agency, Shanghai, February 10 (Yang Jinzhi and Yang Hua)  After comparing fingerprints, Shanghai police have confirmed that the two men who fell from Air France Flight AF112 on January 23 were Turkish nationals.  They were respectively Karacoban, 20, and Ozuyaman, 19.
At 10:58 a.m. on January 23, Shanghai Municipal Public Security Bureau got a 110 emergency call, reporting an incident of men falling from the sky in Shengang Village, Laogang Township in Nanhui District.  Two male foreign nationals were said to have fallen from an airplane flying from south to north in preparation for landing.
After an examination of the scene and some investigations, Shanghai police quickly came to the conclusion that the dead fell from the landing gear compartments of Air France Flight FAF112 that was entering China's airspace.  The conclusion was confirmed by Air France.
After that, Shanghai police conducted the investigations in cooperation with the French and Turkish consulates general in Shanghai and then the police authorities in the two countries.
In early February, based on the belongings left behind by the two dead men on the scene and the materials provided by the Turkish police such as fingerprints and identification cards believed to be of the dead, Shanghai police made technical comparisons and were convinced that the fingerprints were identical, thus confirming finally the true identities of the two dead men.
(HK, Macau, Taiwan) Macau Posted a 13% Budget Surplus Last Year
Xinhua News Agency, Macau, February 10 (Reporter Li Jie)  According to sources from the Macau Special Administrative Region government, Macau's budget for fiscal 2002 ran pretty well with a surplus of 1.7 billion pacatas for the whole year, equal to 13% of the year's budget.
It is said that Macau's budget for fiscal 2002 was originally set as a deficit budget, with a deficit between revenues and expenditures of 870 million pacatas.
Offset with the surplus from fiscal 2001, the budget still had a balance of deficit of 300 million pacatas which was expected to be paid off with years of accumulated surpluses.
However, in actual operations, the SAR government managed to increase sources of revenues and reduce expenditures.  The actual revenues increased about 10% over the original budget while the actual expenditures decreased 8% from the budget.
Avila, director of Finance Services Bureau, said that Macau's increased budget revenue for fiscal 2002 was mainly made possible by the successful opening up of the gambling industry and telecommunication industry as well as the rebound in the real estate sector.
Statistics show that in 2002, tax revenues from gambling posted a significant rise over 2001; in addition to a dramatic increase in the number of new telecommunications subscribers, office building transactions started to pick up, netting a gain of about 30% in property transfer stamp tax alone.
(HK, Macau, Taiwan)  Macau Passes Double Taxation Relief Bill
Xinhua News Agency, Macau, February 11  Legislative Assembly of Macau Special Administrative Region passed a bill on the 10th authorizing the SAR chief executive to sign double taxation relief treaties with other countries and regions.
The so-called "double taxation" means two or more tax jurisdictions levy the same or similar taxes on one taxpayer simultaneously for the same taxables.
According to the bill, if double taxation is levied on one and the same taxpayer in Macau, the SAR chief executive has the authority to take necessary regulatory measures till an interjurisdictional double taxation relief treaty is signed.
The member of the Legislative Assembly in charge of examining this bill entitled "Tax System with Respect to International or Interjurisdictional Double Taxation" said that the tax system must promptly keep pace with the current increasing tendency toward globalization of economy, otherwise it will restrict the flow of capital, commodities and personnel.
It is necessary that Macau sign a double taxation relief treaty with other regions as this will not only help Macau to attract foreign capital, but also facilitate Macau's overseas investment.  It is a critical link in promoting the economic growth.
It is said that at present, Macau has already had a double taxation relief treaty with Portugal, and is discussing with mainland China about signing a treaty which is expected to be reached in the middle of this year.
(From hometown of overseas Chinese)  Quanzhou Recognized as "China's Manufacturing Base of Household Products"
Xinhua News Agency, Fuzhou, February 12 (Reporter Wang Fanfan)  Quanzhou, a region with fast growth of privatized economy, has been recently recognized as "China's Manufacturing Base of Household Products."  A grand award ceremony has been just held by the relevant departments to specially celebrate the occasion.
Shengxin Township which won the title of "China's Manufacturing Base of Household Products" is a new township located in the central part of Nan-an City, hometown of the national hero Zheng Chenggong, in the coastal economic development zone of southern Fujian Province.
Established in 1999 with an area of 61 square kilometers, the township has 11 administrative villages.  It has a population of 45,000 who have over 20,000 relatives residing overseas and compatriots in Hong Kong, Macau and Taiwan.
Committed to developing the household products industry, Shengxin Township at present has formed a complete manufacturing chain led by production of household items.
The township boasts more than 70 manufacturers of household products with total fixed assets worth over 300 million yuan.  More than 10,000 people are engaged in the manufacture and sales of household products with an annual export volume of nearly 200 million yuan.
Main products include various kinds of thin plastic packing bags, colored bags, household plasticware, melamine dinnerware and women's sanitary belts, baby diapers, napkin, knitwear, and children's outdoor gear.  With hundreds of varieties, and nearly a thousand specifications, these products are much sought after everywhere in China and in other countries and regions such as the United States, Canada, Europe, and Southeast Asia.
In 2002, the output value of household products in the township reached 504 million yuan, accounting for 70% of the township's total industrial output value.  14.08 million yuan has been paid in industrial and commercial taxes, which was 67.1% of the township's total tax revenue.
(International) France Proposes to Security Council to Strengthen Arms Inspection in Iraq
Xinhua News Agency, United Nations, February 11 (Reporter Guo Lijun)   On the 11th, the French mission to the United Nations circulated an unofficial proposal among the Security Council members for stronger arms inspection in Iraq.
France proposes to double the official personnel currently conducting arms inspection in Iraq within the short term and then gradually increase the number of arms inspectors till it triples what it is now.
At present, there are about 110 official arms inspectors in Iraq.
France also calls for intensifying aerial reconnaissance or employing the UN security guards to ensure "a freeze" of suspicious sites in Iraq, and using mobile customs patrol units to beef up the inspection of goods entering Iraq.
At the same time, France proposes that a new intelligence agency be established in New York to coordinate all the countries in their efforts to provide intelligence to the UN Monitoring, Verification and Inspection Commission and the International Atomic Energy Agency.
The above-mentioned two agencies are asked to list in order of importance the missions of disarmament Iraq has not accomplished.
It is also proposed that a liaison officer be appointed in Iraq to take charge of daily communication with Iraqi authorities.
France circulated its proposals in the form of "a non-paper."
During the discussion of the Resolution 1441, France and Russia both used this form to express their views.
According to the relevant regulations of the Security Council, this kind of "non-paper" is not as formal as a resolution draft, but it can be upgraded into a resolution draft any time upon the request of the proposing country.
Diplomats here noted that the content of the French proposals does not go beyond the speech made by French Foreign Minister de Villepin on the 5th after US Secretary of State Powell's intelligence briefing, and that this non-paper is a summary and refinement of France's position on arms inspection in Iraq upon the request of some Security Council members.
(HK, Macau, Taiwan) Mainland Tourists Show Strong Purchasing Power in Macau
Xinhua News Agency, Macau, February 14 (Reporter Li Jie)  In recent years, not only has the number of mainland tourists to Macau been increasing but their purchasing power has also been growing rapidly.
According to official statistics released by Macau SAR government, non-resident tourists spent 4.7 billion patacas in Macau in the fourth quarter last year.  Among them, mainland tourists spent 3.3 billion patacas, topping all the tourists from different places of residence.
Since mainland China eased up its policy on overseas travels, the number of mainland tourists taking package tours to Hong Kong and Macau, and going on overseas tours beyond has soared.
Of the 11.53 million visitors Macau hosted last year, 4.24 million were from mainland China.  With the number of visitors coming to Macau surpassing that to Hong Kong for the first time in the fourth quarter last year, mainland China has become the largest source of tourists for Macau.
Although these tourists stay in Macau for an average of 28.8 hours, the average spending per capita reached 2,560 patacas, 64% higher than the mean value spent by tourists from all places.
Analyses show that jewelry and watches, clothing and fabrics, are the hottest commodities among all tourists, accounting respectively for 27% and 23% of their spending in Macau.
The average non-shopping spending, excluding gambling, was 837 patacas per capita, of which food and beverage, and accommodation, the two major categories, accounted for 41% and 36% respectively.
(International) Studies Find Preemies' Learning Disabilities Surmountable
Xinhua News Agency, Washington, February 15  Low birth-weight preemies are generally slow in their mental development and may easily encounter learning disabilities.
Researchers at Yale University in the United States recently found that this kind of learning disabilities can be surmounted as preemies grow older.
Studies confirm that the neurological system of preemies with birth weight lower than 1,500 gram is prone to problems.  As many as 50% of such preemies need special care while attending school.
Although many earlier experiments show that animals can recover from initial brain damages, there haven't been any related reports of preemies' recovery from brain damage.
According to the media report here, researchers at Yale University have tracked and monitored 300 children born prematurely and given them IQ tests when they were at ages of 3, 4 1/2, 6, and 8.  Most of them are found to continuously gain their learning abilities as time passes.
Tests show that of the preemies classified as "mentally retarded" at the age of 3, half have reached the average level in verbal comprehension and IQ tests after five years.
However, about 23% of the infants have shown no improvement of their mental development due to their severe brain damage caused by cerebral hemorrhage.
Researchers said one of the key factors in the mental development of preemies lies in the family environment.
Children who are from a family of three and whose mothers had high levels of education scored better in IQ tests.
Japan's Bell to Invest in Developing Internet Videophones in Shenyang
Xinhua News Agency, Shenyang, February 16 (Reporter Shi Qingwei)  Bell Net Corporation of Japan has just signed an agreement with the administrative board of Hunnan New District of the City of Shenyang to set up a jointly-funded enterprise and plans to invest 3 billion yen in developing software and hardware for Internet videophones in Hunnan New District.
It is said that Phase 1 of the construction project of this jointly-funded enterprise is slated to be completed between April 2003 to March 2005.  By 2005, the enterprise will have 3,000 employees  and become a key R & D and manufacturing base of software and hardware for Internet videophones in northern China.
Industrial experts believe, as China's technology for Internet videophones is still in the stage of research and development, whereas Bell Net Corporation of Japan is the world's leading player in this field, this project promises good future in China.
Established in 1989, Bell Net Corporation is an emerging IT enterprise in Japan mainly engaged in the development and manufacture of software and hardware for computer Internet phone, and network communications service.  Its sales last year were 12.4 billion yen.
Shenyang, Liaoning Province, is the economic center of northeastern China.
According to Wang, Xiangkun, deputy mayor of Shenyang, the development of Hunnan New District is oriented towards building a key IT industrial base.  At present, more and more foreign IT coorporations are coming to set up their businesses in Hunnan.
(International) China and Chile Sign Memorandum on Application of Animal and Plant Sanitary Measures
Xinhua News Agency, Santiago, February 17 (Reporter Hou Yaoqi)  On the 17th, China's National Quality Inspection Bureau and the Ministry of Agriculture of Chile signed here a memorandum regarding the "Agreement on the Application of Sanitary and Phytosanitary Measures."
According to the memorandum, China and Chile will formulate inspection and quarantine requirements for the import and export of animals and plants, animal and plant products and foodstuffs in conformity with the regulations of this agreement and the standards set forth by the World Animal Health Organization, International Plant Protection Convention and the Codex Alimentarius Commission.
The memorandum also stipulates that both sides should conduct inspection and quarantine of the imported and exported animals and plants, animal and plant products and foodstuffs in strict accordance with the agreement the two countries have signed or the inspection and quarantine requirements agreed upon.  The two countries should rely more on scientific basis in dealing with the issue of market entry permission for animals and plants, and animal and plant products and foodstuffs and accompany the exportation of the above products with inspection and quarantine certificates signed by the exporters.
Ge Rongzhi, the visiting vice chairman of China's National Quality Inspection Bureau, and Barrera, acting minister of agriculture of Chile, signed the memorandum.
Euro-zone Trade Surplus Rose to 102.3 Billion Euros Last Year
Xinhua News Agency, Brussels, February 19 (Reporter Feng Jian)  According to the latest statistics report released by Eurostat on the 19th, due to the sharp drop in imports, the euro-zone posted an external trade surplus of 102.3 billion euros in 2002, an increase of more than double over the preceding year.
The statistics report showed that in 2001 the trade surplus in the euro-zone was 49.5 billion euros.
Last year, the trade surplus for the 15 EU nations was 6.1 billion euros.
According to the report, the sharp decline in imports was the main reason for the increase of the trade surplus.
Based on statistics, imports to the euro-zone and the entire EU fell 4% as compared with 2001, whereas exports increased by 1%.
In the first eleven months of 2002, the imports to the 15 EU nations from Japan and the United States fell 12% and 11% respectively, while exports to Japan and Switzerland also fell 6%.
With respect to the external trade of the EU member states, Germany registered the largest trade surplus of 117.9 billion euros. On the other hand, Britain, with a trade deficit of 63.6 billion euros, became the state with the largest trade deficit in the European Union.
Financial Crimes Dropped to 13-year Low in Shanghai, Zhejiang and Fujian
Xinhua News Agency, Shanghai, February 20 (Reporter Wang Hongyang)  In Shanghai, Zhejiang and Fujian, the two provinces and one municipality located in China's financial and trade center and at the forefront of financial reform, the number of financial crimes in 2002 fell 44.4% compared with that in the previous year, with a drop of 22.8% in the amount of money involved.  The number of cases dropped to a 13-year low.
According to the latest news from Shanghai branch of People's Bank of China, in recent years, full improvements in the investigation and conviction process of financial crimes and the prevention system in financial sectors in Shanghai, Zhejiang and Fujian have effectively curbed the trend of rising financial violations.  As a result, the number of crimes, the amount of money involved, the number of big and key cases and the annual total number of cases have shown a good tendency of remarkable decline.
Statistics show that compared with the preceding year, the number of financial crimes in these two provinces and one municipality dropped 22.9% and 35.4% respectively in 1999 and 2000.  The amount of money involved fell 41% and 11.2% respectively; and the amount of money involved dropped 35.3% in 2001.
It is said that in Shanghai, Zhejiang and Fujian, comprehensive crime prevention systems have been successively established which integrate "investigation, education, reform, regulation and surveillance" appropriate to the local financial sectors.  At the same time, social networks of financial crime prevention have also been formed in conjunction with the business operation and supervision departments within the banks, insurance companies and securities firms as well as the local judicial agencies.
(International) EU to Stop Beef Imports from Paraguay
Xinhua News Agency, Buenos Aires, February 20  (Reporter Shen An)  From Asuncion: According to the announcement of the Paraguay Ministry of Agriculture and Livestock on the 20, the EU has decided to stop beef imports from Paraguay due to the Foot and Mouse Disease outbreak in the country.
As reported by the media in Paraguay, Baumgarten, Paraguay's minister of Agriculture and Livestock, announced that the EU made the above decision at the meeting held on the 19th.
In early February, an inspection team from the European Commission's Food and Veterinary Office submitted a report after conducting an inspection in Paraguay.  The report said Paraguay still failed to take sufficient measures related to FMD and there are "serious problems" with the FMD monitoring and inspection systems.  Neither the sanitary control, professional competency, nor the export certification system met the EU requirements.
Paraguay discovered its first case of FMD last October.  After that, prevention and control measures against the plague were taken with the help of other Southern Common Market member states.
Each year, Paraguay exports about 60,000 tons of beef, mainly to countries such as Brazil and Chile.
These countries have already stopped beef imports from Paraguay.
From January to October last year, the EU imported 567 tons of beef from Paraguay.
(International) Austrian Researchers Discover Spinal Marrow Cells that Trigger Chronic Pain
Xinhua News Agency, Vienna, February 20 (Reporter Lin Chuan)  Researchers at Vienna University in Austria found in human spinal marrow a group of neurological cells that have long lasting memory and will become highly agitated the moment they are slightly stimulated by pain. This is another step forward in finding the cause of chronic pain.
Chronic pain sufferers are hypersensitive to pain and eventually have to live with pain in their daily life.
However, what causes the disorder has so far remained virtually unknown.
According to the report by Austrian News Agency, the research team led by J黵gen Sandk黨ler, head of neurophysiology department at the Brain Research Institute, Vienna University, found while doing a biopsy on tissue slices that some spinal marrow cells exhibiting no unusual behavior under normal condition show agitation when stimulated by pain.
The reaction increases as the pain stimuli intensifies.
However, different from other neurons, this group of spinal marrow cells subsequently become oversensitive to pain stimuli and respond dramatically to even minuscule pain stimuli.
Researchers also found that there is a special pathway in spinal marrow cells.  When the cells are stimulated, these pathways will open up to allow in calcium ions, thus setting off a further chain reaction.
According to Sandk黨ler, the reason why chronic pain sufferers are sensitive to even slight pain is that this type of spinal marrow cells have a long-lasting memory which retains "traces of pain."
He noted that this finding can put people on track to search for ways of erasing this memory.
Consumer prices in China up in January
Xinhua News Agency, Beijing, February 21 (Reporter Liu Dongkai)  The monthly report released by the National Bureau of Statistics on the 21st showed that in January the consumer price index in China rose 0.4% over the same month last year, the first rise against the consecutive year-on-year decline in the past 12 months.
NBS said that the rise in consumer price index is mainly due to the fact that this year the Spring Festival was at the end of January while last year's was in February.  As the peak periods of holiday spending were different, they were to some extent incomparable.
The other reason is that the weather this year was colder than it was last year.
Of the 31 provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions surveyed in China, 22 posted a year-on-year rise in the CPI, while seven saw a year-on-year drop.
Statistics show that of all the consumer goods, prices of seasonal goods and services such as fresh vegetables, fruits and entertainment went up, while prices of grain, apparel and durable consumer goods and others related to the long term consumption dropped.
The price hikes of gasoline and diesel led to the rise in the price of propane, bringing up further the prices of living expenses.
China Releases First Sex Education TV Series for Elementary and Secondary Schools
Xinhua News Agency, Haikou, February 21 (Zhang Chuanxuan and Liu Wei)  China's first VCD of TV series "Lectures on Sex Education for Elementary and Secondary Schools" has recently premiered in Haikou, setting off strong percussion among teachers and students alike.
The sex education series released by Electronic Audio and Visual Publishing House of Hainan Province consists of the elementary school edition, middle school edition and high school edition.
According to different age groups, the series presents a progressive, step by step introduction to sexuality, including such special topics as puberty, impregnation, procreation, AIDS prevention and care, and sexual psychology, providing answers to questions children have in their minds with vivid audio and visual aids.
At the premiere held in Zhenfa School in Hainan, over a hundred middle school students watched attentively and in absolute silence.
At beginning, many girls merely lowered their heads and kept reading books, unwilling to raise their heads.  Gradually they became relaxed enough to watch the screen.
Lai Ruixing, principal of the middle school, said that schools are badly in need of such materials on sex education as they can eliminate the embarrassment that teachers skip textbook chapters while students read them in secret.
The release of this series has also been endorsed by the relevant departments.
In November 2002, the TV series "Lectures on Sex Education for Elementary and Secondary Schools" won the 10th China's Population and Culture Award issued by the State Family Planning Commission, the China Population and Culture Promotion Association and others.
First Group Package Tour of Chinese Nationals to Malta and Egypt to Set out at End of March
Xinhua News Agency, Beijing, February 22 (Reporter Qian Chunxian)  The reporter was told on the 22nd that the first group package tour of Chinese nationals to Malta and Egypt will start out here on March 28.
The Chinese tourists can travel across the two continents of Europe and Africa within ten days.
As planned, the tourists can board on an EgyptAir flight to take off from Beijing and proceed to fly to Malta after enjoying a five-day tour of Cairo.
The entire journey is estimated to take 10 days at the cost of about 16,000 yuan for the whole package.
Malta is situated in southern Europe adjacent to Italy.
The scenery of blue sky and ocean as well as a mild Mediterranean climate has made Malta a famous tourist attraction in the world.
Egypt is one of the world's four ancient civilizations, and its long history has drawn tourists from all parts of the world.
Malta became the first European country to gain Destination Status for Chinese nationals' personal leisure tours in 2001.  Egypt became the first African country to gain the same status in 2002.
EgyptAir officially opened the first direct flight route from Cairo to Beijing in January this year.
This first group package tour is jointly promoted by Malta Tourism Authority, Egyptian Tourist Bureau and Guang Zhi Lu International Travel Agency.
(International) Blix Demands Iraq Start Destroying al-Samoud Missiles within a Week
Xinhua News Agency, United Nations, February 22  According to the local media reports on the 22nd, Hans Blix, chairman of the UN Monitoring, Verification Inspection Commission (UNMOVIC), has issued an ultimatum to Iraq, demanding that Iraq start destroying its al-Samoud missiles within a week.
Buchanan, press secretary for UNMOVIC, said that Blix has handed this ultimatum regarding "the destruction of 'al-Samoud 2' missiles and related equipment" to Mohammed al-Douri, Iraq's ambassador to the United Nations, demanding that Iraq start destroying the proscribed weapons before March 1.
A duplicate of the ultimatum has already been submitted to the UN Security Council.
The experts believe that this ultimatum has put Iraqi President Saddam Hussein in a dilemma.
By destroying these missiles, Iraq will lose the key weapons to defend itself against the US attacks, while rejecting UNMOVIC's request will give the United States and Britain more excuses for taking military actions against Iraq.
Blix and Baradei, director general of the International Atomic Energy Agency, said in their second report on arms inspection in Iraq submitted to the Security Council on the 14th that the evaluation by the UN missile experts has found the range of al-Samoud missiles to exceed 150 kilometers, which violates the related UN resolutions.
(International) Georgian President Stresses on Preventing Illegal Chechen Armed Groups from Entering Pankisi Gorge
Xinhua News Agency, Moscow, February 24 (Reporter Dong Longjiang)  From Tbilisi: Georgian President Shevardnadze stressed in his national radio address on the 24th that at present, the top priority of Georgia's law enforcement agencies is to prevent and completely stop illegal Chechen armed elements from infiltrating the Pankisi Gorge.
Shevardnadze said although Georgia's internal troops, police forces, security departments and ministry of defense cleaned up the foreign armed groups which infiltrated the Pankisi Gorge in last year's special operations, it is possible that some illegal armed elements, disguised as refugees, are still hiding in the Pankisi Gorge.
Shevardnadze said that Georgia's law enforcement agencies have the capacity to uncover these illegal armed elements.
At the same time, he announced that Georgia's law enforcement agencies will soon continue their crackdown on illegal armed rebels in the Pankisi Gorge.
In his address, Shevardnadze emphasized the importance of having cooperation and exchange of intelligence with Russia and the United States in this regard.
The Pankisi Gorge, situated within the territory of Georgia, borders on Chechnya in Russia.
Russia believes that a large number of Chechen armed elements are hiding in the Pankisi Gorge and accuses Georgia of providing refuge to them.
Last year, the relationship between Russia and Georgia was strained for some time due to the issue of the Pankisi Gorge.
(International) NYSE Down Again as US and Britain Submit Proposals for War on Iraq
Xinhua News Agency, New York, February 24  Investors became worried again about the prospect of war as the United States and Britain insisted on making new proposals to the UN Security Council for military strikes on Iraq.  On February 24, all three major stock indices on New York Stock Exchange plummeted to a new low since January 30.
In addition, the latest report on the performance of US retailers showed that US retail sales in February offered no reason for optimism, further shattering consumer confidence.
Dow Jones Industrial 30 Index fell sharply 159.87 points, or 2%, to close at 7858.24 on the very same day.  The tech-heavy Nasdaq Composite Index dropped 26.64 points, or 2%, to 1322.38  The Standard and Poor's 500 fell 15.59 points, or 1.8%, to close at 832.58.
Although both the NYSE Composite Index and Russell 2000 Index, which represents small companies, plunged, the American Stock Exchange Market Index posted a rise.
The decliners over advancers on NYSE was 5-2.  The trade volume dropped to 1.53 billion shares from 1.71 billion shares the previous trading day.
China Red Cross Raises Charity Funds for Disaster-hit Xinjiang
Xinhua News Agency, Beijing, February 25 (Reporter Wu Jing)  China Red Cross Society set up a donation hotline and account on the 25th, calling for people from all walks of life both at home and abroad to help assist their compatriots in Xinjiang that was hit by an earthquake on the 24th.
CRCS' donation hotline number is 010-65139999 (24 hours).
The account number is 02000010090144132-52 at Dong Si Nan Sub-branch of China Industrial and Commercial Bank.
After the earthquake struck on the 24, CRCS immediately sent 250,000 yuan to disaster-hit Xinjiang and again dispatched a disaster-relief team to the stricken area on the 25th.
On the 24th, an earthquake measuring 6.8 on the Richter scale hit Bachu-Jiashi area in southern Xinjiang.
As of early morning of the 25th, the death toll has risen to 261.  2,050 people were seriously injured; and 8,861 houses collapsed.
At present, with night temperatures in the disaster-hit area at about minus 2 degrees Celsius, the earthquake victims are in urgent need of foods and clothes.
(International) Brazil's Risk Index Drops
Xinhua News Agency, Brasilia, February 27 (Reporter Yang Limin)  Brazil's risk index fell to 1191 points on the 27th, down 2.37% from the previous day.
This is the first time that this index has dropped below 1200 points in the 8 months since the financial turbulence broke out in Brazil in June last year.
In the meantime, Brazil's bonds traded on the international market rose by 0.42% on the very same day to the 74% of their face value.
This is also the best record in 8 months.
A country's risk index is closely linked to the price of bonds.  The higher the index is, the lower the price of bonds will be.
Last year, Brazil's risk index once exceeded 2400 points, driving down the price of bonds to 48% of their face value.
Since the new administration took power this year, Brazil's risk index has been continuously dropping.
Recently, there has been an increase in the demand of Brazil's bonds as foreign investors think they are cheap in price and high in returns, resulting in a faster drop of Brazil's risk index.
However, analysts pointed out that although international investors are currently in favor of Brazil's bonds, in the event of a US-Iraq war when there will be a decrease in foreign investment, the country's risk index may rise again to trigger another drop in the price of bonds.
No Signal from ESA's Beagle 2 Probe Since Its Landing on Mars
(Agence France-Presse, London, 1st) - European Space Agency (ESA) spokesman Bonacina said the U.S. orbiter failed to communicate with the European lander Beagle 2 since its landing on Mars.  The hope to pick up a signal from Beagle 2 is now entrusted to its mother ship, the Mars Express.
"We did not have any progress," said Bonacina.
"Right now, we have to put our hopes on the mother ship.  We have to wait for the Mars Express to gather information," he said.
U.S. Mars probe, the Odyssey spacecraft, did not pick up any signal from the European Mars probe, Beagle 2, yesterday.  Beagle 2 carries on the mission to search for signs of life on Mars after it separated from Mars Express for a landing on Mars.
United States National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) launched the Mars Odyssey into Mars orbit for another exploration mission.
The Paris based ESA said the Mars Express, an orbiter built by Europe, has now entered the polar orbit.  It will hopefully transmit some signals back next week.
The Beagle 2 was scheduled to land on Mars on Christmas Day, but its signal is still difficult to pin down.
Beagle 2 became the first European spacecraft to land on another planet after it was released from Mars Express on December 19.
During its eighteen-day mission, Beagle 2 was programmed to collect rock and soil, analyze signal transmission and search for all forms of life.
Some scientists have boldly predicted that the British-built spacecraft might have fallen into a crater.
Pakistani President Musharraf Won the Trust Vote in Senate and Lower House
(Agence France-Presse, Islamabad, 1st) - As legislators of Islamist parties abstained and opposition parties boycotted the vote, Pakistani President Musharraf has today won the vote of confidence in both Senate and Lower House that legitimizes his ruling until 2007.
Information Minister Rashid told AFP reporter, "Musharraf has won a majority vote in the national assembly.
There was not a single vote against him."
In the 342-seat lower house, 191 legislators voted in favor of Musharraf.  Legislators of Islamist parties had abstained from voting while opposition parties boycotted the controversial vote of confidence.
Musharraf made concessions to the six Islamist parties and agreed to resign as army chief.  At the same time, Musharraf has to obtain Supreme Court approval within 1 month if he ever sacks the parliament.
In the 100-seat senate, 56 senators voted to support Musharraf.  The 42 senators of Islamist and opposition parties had either abstained or boycotted the vote.
Musharraf obtained power in a coup in October 1999 and has refused to step down since then.
Burundian President: Ex-rebels to Join Army's Leadership
(Agence France-Presse, Bujumbura, 1st) - Burundian President Ndayizeye said today in his New Year's speech to the nation that the post-war armed forces chief of staff is be formed before next week and will include leaders of former rebels.
The former rebel, "Forces for the Defense of Democracy" (FDD), welcomed the move and applauded it as a "crucial step" in the creation of new armed forces.
According to President Ndayizeye's televised speech, former rebel fighters in Burundi's 10-year civil war must be settled in by January 5.  The new army leadership is to be made up of 40 percent former rebels and should be in place by January 7.
"All parties that signed the (November 2003 ceasefire) accord should finish the cantoning of their fighters by January 5, 2004, at the latest," Ndayizeye said.
He also said the integration of ex-rebels in the chief of staff should be put in place before January 7.
The exercise mainly concerns the FDD, the largest of the six rebel movements that signed the accord.
The seventh rebel movement, the "National Liberation Forces", has refused to sign the peace accord.
Burundi's civil war between Hutu rebels and Tutsi government troops has claimed some 300,000 lives since 1993.
China Seized 186 Tons of American Beef
(Agence France-Presse, Beijing, 2nd) - China's state-owned media, the "Beijing Youth Daily", reported today that related authority commenced an inspection on meat product markets and had seized 186 tons of American beef in Beijing yesterday amid concerns that imported beef could be contaminated with the mad cow disease virus.
The Beijing Youth Daily pointed out that the seized beef would be disposed of after being examined according to advice from the Ministry of Agriculture.
China was one of the more than 30 countries that suspended the import of U.S. beef products last week.
The ban applies to all cow-related products except milk and other dairy products, leather and gelatin used for photography.
According to Beijing Youth Daily, the Beijing Agriculture Bureau recently issued a series of prevention and monitoring orders and launched a citywide market inspection.
At this moment, the mad cow disease has not been found in any city or anywhere in China.
The aforesaid confiscation of beef was the second seizure in a week.  Before that, related authority has seized 60 kilograms of beef onboard a U.S. cargo ship in Ningbo, Zheijiang province.  Those beef were produced in the U.S. Washington State where the mad cow disease case was found.
It is not clear how much U.S. beef China has imported but Commerce Ministry statistics indicate a value of US$532 million for imported meat products from U.S. in last year.
During January to July last year, China imported US$316 million of meat products from the United States.
North Korea Said to Allow a U.S. Delegation to Visit Yongbyon Nuclear Facilities
(Agence France-Presse, Washington, 2nd) - The USA Today newspaper reported today that Pyongyang agreed to allow a U.S. delegation, which includes a top-notch nuclear scientist, to visit North Korea's Yongbyon nuclear facilities next week.
A member of the delegation told USA Today that the Bush Administration approved the delegation's North Korea visit, which has been scheduled for Jan 6-10.
This will be the first time that a delegation from a foreign country is allowed to visit North Korea's controversial nuclear facilities after the country expelled United Nations nuclear inspectors a year ago.
The U.S. delegation includes a China expert from Stanford University, two Senate foreign policy aides and a former State Department official who has negotiated with North Korea.
The delegation's nuclear specialist, Hecker, had led the U.S. Los Alamos National Laboratory from 1985 to 1997.  The first atomic bomb was developed in that laboratory.
Before that, North Korea recently notified the U.S. embassy in Beijing that Pyongyang is ready to attend the delayed second round six-nation talks on the Korean Peninsula nuclear crisis.
U.S. officials pointed out earlier in the week that Pyongyang signaled its readiness to attend the six-nation talks to be convened early this year.
The first round six-nation talks was convened last August in Beijing and ended without any conclusion.  North Korea said later the discussion was "useless".
A second round of six-nation talks was scheduled for December last year but was pushed back to early this year because of disagreement as to what steps should be taken to solve the problem.
Washington has demanded North Korea to scrap its nuclear program unilaterally, while Pyongyang insists on a legally binding security guarantee from United States as a condition for any agreement to abandon the nuclear program.
U.S. Government Said It Had No Part in the Delegations to North Korea
(Agence France-Presse, Washington, 2nd) - U.S. government said today it had no part in the two delegations planning to visit North Korea.  The delegations are hoping to visit the Yongbyon nuclear power plant, the trigger of the diplomatic storm between the two countries.
Two teams -- one of academics and scientists, while the other of Congress aides -- plan to visit North Korea as China strives to bring U.S. and North Korea plus Japan, Russia and South Korea back to the negotiating table.
"We have nothing to do with this group or groups and their reported plans to visit North Korea," said State Department deputy spokesman, Ereli.
"I think the public should clearly understand that the groups or individuals are not representing the government," Ereli said.
One delegation is led by a senior China expert from Stanford University, a nuclear specialist, Hecker, who is a former director of Los Alamos National Laboratory, and also includes Pritchard, a State Department envoy talked with North Korea last year.
USA Today newspaper said today the delegation would visit the Yongbyon nuclear power plant but a member of the delegation told AFP the Yongbyon visit is still not certain.
There is now some uncertainty to the visit after it was widely reported by media.  It is not clear whether the team would still be allowed to enter North Korea.
Luse, an aide to Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman Lugar, and Jannuzi, an aide who works for the ranking Democrat of the panel, Senator Biden, will lead the other delegation.
U.S. Waiting for Israel's Clarification on Golan Heights Settlement Plans
(Agence France-Presse, Washington, 2nd) - The United States government said today that Israel had not provided a satisfactory answer to U.S. request for clarification about the reported plans to expand Jewish settlement in the occupied Golan Heights.
State Department said Israel responded to U.S. after the reports on Wednesday (31st).
However, Israel's response failed to remove the doubts of U.S. government.
"We have received an answer but not a very clear one.  We are not sure about the situation," said State Department deputy spokesman, Ereli.
He reiterated Washington's opposition to any new settlement activity.
"We have said clearly that we oppose any new settlement activity.  We do not believe such activities are constructive and they should all be frozen," Ereli said.
Media reports said Israel was planning to build nine new settlements in Golan Heights, which was seized from Syria in 1967.  The plans will boost the Jewish population from 10,500 to around 15,000 in three years.
Many Arabian countries condemned the occupying move as illegal.
Toyota Prius Sedan Named North American Car of the Year
(Agence France-Presse, Detroit, 4th) - In the International Auto Show in Detroit, journalists today named Toyota's Prius sedan North American Car of the Year, while Ford's F-150 full-size pickup was chosen as Truck of the Year.
"This award does a lot to validate the hybrid power train," said Press, Toyota's executive vice president in charge of sales.
The 2004 model year Prius has been redesigned by Toyota.  The hybrid-electric car went on sales in October last year with a price tag of US$20,000.  The initial sales have been better than expected.
Last month, Toyota announced a 31 percent increase in production of Prius.
Press said Toyota is hoping the success of the new Prius will stimulate the sales of a similar hybrid-electric powered sport wagon, the Highlander, when it goes on sale later this year.
The new Highland will appear in the International Auto Show in the next couple of days.
The show today was restricted to media.
Ford's redesigned F-150 pickup won the Truck of the Year honor.
According to Lyons, president of a Ford sales division, F-150 is the best selling model in the world.  The 2004 model year F-150 has been redesigned and set an unprecedented sales record in December last year with 84,600 units sold.
Lyons said Ford Motor Company plans to capitalize on F-150's early success and will make untiring efforts to fulfill the goal of selling one million F-series trucks this year.
Zambia Intends to Deport a British Writer for Insulting the Zambian President
(Agence France-Presse, Lusaka, 5th) - Zambian Home Affairs Minister Shikapwasha said Zambia has ordered the depot of British writer Clarke for "insulting" Zambian President Mwanawasa in his column in a privately-owned newspaper, the "Post".  Clarke has to leave the country within 24 hours.
Shikapwasha told a group of Mwanawasa supporters who marched to Home Affairs Ministry demanding the deportation of Clarke, "Mr. Clarke must leave the country within 24 hours.
I want to announce to the whole nation.  We have already taken actions."
However, Clarke said in his interview by AFP that he has not received any notice.
"I am not aware that a deportation order has been issued," Clarke said.
Home affairs permanent secretary Mumba said earlier he had recommended the interior minister to issue a deportation order.
"When you insult the president of a nation, you are actually insulting the people he represents.  Clarke should go back and start writing about his own people," Mumba said.
Clarke has lived in Zambia for many years and is married to a prominent Zambian women rights' activist.
The editor of the "Post", Mmembe, said he would take responsibility for the article published last Thursday and urged the Zambian government to deal with him rather than Clarke.
In the past, the Zambian government has deported foreigners for allegedly insulting the President or leaders in government.
Koizumi Vowed to Continue Economic Reform This Year
(Agence France-Presse, Tokyo, 5th) - During a press conference on the first working day after the new year holiday, Japanese Prime Minister Junichiro Koizumi vowed to push forward economic reform this year.  "While the economic situation remains difficult, we are finally able to see signs of a recovery," Koizumi said.
Koizumi stressed that, "I will stick to reform policy and push ahead with reforms.
I will continue reform effort until it lead us to a economic recovery."
Koizumi said he would concentrate especially on parliamentary debate on the privatization of the postal services this year.
"We are finally taking actions on the privatization of postal services.  This is the main axle of the economic reforms," he said.
Koizumi added that he hoped to submit legislation on the related plans to the parliament early next year.
Koizumi pledged to fully privatize the postal services, which have 280,000 employees, by 2007.
Postal services in Japan are regarded the biggest bank in the world because of the 355 trillion yen (US$3.3 trillion) in savings and insurance funds that it manages.
However, the gigantic plan is facing tough opposition from conservative lawmakers in the parliament.
The project got started when Koizumi was acting as minister of posts and telecommunications back in 1993.
Analysts said that Japan's economy is forecasted to maintain a steady growth of around two percent this year, but individuals in the country are likely to remain concerned about further salary cuts and layoffs.
Japan's jobless rate remains above five percent as many companies continue their restructuring efforts to secure profits.
U.S. Begins Fingerprinting and Photographing of Foreign Visitors
(Agence France-Presse, Washington, 5th) - In tandem with the support by Singapore (which has the largest airport in Asia) to deploy more air marshals to counter terrorist threat, United States will begin the new measure of fingerprinting and photographing foreign visitors from today.
Washington strengthens its screening of foreign visitors as concerns about security on aviation escalates around the world recently.  In the past week, concerns have prompted the temporary cancellation of several scheduled flights to and fro United States.
Photos and fingerprints are applicable only to foreign visitors that require visas to enter U.S.  The general expectation is about 23 million visitors of this category this year.
The Department of Homeland Security, which implements and runs the "United States Visitor and Immigrant Status Indicator Technology" (US-VISIT), pointed out that citizens from 28 countries, mostly in Europe, are exempted from the aforesaid process.
Immigration organizations criticize the program as an infringement of civil rights and also another step towards a monitored society but Homeland Security Secretary Ridge has been giving every effort to defend the program.
"One of the most important jobs of any government is to protect the security at its borders.  We are launching the program to do this job better and I do not think it is offending.  In fact, the process takes only 15 seconds and obviously no one would care," Ridge said in interview by National Broadcasting Company (NBC).
By 2005, every port of entry on land, sea and air will have the photographic and fingerprinting technology in place.
All U.S. visas and passports will eventually include "biometric identifiers" such as photos and fingerprints etc.
Prior to the launch of the aforesaid program, United States had just raised the level of terror alert in December last year.
U.S. and North Korea Hardened Their Stance: Six-Nation Talks Pushed Back to Middle of the Year
(Agence France-Presse, Seoul, 6th) - South Korea said today that a new round of six-nation talks could be pushed back to the middle of the year as North Korea and the United States hardened their positions.
"I hope talks will be held in the first half of this year at the latest," South Korean Foreign Minister Yoon Young-Kwan told journalists while heading to Chong Wa Dae for a cabinet meeting.
Yoon Young-Kwan made the above comments after Washington dismissed Pyongyang's latest offer to freeze nuclear facilities in exchange for concessions.  Washington further said there are still serious discrepancies to solve before any meeting can be held on the nuclear crisis.
Yoon Young-Kwan said scheduling problems among the six participating nations effectively ruled out the possibility to re-open the six-nation talks in January.
However, he gave no clue as to why a new round of talks could be delayed to June or later.
Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Losyukov blamed the hard stance of United States and North Korea for the delay.
He attended the first round of talks in Beijing in August last year.
"The reasons are the same old ones -- mistrust and very high demands set by both sides," Losyukov told Interfax news agency after a meeting with senior Chinese officials yesterday.
Yoon Young-Kwan suggested the possibility of a long time delay after North Korea demanded concessions from U.S. again before the start of a new round of six-nation talks.
Washington has accused North Korea of setting precedent conditions before the new round of six-nation talks.
United States is seeking North Korea's undertaking to scrap its nuclear weapon program.
North Korea said it would freeze its nuclear facilities if Washington lift economic sanctions against Pyongyang and resume energy aid.
In the past, North Korea also maintained that U.S. has to sign a nonaggression treaty with the country.
SAARC Concluded: A Glimmer to Better Indo-Pakistan Relation
(Agence France-Presse, Islamabad, 6th) - The South Asia summit concluded today after breakthrough talks between rival nuclear giants India and Pakistan were held during the summit and the sealing of a free trade treaty between participants.  This is certainly an epoch-making event for South Asia.
In her speech at the concluding session of 12th summit of South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC), Bangladeshi Prime Minister Zia described "the summit as an important watershed in enhancing South Asian regional cooperation".
Yesterday, Indian Prime Minister Vajpayee and Pakistani President Musharraf met outside the summit for the first time since a near war conflict in 2002.
The hostility between the two super powers in SAARC had already hampered regional cooperation and development.  The leaders of participating nations were all encouraged with the peace momentum generated by the historic meeting between India and Pakistan.
"I think the standpoints of India and Pakistan have clearly changed and they are striding forward to a peace process," Pakistani military analyst Masood told AFP.
As Pakistani President Musharraf declared the official closing of the summit, he praised the consents on antiterrorism, poverty suppression and the construction of a free trade zone from 2006.
He further praised the summit for "injecting new vitality into regional cooperation".
During the summit, the head of state and foreign minister of Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka signed the South Asian Free Trade Agreement (SAFTA), a social charter, poverty fighting strategy, suppression of terrorism and the "Islamabad Declaration".
Bush Praises NASA's Mars Mission
(Agence France-Presse, Washington, 6th) - U.S. President Bush phoned National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) today to congratulate the officials behind the Mars Mission.  The President praises their work, which he thinks helped heal wounds from the Columbia disaster.
"The President thanked the NASA team for their hard work, wisdom and strategy, which once again affirm the great American spirit of exploration," White House spokesman McClellan told the media.
Bush said he shared the wonder inspired when the Spirit robot beamed back from the Red Planet the first color image showing the surroundings of its landed spot.
McClellan said, "The president has the same excitement of all Americans when we see the dramatic scene.
Even though we know that it is only a glimpse of Mars by the Spirit."
"The president strongly supports the exploration of space.  He thanks all member of the NASA team for their efforts, without which U.S. cannot continue to be on the leading edge of space exploration and discovery," McClellan said.
World Renowned Japanese Geisha, Kiharu Nakamura, Died in New York At the Age of 90
(Agence France-Presse, Tokyo, 7th) - Japanese Publisher Soshisha Co. Ltd. said Kiharu Nakamura, who abandoned her career as a geisha about half a century ago and moved to America, has died on the 5th at the age of 90 in her home at New York.
Soshisha Co. Ltd. has published 10 books authored by Kiharu Nakamura, including her autobiographical best seller, the "Edokko Geisha Ichidaiki" (Autobiography of an Edo Geisha), in 1983.
"Edokko Geisha Ichidaiki" has been translated into eight languages and adapted into a television show and a drama in Japan.  The book portrayed Nakamura as the only Japanese geisha who could speak English in the pre-World War II era.
French avant-garde artist Cocteau, king of comedy Chaplin and U.S. baseball star Babe Ruth were among the foreign celebrities who were entertained by Nakamura during their visits to Tokyo.
Soshisha Co. Ltd. said Nakamura inspired Cocteau to write the poem "geisha".
According to a statement from Soshisha Co. Ltd., Nakamura was born in the family of a doctor in Tokyo's Ginza district.  She ignored the objections of her parents and became a geisha at the age of 16 in Shimbashi entertainment district.
After years as a geisha in Shimbashi, Nakamura married a diplomat in 1940 but was divorced shortly afterwards.
After the War, Nakamura went back to work as a geisha in Shimbashi and moved to the United States in 1956.
Apart from teaching traditional Japanese music and dance, Nakamura also served as a consultant for operas, including Madame Butterfly.
Nakamura has a son, who is now working as a university professor of modern arts.
Vietnam Airlines Starts a New Route to Frankfurt, Germany
(Agence France-Presse, Hanoi, 8th) - Vietnam Airlines starts a new twice-weekly service to Frankfurt, Germany.  This is the second destination in Europe after Paris and also part of the airline's rapid route expansion strategy.
Vietnam Airlines will use Boeing 767 aircraft and flies from Ho Chi Minh City every Tuesday and Thursday to Frankfurt with stopovers in Hanoi and Moscow.
"We are establishing this route to serve the large number of Vietnamese living in Germany," a spokesman from Vietnam Airlines said.
Vietnam Airlines is currently flying to more than 20 international destinations.  It has inaugurated a number of new routes last year and is poised for further expansion.
Vietnam Airlines announced plans to double its fleet to 70 aircraft by 2010 earlier this week.
Despite the outbreak of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) and the war in Iraq, Vietnam Airlines carried 4.05 million passengers in 2003, up one percent.
Vietnam Airlines has set a target of carrying five million passengers this year and it expects about half of them (2.4 million) to be foreigners.
Schools Refuse to Admit HIV Kids: Priest Took Issue to Court
(Agence France-Presse, Nairobi, 7th) - D'Agostino is a candid and outspoken U.S. priest, who runs an AIDS orphanage in Nairobi, capital city of Kenya.  In order to plead on behalf of infected kids, he took the Kenyan government to court in an attempt to compel state-owned schools to revoke their exclusion of HIV-infected children.
Notwithstanding an estimated 2.5 million people are carrying the HIV virus in Kenya, AIDS and HIV are still considered taboo topics in Kenya.
D'Agostino runs the Nyumbani orphanage, which has accepted many HIV-positive children.  He claimed that many children in the orphanage had been refused admission to primary schools.  The approach taken by school management is a violation of the government's policy of obligatory universal primary education.
"Refusal to admit children to public schools, especially those infected by HIV, is inhuman, illegal and a gross violation of human rights.  Education is a fundamental right.  Any refusal is a violation of the rights of these children," D'Agostino's lawyer, Namwamba told the court presided by judge Koome.
D'Agostino is seeking a court order forcing state-owned schools to enroll children irrespective of their HIV status.
Kenyan ministry of education, through its lawyer Gacivih, said it was unaware of the discrimination but such school policy appeared sympathetic.
Gacivih said the ministry of education was willing to discuss the matter with Nyumbani Children's Home, which is situated in the northwestern outskirts of Nairobi.
Judge Koome ordered the two sides to hold discussions today and report the conclusion back to court tomorrow.
U.S. to Release Hundreds of Iraqi Prisoners
(Agence France-Presse, Baghdad) - The chief U.S. administrator in Iraq, Bremer, announced in his policy speech that the U.S.-led coalition will release 100 Iraqi detainees on the 8th and also another several hundreds are to be freed in the next couple of weeks.
Bremer, with the interim Governing Council chairman Pachachi at his side, also unveiled a new offer program, under which any assistance leading to the capture of any of the more wanted criminals may receive a maximum reward of US$200,000.
Pachachi praised the coalition for adopting the aforesaid policy and said that was the result of the Governing Council's lobbying effort.
"The Governing Council has been promoting a peaceful reconciliation amongst all citizens of Iraq for a long time.  In order to achieve this objective, we have demanded the coalition to review the problem of prisoners," Pachachi told reporters.
A coalition spokesman who declined to be named said later that a total of 506 detainees would be released in the next couple of weeks.
"The coalition will release the first batch of 100 detainees tomorrow," Bremer said in his short speech to reporters.
Bremer is making a peace gesture at a time when the coalition strives to comfort and reduce accumulated hatred in Saddam's tribe, the Islamic Sunnites community.
Hussein was captured alive by U.S. troops after fleeing and hiding for eight months.
"As the tyrant is now a prisoner and the majority of his gang are either dead or captured, it is now the time for a reconciliation," Bremer said.
The condition for a release is that the prisoner "must renounce violence" and have a guarantor, such as a prominent person in his community or a religious or tribal leader, who will accept responsibility for the good conduct of the individual being freed.
Bremer pointed out that all prisoners to be freed had never directly involved in any attack on the U.S. army or any other fatal attacks and were never involved in criminal activities or crimes against humanity.
Bremer said those to be released "made a mistake but have now waken up to reality" and "we are prepared to give some of them a chance to make a fresh start".
WHO Experts Went to Guangzhou Again for Causes of SARS
(Agence France-Presse, Guangzhou, 10th) - World Health Organization (WHO) today launched their second investigation this year into the reemergence of a severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) case in southern China.
WHO had earlier conducted an investigation into China's first confirmed case of SARS in six months.
In an attempt to identify the cause of a confirmed and a suspected SARS case, a team of WHO experts and Chinese health authorities conducted a surprised inspection on a local seafood and wildlife restaurant in Guangzhou.
"This trip builds on a review of data we collected in our previous trip ... we will try to put different pieces together," said Wadia, a spokesman for WHO in Guangzhou.
At the same time, the Chinese government is urging the public to eradicate rats and other harmful animals that might carry the SARS virus.
Health officials were targeting the aforesaid Seafood restaurant, a 24-hour eatery in Guangzhou's old city districts, because a 20 year-old waitress there was officially diagnosed as a suspected SARS case on Wednesday evening.
"We have examined very carefully for any environmental problems that might exist in the restaurant and we are going to continue with further investigations," WHO expert Breiman said.
"We have talked with the restaurant staff and learned how things worked in the restaurant.  We then looked at the place where food was prepared and a team of environmental experts will continue with that," Breiman said.
Breiman said it was too early to conclude the cause of the disease, as the team still needed time to analyze information.
U.S. Backs Japan to Build ITER
(Agence France-Presse, Tokyo, 10th) - For the first time, United States publicly backed the selection of Japan's Aomori Prefecture rather than the French town of Cadarache as the site for the multi-billion-dollar International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor (ITER) because it thinks Japan offers a superior site.
The ITER project will choose either the French Cadarache or the Japanese village of Rokkasho in Aomori Prefecture, northern Japan.
The project aims to be a test bed for emulating the sun's nuclear fusion, which is praised as the clean, safe, inexhaustible energy source of the future.
However, the project is not expected to generate electricity before 2050.
During a visit to Tokyo, U.S. Secretary of Energy Abraham told a gathering of Japanese business leaders, "I am proud to say today that the United States strongly supports the building of ITER in Japan.
From a technical standpoint of view, you are offering a superior site".
"The location of Rokkasho village is suitable for receiving the large materials needed for ITER.  Your technical and engineering skills are admired by the world.  In addition, the local community clearly welcomes this project and are trying their best to ensure Rokkasho village is selected," Abraham said.
A spokesman of U.S. embassy in Tokyo confirmed it was the first time that Washington publicly supported the construction of ITER in Japan.
An official from Japan's science and technology ministry said, "We are highly encouraged by Abraham's comment.
We will continue to work with other countries so that we can build ITER in Rokkasho village."
NPA Refused to Talk Peace with Arroyo's Government and Launched a New Wave of Attacks
(Agence France-Presse, Manila, 10th) - Philippines military said eight people have been killed as communist insurgents launched a new wave of attacks, including an attempted raid on a power plant and the burning of a telecommunications tower.
The attacks came as the spokesman of the communist New People's Army (NPA) declared that they would no longer pursue peace talks with the government of President Arroyo but would rather wait for her successor.
"We have no more hope in engaging in peace talks with the government of Arroyo even if she says they are ready to talk," said NPA spokesman Rosal in a television interview.
The Philippines government was planning to hold preliminary talks with NPA later this month towards resuming formal peace negotiations.
Rosal said NPA would like rival presidential candidates running against Arroyo in the May presidential election to make their proposals of how to re-start the peace talks if they are elected.
Rosal said NPA would also demand that they be removed from U.S. and European lists of terrorist groups as a precondition to resume negotiations.
Three soldiers and four NPA guerrillas were killed and seven soldiers wounded after 50 guerrillas attacked a government detachment responsible for defending a power plant in Calaca town.
Iraqi Police and British Soldiers Killed 6 Civilians in a Protest by Unemployed Workers
(Agence France-Presse, Baghdad, 10th) - British soldiers and Iraqi police have shot and killed 6 civilians in a protest at southern Iraq today.
Meanwhile, the Pentagon said Hussein is to be treated as a prisoner of war and he may stand trial within 6 months.
In Baghdad, three loud explosions were heard within an hour but U.S. military said they have not received any relevant information as yet.
Recently, Baghdad suffered from a series of car bomb attacks.  The latest one was on December 31 last year, in which a busy restaurant was blown up causing 8 dead and 24 wounded.
Meanwhile, U.S. military was also launching a major offensive, called "Operation Iron Grip", and commenced shelling on guerilla bases in suburban Baghdad.  U.S. fire can be heard in many parts of the capital from time to time.
In another development, the U.S.-led coalition said today the crash of a U.S. "Black Hawk" helicopter near Falluja last week might be caused by anti-America guerilla attacks.
Nine died in the incident.
According to the coalition, U.S. soldiers have shot and killed two Iraqi policemen by mistake in the highly tensed city of Kirkuk.
Meanwhile, several hundreds of unemployed workers started a protest in the southern city of Amarah.  Finally, Iraq police and British troops opened fire to disperse the crowd and caused 6 dead and 8 wounded.
China Sending Another Delegation to U.S. on a US$2 Billion Purchasing Mission
(Agence France-Presse, Beijing, 12th) - China's state media reported that a Chinese purchasing group is heading for U.S. to sign contracts for the purchase of more than US$2 billion of high tech equipment.
The Beijing Morning Post, citing the words of a Ministry of Information Industry official, said the deals with Motorola, Intel Corp and Cisco Systems Inc etc. would be signed in the United States tomorrow.
The majority of the Chinese companies in the delegation are large telecom firms or computer makers in China, including China Telecom and Legend Group etc.
This is the third Chinese delegation to go on a purchasing mission to the U.S. since last November.
China is trying to reduce its ballooning trade surplus with U.S. and the aforesaid delegation is only part of its efforts.
The Beijing Morning Post said a U.S. Department of Commerce official welcomed the move because it was helpful to reduce U.S. trade deficit with China.
According to figures published by United States, the country had a US$103 billion trade deficit with China in the year before last, which is expected to have soared to US$130 billion in 2003.
Syria Says Israeli President's Invitation to Syrian President Has No Sincerity
(Agence France-Presse, Damascus, 12th) - Israeli President Katsav today invited Syrian President Assad to visit Jerusalem for peace talks.  However, Syrian officials dismissed the offer as "no sincerity" and accused Israeli leaders of trying to sidestep the land-for-peace basis of the Middle East peace process.
"I invite President Assad to come to Jerusalem to seriously negotiate with Israeli leaders the conditions of a peace accord," Katsav said on an Israeli public radio earlier in the day.
"President Assad will be welcomed, but there should be no preconditions," Katsav said.
In an interview by CNN, Syrian Expatriates Minister Shaaban said Israel must declare its willingness to resume negotiations from where they broke off four years ago.
Shaaban said Katsav's invitation is not a "serious response" to Assad's call last month for a revival of contacts with Israel.  He also accused Katsav of seeking a "photo opportunity" with the media.
Syria state-owned news agency SANA quoted the words of an unnamed senior official, who charged Israeli President as trying to evade the land-for-peace basis of the Middle East peace process.
"It is not a question of a visit or who is taking the initiative.  The latest statements by Israel are clearly aimed to avoid the peace process," the official said.
"Part of the solutions and measures could not possibly bring peace to the Middle East area," the official added.
In the previous negotiations with Assad's deceased father, the then Israeli premier Barak agreed to an almost total withdrawal from the Golan Heights, save for a narrow strip of land on the eastern bank of the Sea of Galilee.
However, Damascus rejected the proposal and demanded Israel to return all of the Golan Heights, which Israel occupied in the 1967 war and annexed in 1981.
Growing Friction in the Command Chain of Liberia's Largest Rebel Group
(Agence France-Presse, Monrovia, 12th) - Tension over control of Liberia's largest rebel group, Liberians United for Reconciliation and Democracy (LURD), deepened after the ouster of the chairman, Conneh, and a top rebel leader insisted Conneh was still in charge.
The uprising by LURD in 1999 against former president Taylor's regime had sparked a four-year civil war and LURD finally controlled some four-fifths of the country.
Taylor accepted exile in Nigeria in mid-August last year to pave the way for peace in this West African country and the former government, the rebels, and the political opposition formed a transitional government.
However, a group calling itself LURD's "military high command" said a few days ago that they had replaced Conneh with his estranged wife Aisha Keita Conneh, after accusing him of trading LURD's posts in the transitional government for money.
LURD founder Dweh, current speaker of the transitional legislature, insisted that only LURD's national executive council could sack the leader of the organization.
"I founded LURD in Nigeria and I can assure the Liberian people that there is no split in LURD and nothing can derail the peace process," Dweh told the media on the evening before yesterday.
Dweh blamed the split within LURD on behind-the-scenes manipulations by Bryant, leader of the transitional government, and other senior LURD leaders in the transitional government.
Bryant, a businessman, was appointed in October last year to lead the war-battered state to elections in 2005.
Dweh accused Liberia's justice, transport and labor ministers, under the support of Bryant, conspired with Aisha Conneh and promised her the chairmanship of LURD once Conneh was ousted.
He warned that should Bryant continue to violate the peace accord, the warring factions would have to go back to the drawing board in Accra and consider the possibility to replace Bryant.
Former American Boxer Accused a Promotion Company of Bribing Him to Take a Dive
(Agence France-Presse, New York, 12th) - According to a report in New York Daily News, Rose, a former American boxer, said he was offered US$5,000 to lose a fight by officials of Top Rank, a company promoting professional boxing in U.S.
Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) is investigating Top Rank, which is run by Arum.
The 34-year-old Rose said two Top Rank representatives visited him at his home a few weeks prior to his December 1995 fight with fellow American Eric Esch, nicknamed the "Butterbean".
"It was just after noon and I was resting at Home when someone knocked on my door.  I looked out through the peephole and there were two white guys from Top Rank who said they wanted to talk to me about the Butterbean fight," Ross told the newspaper.
"They said, 'We have some money for you, a substantial amount of money.' They hoped I would take a dive in the match. They didn't want me to beat Butterbean."
Rose has spoken to investigators about the 1995 incident as part of a 20-month probe of corruption in American boxing circles.
Rose refused the bribery and knocked the previously unbeaten Eric out in the second round of a fight held at the Madison Square Garden.
New York Daily News rushed to Eric's Alabama residence and asked him whether he believed the words of Ross.  However, Eric defended Top Rank and said, "Rose was not of that caliber.  Why would you ask a boxer with a 1-6 record to take a dive?  I don't believe Top Rank would do anything illegal."
FBI officers raided Top Rank headquarters in Las Vegas on the 6th, seizing financial, medical documents and computers.
The report also said FBI was looking into evidence of fight fixing, including the Mosley-Hoya championship fight in September.
U.S. Hopes Asian Countries Will Leave the Mad Cow Fears Behind
(Agence France-Presse, Manila, 14th) - Despite one mad cow case was reported in U.S. last month, U.S. Agriculture Department officials said Asian countries can feel relieved and continue to consume U.S. beef after a short period of time.
U.S. has immediately stepped up safety testing after the discovery of first mad cow case.  Despite such efforts, several Asian countries, including Japan and South Korea etc., had immediately banned or limited the import of U.S. beef.
U.S. officials said yesterday the relevant authorities have enlarged the investigations of the mad cow disease.  The beef produced in the area where the mad cow disease was found, had never been exported.  In addition, the relevant authorities have been very stringent in testing and quarantine work in the past 10 years to prevent the spread of mad cow disease.
The mad cow disease is also called bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) and has been linked to the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease in humans, which causes vacuolation and spongiform changes in the human brain.
"We are very optimistic that these Asian countries will narrow the scope of bans in next month or so," Graham, director of Asian Affairs, U.S. Agriculture Department said.
"We have guaranteed to all Asian countries that our beef are safe for consumption," Graham said.
He said a Japanese delegation is currently in U.S. to study the measures adopted by U.S. to prevent the spread of mad cow disease.
South Korea Stepped Up Quarantine To Contain Bird Flu
(Agence France-Presse, Seoul, 14th) - South Korean officials said the country has stepped up quarantine efforts to contain the spread of bird flu after a new outbreak of the disease was reported in nine days.
South Korea agriculture ministry said a tight quarantine zone has been established around a chicken farm in Yangsan, 390 kilometers southeast of Seoul.
Health officials have detected the bird flu virus in this area on Monday.
It was South Korea's first confirmed outbreak of bird flu in nine days.
In last month, the highly contagious disease between poultry appeared to have been brought under control after hitting 15 areas nationwide and the authorities slaughtered nearly two million chickens and ducks.
"We have culled all chickens in the affected area and are strictly restricting the movement of poultry," Kim Chang-Seob (transliteration), head of animal health division, South Korea ministry of health said.
The new bird flu case prompted government officials to strengthen quarantine efforts in other areas.
Kim Chang-Seob said the bird flu virus could survive in dust for two weeks and for at least 35 days in excrement.
Summit of the Americas: Bush Barely Keeps the Free Trade Zone Plans
(Agence France-Presse, Monterrey, Mexico, 13th) - U.S. President Bush won a grudging support from 33 other leaders in the Summit of Americas today for the plans to launch an ambitious pan-American free trade zone next year.
However, the Summit of the Americas remained divided on how to combat spreading poverty in the western hemisphere and the United States failed to get an anti-corruption clause included in the final announcement.
The free trade zone, which would stretch from Alaska in the north to Argentina in the south, is entitled the world's largest free trade area, with a market of some 800 million people and a gross domestic product of 13-trillion U.S. dollars.
However, Argentine President Kirchner criticized the U.S. in his speech at the closing of the two-day summit.  He said a Free Trade Area could not possibly solve the problems of the Americas.
Brazil, South America's largest economy, and Venezuela, a key U.S. oil supplier, fought to keep free trade off the summit agenda.  It was only after intense debates that leaders agreed in a declaration to finish negotiating the proposed free trade area of Americas by January 2005.
Iran's Political Struggle Intensifies: Reformists Threaten to Resign from Government
(Agence France-Presse, Tehran, 13th) - Iran's reformists raised the stakes today in their bitter struggle with powerful conservatives over candidacy in the parliamentary election.  Some top cabinet officials threatened to resign unless the conservatives backed down on a move to bar reformers from next month's election.
One of Iran's vice-presidents, Satarifar, warned that the entire government may resign if it is unable to block the attempt by the Guardians Council (of Constitution) to disqualify thousands of candidates from the February 20 parliamentary polls.
"If the government considers itself unable to meet its obligations to protect the rights of citizens and organize free election, then staying in office is not an option," Satarifar said.
All of Iran's 27 provincial governors have also threatened to quit and a source close to President Mohammad Khatami said at least 10 ministers had already prepared letters of resignation.
However, a media report claiming the mild-mannered president himself was ready to step down was denied by his aides.
Disgruntled Reformists' Members of Parliament (MPs) continued their sit-in at the Iranian parliament for the third day and said they were prepared to stay put for weeks.
A total of 83 reformists were disqualified from standing for re-election.
Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) said the MPs have already challenged the Guardians Council and urged it to withdraw the rulings.
The 12-member Guardians Council is not an elected supervision authority and has been a bastion of the religious conservative right.
Ms. Ebadi, a Nobel Peace Prize laureate loathed by hardliners, said she would later visit the parliament to lend her support to the sit-in MPs and the protest.
Soaring New Zealand Dollar Has Not Weaken Confidence of Businesses
(Agence France-Presse, Wellington, 15th) - New Zealand Institute of Economic Research (NZIER) said in its latest quarterly report that the soaring New Zealand dollar has brought in some negative impacts but businesses are still confident in New Zealand.
The report said only 2 percent of firms were pessimistic about business conditions over the next six months.  As comparison, the numbers were 3 percent and 20 percent for the preceding two quarters.
The report said there was solid growth in the fourth quarter last year according to different indicators surveyed by the report and 31 percent of firms reported an increase in their own activity over the period.
However, leading indicators suggest the economic growth in New Zealand "may fall mildly in next few quarters".
NZIER economist Gardiner said the New Zealand dollar's rapid appreciation over the last three months had widened the gap between exporters' and non-exporters' confidence.
Eleven percent of exporting firms in the manufacturing and building sectors expected conditions to deteriorate over the next six months while 14 percent of non-exporting firms were optimistic.
The New Zealand dollar has appreciated 30 percent in the past two years.
Resignation of CFO and U.S. Unit Chief Triggered Worries about Adecco
(Agence France-Presse, Zurich, 16th) - Adecco, the world's largest temporary employment agency, said its chief financial officer (CFO) and head of U.S. operations, Weber, had resigned after rumors of an accounting problem in the company.  The exit intensifies the fears of another corporate scandal.
In this week, Weber had just downplayed the significance of the postponement of publishing financial results, which was originally scheduled for February 4.  However, the announcement was delayed when "material weaknesses in internal controls" in Adecco's North American business came to light.¡C
Financial controller Cano will take over Weber's job on an interim basis.
Adecco Staffing chief executive Arrieta has also resigned and will be succeeded by Marcel, chairman of Adecco France, which is the group's largest overseas company in a country.
In addition, former chief executive officer (CEO) Bowmer, who had adopted an advisory role as chairman of the board, will once again take over the helm of the troubled firm, leaving current CEO Caille to "concentrate on managing day-to-day business".
Traders said the unusual changes in top-level personnel once again put Adecco shares under pressure.
By 9:40, Adecco shares had stabilized and slightly rebounded from the massive drop at opening.  However, Adecco was still down 3.6 percent while the Swiss stock market advanced 20.3 points during the same period of time.
Adecco announced on Monday that it will postpone the announcement of financial results for its fiscal year and its shares had since gone into choppy trading.
Japan Targets a Balanced Budget within 10 Years
(Agence France-Presse, Tokyo, 16th) - Japan's finance minister Sadakazu Tanigaki said today he was confident the world's second-largest economy would be able to break away from a "fiscal crisis" and put public finances in order within 10 years.
Sadakazu Tanigaki said the combined deficits at central and regional governments amounted to five percent of Japan's total domestic output, which could be eliminated in 10 years if deficits are reduced by 0.5 percent on average every year.
He told a group of journalists, "Japan's fiscal condition remains in a crisis.
Our conditions are the worst among major industrial nations in terms of both (fiscal) flows and reserves."
Tokyo officially set the target of turning "primary deficits" into a "primary surplus" in the year to March 2014 -- the first time in more than two decades that multi-level public finances will be balanced.
This is the first time the government under Prime Minister Junichiro Koizumi has given a clear target for Japan to regain a "primary surplus".  Under such circumstance, tax revenues will exceed the amount of expenditures excluding debt-servicing costs.
The last time Japan reported such a surplus was in the year to March 1992, which ended a sequence of six years in surplus.
Tokyo Stock Exchange Has Approved Shinsei Bank Listing
(Agence France-Presse, Tokyo, 16th) - The Tokyo Stock Exchange said today it has approved an application by Shinsei Bank to list on the exchange, with trading of shares starting from February 19.
U.S. investment fund Ripplewood Holdings took over and restructured the Shinsei Bank prior to making this initial public offering, in which the Bank will offer 242 million shares to domestic investors and an additional 198 million shares to offshore investors.
The offer price will be decided on February 9.
Shinsei Bank has also set aside 36.3 million shares for a possible over-allotment in case some applications might not be able to complete.
Shinsei bank was formerly the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan, which was put under state control in 1998 after it filed for bankruptcy.  After reorganization, the Bank is now offering retail financial services.
For the year to March 2004, Shinsei Bank group forecast net profit of 65 billion yen (US$613 million), up 22.6 percent over previous year, and a recurring profit of 60 billion yen, up 76.5 percent, on revenue of 175 billion yen, down 13.0 percent.
Shinsei Bank also said it had a total of 132.3 billion yen in non-performing loans as at end of last month, down from 154.2 billion yen three months earlier.
Iran: The Death Toll from the Earthquake in the Historic City of Bam Has Reached 41,000
(Agence France-Presse, Tehran, 16th) - A spokesman for Khamenei, Iran's supreme religious leader, said today the death toll from the earthquake on December 26 last year in the historic city of Bam has reached 41,000 and the final figure could hit 45,000.
Previous estimates had put the death toll at between 30,000 and 35,000.
"At present, the death toll of Bam earthquake has reached 41,000, and there is a possibility that this could increase to 45,000," Mohammadi-Gholpayghani, a director of Khamenei's office, told Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA).
"This is a miserable catastrophe," IRNA quoted his words.
Meanwhile, he pledged that the government would accelerate the reconstruction work.
About 30,000 were injured in the Bam earthquake.
A senior provincial official said the reconstruction of Bam would take two years and the government has already invited companies in Iran and outside Iran to submit tenders for reconstruction works.
More than Ten Thousand Marched in Anti-Nuclear Protests in Paris
(Agence France-Presse, Paris, 17th) - Up to 15,000 anti-nuclear protestors marched in Paris and protested against a new generation of reactors.  Protesters also criticized the police of stirring trouble by allowing a separate rally against a ban on religious headscarves in schools.
The main target of these anti-nuclear protestors is the European Pressurized Water Reactor (EPWR), the first of which is to be built in Finland by a consortium including the French state-owned Areva group and German engineering giant Siemens at a cost of three billion euros (US$3.7 billion).
France, which is one of the most nuclear energy-dependent countries in the world, is expected to approve this type of reactors in the near future.  France needs new reactors to start replacing some of the 58 nuclear plants that produce 80 percent of the country's electricity and are nearing the end of service.
"It is in fact a genuine revival of nuclear energy that is unfolding before us," said Lhomme, a spokesman for the group 'End Nuclear Network' which organized the demonstration.
Lhomme criticized the police for allowing another rally.  "We believe the interior ministry is looking for trouble," he said.
The interior ministry in France oversees police works in cities.
The other rally was held almost at the same time at the same spot in Paris and drew thousands to protest government plans to ban Islamic headscarf and other "conspicuous" religious insignia in schools.
Anti-nuclear protesters, who numbered more than 15,000 according to organizers and under 6,000 according to police, built a pyramid of tin cans in the square denouncing what they called the "radioactive waste scandal left for future generations".
Suicide Bomb Killed 23, Wounded 95 in Baghdad
(Agence France-Presse, Baghdad, 18th) - According to U.S. military and Iraqi hospitals, the death toll rose to 23 and the number of wounded to 95 in a suicide car bombing this morning, which blew up the front gate of the U.S. headquarters in Baghdad.
"We have received three dead and 30 wounded," said Doctor Juma at Karrama hospital.
This latest casualty report has raised the dead toll by another three.
A U.S. military spokesman earlier said there were 18 killed and 28 wounded according to a toll compiled at its own military hospitals.  Among those killed, 16 were Iraqis and two were Americans working for the U.S. defense department.
In addition, an emergency room doctor said another two people were reported dead at Baghdad's Yarmuk hospital.
There was no other fatal report at other local hospitals but Yarmuk, al-Kindi and the Neurological Surgical hospital reported a total of 37 wounded.
The aforesaid U.S. military spokesman identified the wounded in U.S. hospitals as 22 Iraqi civilians, four U.S. civilian contractors and two U.S. soldiers.
It was not clear at this time whether the suicide bomber has been counted in the death toll.
Shrinking Workforce Will Impact Economic Output in European Union and Japan
(Agence France-Presse, Davos, Switzerland, 19th) - According to a study by the World Economic Forum and the consultancy firm Watson Wyatt Worldwide (WWW) published today, European Union's (EU's) share of global economic output may reduce to about half of its current level by 2050 as its workforce shrinks.
In contrast, the abundance of workers in developing countries such as India and China should help boost economic growth.
Managing director of WWW, Sammans, said, "Economic output is determined by the growth in labor force and the productivity rates.
In countries with dramatic labor shortages, the supply of goods and services may not meet demands and standards of living."
The study, entitled "Living happily ever after: the economic implications of aging societies", said medical advances have increased life expectancy and the number of people in retirement compared to the number of working-age population is rising (especially in the developed world), which is going to impact directly the economic output.
"Assuming current demographics and economic trends hold, the EU's share of total global output will shrink from 18 percent today to 10 percent in 2050," according to a statement about the study.
"Japan's share would decline from eight percent to four percent," the statement also warned.
Israeli Ambassador to Sweden Damaged an Artwork and Triggered Diplomatic Dispute
(Agence France-Presse, Stockholm, 18th) - Israeli ambassador to Sweden, Mazel, damaged an artwork that commemorates a Palestinian suicide bomber in Sweden's Museum of National Antiquities and triggered a controversy.  Israeli Prime Minister Sharon stepped in today and turned the incident into a full-scale diplomatic row.
Last Friday, ambassador Mazel visited an art exhibition held at Stockholm's Museum of National Antiquities and saw an exhibit showing the photo of the suicide bomber in Haifa last October.  He vandalized the work and was thrown out by the authority.  The incident triggered diplomatic dispute between Israel and Sweden.
Israel has demanded Sweden to dismantle the installation, but its request has been refused.
The incident was widely reported in the Swedish newspapers.
The exhibition is part of an upcoming international conference on genocide hosted by the Swedish government and Israel is also scheduled to participate.
Video footage at the scene showed Mazel put forth his strength in pulling down one of the spotlights and threw it into the water, causing the installation to short-circuit.  Ambassador Mazel was later ordered to leave by the museum director.
Israeli Prime Minister Sharon backed Mazel's actions today and turned the incident into a full-scale diplomatic row.
The exhibit showed a sailboat, entitled "Snow White", navigating at sea with a sail at bow made of a smiling photo of Hanadi Jaradat.
Hanadi was a Palestinian trainee lawyer living in Israel.  She launched a suicide bomb attack in Haifa last October in revenge for her brother, who was killed in an explosion induced by Israeli.  The attack killed 21 Israelis and triggered a new round of conflict between Israel and Palestine.
"I cannot tolerate this kind of artwork.  It is an insult to the families of the victims.  As an ambassador of Israel, I cannot be indifferent to such an obscene distortion of reality," Mazel said.
Democratic Party: Baghdad Blast is Evidence of a Failure of U.S. Policy in Iraq
(Agence France-Presse, Washington, 18th) - Democratic presidential candidates seeking to replace Bush in the White House have all pointed out today that the latest massive suicide bombing in Baghdad is evidence of a failure of United States policy in Iraq.
This attack, killing at least 25 people and injuring about 30 people, is the most deadly attack since the beginning of the U.S. occupation.
Bush's Democratic opponents criticized Bush's Iraq policy severely.  Some of the opponents said the attack is the latest proof of a failure in Bush's Iraq policy.
"We have a failed policy right now.  I have no idea why the Administration is not willing to change it," Edwards, Senator of North Carolina told CBS television.
"Obviously, the first thing we need to do is to internationalize the security force in Iraq.  Another thing to do is to hand over the transitional government to the United Nations," He said.
In a public appearance with Democratic presidential candidate Dean, former U.S. President Carter said the U.S.-led Iraq war "has proven to be based on erroneous information and misleading statements" while the latest attack is "a sustained demonstration of tragedy".
Dean has put his election focus on opposing the Iraq war.
Iraqi Insurgents Use Advanced Weapons Against U.S. Helicopters
(Agence France-Presse, Washington, 18th) - Senior U.S. army officials said Iraqi rebels are using increasingly sophisticated weapons to attack U.S. helicopters.
Senior Army officials familiar with a classified study told New York Times today that the study found Iraqi guerrillas have used rocket-propelled grenades as well as more advanced heat-seeking surface-to-air missiles to attack U.S. helicopters.
The officials said the study was conducted before the three most recent attacks this month, but those incidents can only reinforce the report's findings.
The study aimed at identifying ways to help pilots evade attacks by Iraqi guerrillas using this kind of weapons but the officials did not elaborate on any new discovery.
Judging from the methodology used in the new wave of attack, it is certainly disturbing because it appears the Iraqi guerrillas have already studied the fighting tactics of U.S. aircrafts carefully.
The research team has found the Iraqi insurgents used an SA-16 shoulder-fired missile in more than one occasion, which is especially worrying.
This type of missile has a sophisticated guidance system that is harder for pilots to thwart.
A senior Army aviator in the Persian Gulf region said, "The enemy enjoys a strategic success each time one of our aircraft is shot down.
It becomes a major media event and the defeat or victory is decided immediately. Therefore, the enemy sees this tactics as very useful."
Since October 25 last year, nine military helicopters have been shot down or have crashed, killing at least 49 U.S. soldiers.
Carter Praised Dean on Eve of Democratic Iowa Caucus
(Agence France-Presse, Plains, Georgia, 18th) - Former U.S. president Carter praised Democratic presidential candidate Dean, a former Vermont governor, for his "courageous and outspoken" opposition to the Iraq war on the eve of the Iowa caucus
"I have been particularly grateful at the courageous and outspoken posture and position that governor Dean has taken from the beginning," Carter told reporters in his hometown, Georgia Plains.
The Nobel Peace Prize laureate said, "In the last year and a half, I have spent a lot of time strongly opposing the completely unnecessary and unjust war in Iraq.
Despite my strong efforts, the war commenced and now has proven to be, not only based on erroneous information and misleading statements, but also a sustained demonstration of tragedy."
Carter praised Dean as a strong "advocate of peace".  His statements fell short of a formal endorsement, but U.S. televisions broadcasted Carter's remarks.
As a left-leaning former governor of a northern state, Dean could be at a disadvantageous position when he faces Clark, a retired general and a centrist from Arkansas.  However, Carter's support could boost Dean's chances in the more conservative, religion-conscious southern states.
Carter said in a recent television interview that he saw Dean as the most likely Democratic candidate to go against Bush.
Democrats Criticized Bush for Creating a New Axis of Evil
(Agence France-Presse, Washington, 21st) - On the evening of 20th, opposition Democrats accused President Bush of leading the United States into an isolation from the world and creating a new "Axis of Evil" with his policies.
After a replay of the president's State of the Union speech, the Democratic leader in the House of Representatives, Pelosi, attacked the human and financial costs of last year's Iraq invasion.
The opposition Democrats is being especially hard hitting against Bush because it is another election year (U.S. presidential election will be held in November this year).
Clark, a leading contender for the Democratic nomination, said Bush had created his own "Axis of Evil".
Two years ago, Bush created the term "axis of evil" in his State of the Union speech to describe some countries that were threatening United States.
"That is an axis of fiscal policies that threaten our future; foreign policies that threaten our security and domestic policies that put families dead," Clark said.
U.S. Urged Iran Again to Allow Free and Fair Election
(Agence France-Presse, Washington, 21st) - Iran's political crisis deepened as Iran's hard-liners and the reformist government continue to struggle over candidates qualification for the parliamentary election.  U.S. has urged Iran again to allow a free and fair election in February.
"We think it is important that Iran's leadership permits free and fair election through an electoral process that meets international standards.  The Iranian government has to be responsive to the needs of the people," State Department deputy spokesman Ereli said.
"The political situation in Iran is evolving and there are a lot of developments every day.  We are watching the situation carefully," he said.
Ereli made the above comments in response to reporters' questions on the resignations of Iran's ministers and vice presidents.
It was reported that some ministers and vice presidents of Khatami's reformist government have resigned as protests against the banning of a large group of reformist candidates from the parliamentary election to be held on the 20th of next month.
A Small Plane Crashed into a Residential Area in Japan, Killing All 3 People Onboard
(Agence France-Presse, Tokyo, 22nd) - A small plane has crashed into a residential area in Yamanashi Prefecture, central Japan, killing all three people on board but "miraculously" missing nearby houses, a kindergarten and a hospital.
An emergency official at the Yamanashi prefectural government, Yamamoto, said the single-engine Cessna 172p, piloted by a young man of 32 years old, crashed into a small parking lot.
One of the passengers, who died in the crash, was a photographer.  He was taking aerial pictures of children lining up to form letters outside a local kindergarten.
The kindergarten is only 100 meters from the crash site.
Yamamoto said, "The small plane crashed right next to houses and a hospital.  All three people on board were killed.
It was a miracle that the plane did not crash into houses or the hospital.
There was strong wind and fuel was leaking.  The plane could have crashed on homes or the hospital.
That would cause a major fire."
An aviation official at the Transport Ministry said the plane took off from Chofu airport in western Tokyo this morning and was scheduled to return there two hours later.
The cause of the accident was not immediately clear.
NASA Has Lost Contact with the Mars Probe, the Spirit
(Agence France-Presse, Washington, 22nd) - The officials of United States National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) said today NASA has lost contact with the landed "Spirit" because of a serious breakdown in the rover vehicle.
"We have discovered a serious anomaly on the rover vehicle," said Theisinger, officer-in-charge of the Mars exploration rover mission.
NASA said yesterday that thunder and lightning storms over Australia had prevented scientists from sending daily instructions to the Spirit.
However, experts now think a more serious problem has caused the breakdown in communication.
Spirit arrived Mars on January 3 and started searching for signs of life on the red planet last week.
Spirit's twin rover, the "Opportunity", is scheduled to land at nighttime between January 24 and January 25.
The 820 million dollar exploration mission expects the two solar powered rovers to keep working for about three months.
U.S. Optimistic on New Talks with North Korea after Discussions with Japan and South Korea
(Agence France-Presse, Washington, 22nd) - United States said today it was "very optimistic" that the multi-nation talks, aimed at resolving the North Korea nuclear deadlock, would be resumed soon.  However, U.S. also said the efforts to invite Pyongyang back to the negotiation table had only edged forward.
"We believe it is very likely to have another round of six-party talks before very long.  However, we still do not have a definite date," U.S. top diploma in charge of Asia Pacific Affairs, Kelly said.
Kelly has held talks with senior officials of Japan and South Korea.  They discussed the latest development in the North Korea nuclear problem.  Kelly said the possibility of a second round of talks is still very high.  He was also confident that North Korea would eventually be convinced to scrap its nuclear program.
"We believe it is very likely that the six-party talks can continue," Kelly told reporters.
However, he said any agreement should cover all issues including Pyongyang's guaranty to subject itself to inspection, scraping the enriched uranium program completely, reprocessing of plutonium and treatment of existing nuclear weapons.
North Korea has shown the U.S. non-official delegation the plutonium described by Americans but denied they have any plan for enriched uranium.  North Korea also refuted the U.S. claim that Pyongyang admitted the existence of an enriched uranium plan during the 2002 talks.
WHO Confirmed the 6th Fatal Case of Bird Flu in Vietnam
(Agence France-Presse, Hanoi, 24th) - World Health Organization (WHO) today confirmed the sixth fatal case of bird flu in Vietnam: a 13-year-old boy in Ho Chi Minh City has died after contracting the bird flu virus.
This is the first death case due to bird flu in Southern Vietnam.
A Vietnam health official said earlier that the sixth bird flu sufferer has died taking the death toll from the disease in Vietnam to six people.  Obviously, the public is increasingly worried about the spread of the virus to human.
The boy was tested positive for the bird flu virus, H5N1, earlier and hence, became a confirmed death of this disease.
Nguyen The Dung (transliteration), director of Ho Chi Minh City health department told AFP that the boy has passed away at the city's Paediatric Hospital No. 2 on January 22.
The boy was admitted hospital for respiratory ailments on the 19th.
WHO said they are monitoring the situation closely with Vietnam health authorities.
Another Vietnam health official said two sisters also died at a Hanoi hospital on the 22nd because of respiratory illnesses.  Health authorities suspect the two might also be victims of the bird flu.
Bird Flu Infected Millions of Chickens in Indonesia
(Agence France-Presse, Jakarta, 25th) - Indonesia Agriculture Department said today millions of chickens died of bird flu but the disease has not infected any human this far.
Sudarjat, officer in charge at agriculture ministry's animal husbandry department said the public need not panic because the potentially deadly disease has not infected anyone in Indonesia.
There are 7 countries in Asia currently affected by bird flu and 6 people died in Vietnam.
Indonesian officials said earlier the type of avian influenza, which infected the majority of poultry in Java and Bali islands last November, was the Newcastle disease.
This morning, agriculture ministry spokesman Priyono said there was still no sign of a bird flu crisis in Indonesia.
In the evening, he told AFP that it was still not clear whether the outbreak of avian flu was caused by the H5N1 virus.
The H5N1 virus has caused most of the deadly cases in Vietnams.
The spokesman said 4.7 million birds have died since November by a combination of Newcastle disease and Type A avian influenza.
About 60 percent of the birds died from Newcastle disease.
He said the government has not ordered any culling of poultry.
The state-owned Antara news agency quoted the words of Sudarjat and reported that authorities are performing tests using serums from Britain and Australia to determine the strain of the virus involved.  However, the results would only be known on Wednesday or Thursday.  The government would then report to the relevant international organizations.
Traffic in Chaos As Snow blanketed Western and Northern Europe
(Agence France-Presse, Paris, 29th) - Snowfall blanketed about half of northern and western Europe triggering traffic and rail chaos as well as cancellation of hundreds of flights in Britain, Germany and Denmark.
In London, Heathrow airport spokesman said accumulation of snow led to cancellation of more than 200 flights last night and a further 80 flights had been dropped this morning.
Accumulated snow had also affected the two other airports close to London, Gatwick and Stansted, with a total of 18 flights cancelled due to the weather.
In Germany, the winter weather led to cancellation of over 60 flights heading for Frankfurt international airport, the country's largest.
Transport Authorities said the remaining several dozens of flights for Frankfurt experienced delays and that the wintry weather was likely to affect air traffic for the rest of the day.
In France, road traffic restrictions went into force in Paris after snowfall last night, but similar measures in other parts of the country were lifted early this morning.
Services at the main Paris airports were reported to be near normal.  Yesterday, Charles de Gaulle Airport reported delays due to a combination of snow and fog.
Nevertheless, the Paris airports authority advised air travelers to check whether their flights were delayed before leaving home.
With the exception of the Mediterranean coast, most of France was blanketed in snow.
The Chinese New Year has been one of the traditional festivals highly valued by the Chinese people and by now, it is only slightly more than 2 weeks away.
In these bustling and joyful days, we are accustomed to gather together with relatives and best friends and exchange gifts to express our wishes.
In accordance with the spirit of "Linking People; Delivering Business", Hong Kong Post starts to provide "Hong Kong / Mainland Gift Fulfillment Service" in collaboration with China Post, which can help Hong Kong citizens to send their wishes and blessings to friends and relatives in Hong Kong or mainland China during the spring festival period.
For a long time, Hong Kong Post is devoted to cooperate with other postal institutions to provide international fulfillment services.
Since December 2002, Hong Kong Post has cooperated with Australia Post to launch a fulfillment service for western wines, which provides premium products to Hong Kong citizens.
This time, we are in collaboration with China Post, elevating the existing close cooperation in postal services, postal money order, and courier etc. to the cross border fulfillment service.  Directed at the increasing market demand by Hong Kong citizens to send gifts to relatives, friends and clients in mainland, we have launched this "Hong Kong / Mainland Gift Fulfillment Service".
The first batch of gifts includes several nicely packed gift sets for the Chinese New Year.  The gift sets include selections of candies and nuts, tealeaves, dried seafood etc. and have a wide range of prices to suit your needs.
They are very elegant gifts; no matter you are sending them to relatives, friends or business partners.
As we can all see, the Consumer Council has made many contributions to protect the rights of consumers over the past 30 years.
If we want to evaluate the achievements of the Consumer Council, the best measure would be a check on any real improvement in consumer rights.
I totally agree with what Chairman Chan has just said -- after 30 years, the consumers not only fully understand their rights now but all walks of life in our community have attached importance to consumer rights.  This is clearly the fruitful result of efforts by Consumer Council and the government.
The Consumer Council conducts regular testing on products and performs market research on products or services.  It also studies the operations of various trades and professions.  The Council publishes fair and objective market information through its monthly magazine, the "Choice".
The public has a lot of faith in the "Choice" monthly magazine and the Council is now working on a web version.  This will enhance the magazine's function and help consumer to acquire more up-to-date market information.
